This book is an introduction to the theory of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

multiverse
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in inflationary cosmology and to the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

measure problem.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is likely, given the present cosmological knowledge, that the universe
 may continue expanding forever and that local conditions in the universe
 are at least to some extent randomly produced.
 As a result, different and causally independent regions of the universe
 — that is to say, regions inaccessibly far removed from each other in space
 and time — may, by chance, acquire the hot homogeneous state (the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hot Big Bang
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) that is known to be the origin of our observed universe.
 It follows that, given unlimited time, the universe will generate an 
\emph on
infinite
\emph default
 number of regions similar to ours, where galaxies and stars may give rise
 to intelligent life capable of scientific observation.
 Each region where local conditions are approximately homogeneous is called
 a pocket universe
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
pocket universe
\end_layout

\end_inset

, while the totality of (infinitely many) pocket universes is called a multivers
e
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
multiverse
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In almost all scenarios of multiverse cosmology (the most recent such scenario
 being the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

landscape
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of string theory vacua) it is virtually certain that the different pocket
 universes will have different physical properties, such as the observed
 values of physical constants, including the masses of elementary particles,
 the fine structure constant, and the effective value of the cosmological
 constant.
 Since our present location in the universe is (presumably) in no way special,
 it follows that the presently observed values of physical constants are
 randomly generated and cannot be predicted on the basis of a fundamental
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

theory of everything
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
theory of everything
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 In other words, the local values of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

constants of nature
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in each pocket universe are 
\emph on
environmental
\emph default
 
\emph on
givens
\emph default
 rather than manifestations of global underlying physical properties.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A natural approach in this situation is to try predicting the probability
 distribution for the local values of physical constants observed in a randomly
 chosen pocket universe.
 This approach has been initiated in the late 1980s, and quite soon a difficulty
 (now known as the measure problem) presented itself.
 The root of the measure problem
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
measure problem
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the fact that it is impossible to compute statistical averages directly
 on the ensemble of infinitely many pocket universes.
 The notion of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

randomly chosen
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 pocket universe is mathematically ill-defined.
 One needs to introduce a cutoff on the infinite set of pocket universes;
 however, the results depend sensitively on the cutoff procedure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The measure problem has resisted solution for more than two decades since
 its original formulation in the early 1990s, which was in the context of
 cosmological inflation driven by scalar fields.
 At present, the renewed interest in the measure problem is due to the discovery
 of inflationary models in the string-theoretic landscape, which allows
 a very large number of metastable vacua with different physical laws.
 The need to extract predictions from these models has stimulated significant
 research activity in this field, resulting in the appearance of several
 competing measure proposals and a deeper understanding of the issues involved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This book gives an overview of the presently known approaches to the measure
 problem and proceeds to describe a novel measure proposal, which was developed
 in a series of recent publications.
 Currently the measure problem in multiverse cosmology is an active area
 of research, and more progress may be achieved in the near future.
 Rather than trying to anticipate the forthcoming results, I wish to concentrate
 on the exposition of concepts and mathematical methods that will probably
 remain useful for future research in this area.
 I give merely a brief expository presentation of inflationary cosmology,
 referring the reader to numerous available textbooks for the needed background
 material.
 To recover the necessary background, the reader is only obliged to follow
 an introductory course in inflationary cosmology and cosmological perturbations.
 Similarly, I include only a necessary minimum of facts regarding the landscape
 of string theory; no knowledge of string theory is assumed or needed in
 this book.
 On the other hand, I show some derivations and illuminate details not ordinaril
y given in the literature on eternal inflation.
 Terminology defined in this text is shown in 
\series bold
boldface
\series default
; I reserve 
\emph on
italics
\emph default
 for emphasis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first papers on eternal inflation were published by Andrei Linde, Alexey
 Starobinsky, and Alexander Vilenkin between 1982 and 1986.
 I will attempt to give due credit by referencing substantially all contributors
 to the field.
 A recent book 
