Introduction 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cosmology is the branch of physics concerned with description of the universe
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

at large
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as manifested by large-scale astronomical observations.
 Since the discovery of the expansion of the universe by Hubble and the
 development of the general relativistic model of non-stationary homogeneous
 spacetime by Friedmann and others, the accepted point of view has been
 that the universe is expanding, and that in the distant past the state
 of the universe was extremely different from its present state.
 How the universe began (if it had a beginning) and how it evolved to its
 present condition are among the main questions modern cosmology aims to
 answer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although the goal of describing the entire universe might seem to require
 a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

theory of everything
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
theory of everything
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which may or may not be ever constructed but in any case is not presently
 available, it turns out that many important cosmological observations could
 be explained in the framework of currently available physical theories,
 in particular the known high-energy physics and classical gravity.
 Gamow and others introduced a model of the universe expanding from an extremely
 hot and dense state (the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hot Big Bang
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 In what concerns the evolution of the universe after the Big Bang, this
 scenario is in such good agreement with observations that it is now considered
 to be the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

standard cosmology.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 However, the standard cosmology leaves several important questions unanswered.
 For instance, in the Big Bang scenario one 
\emph on
assumes
\emph default
 rather than derives the initial state of the universe — a state characterized
 for instance by high temperature, homogeneity, and isotropy over extremely
 large length scales — and the origins of this highly fine-tuned initial
 state still need to be adequately explained.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is why one of the central problems of cosmology today is to describe
 the era 
\emph on
before
\emph default
 the onset of the hot Big Bang scenario.
 Because of the present lack of detailed knowledge of high-energy physics
 and quantum gravity, and due to insufficient precision and scope of available
 astrophysical observations, numerous cosmological models of the very early
 universe compete on more or less equal footing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The currently popular and observationally well-supported models of the very
 early universe are 
\emph on
inflationary
\emph default
 models.
 The scenario of inflation assumes an epoch of an extremely fast expansion
 (
\series bold
inflation
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
inflation
\end_layout

\end_inset

) of the universe, during which the universe becomes very cold and homogeneous
 over large scales.
 This epoch is followed by 
\series bold
reheating
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
reheating
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to a hot thermal state, with the temperature being approximately homogeneous
 in space.
 The resulting hot state becomes the starting point of the standard 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hot Big Bang
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 scenario.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inflationary models have been extensively studied during the last three
 decades.
 It was found early on that in most inflationary models driven by scalar
 fields the process of inflation is strongly affected by quantum fluctuations,
 which may randomly postpone or advance the onset of reheating.
 One talks of a 
\series bold
random-walk
\series default
 
\series bold
inflation
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
random-walk inflation
\end_layout

\end_inset

 in order to describe the evolution of the scalar fields.
 In regions where reheating has been delayed, the exponential expansion
 continues and produces more inflating regions.
 As a result, the universe viewed at extremely large distance scales presents
 a mosaic of domains with dramatically different physical properties: Some
 regions have already thermalized and developed matter structures such as
 stars and galaxies, while other regions still undergo an inflationary expansion
 and are cold and empty.
 Thus, a radical departure from homogeneity can be expected at extremely
 large distances.
 Generically, at 
\emph on
arbitrarily
\emph default
 
\emph on
late
\emph default
 times there will still exist large domains that continue inflating.
 This phenomenon was called eternal inflation
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
eternal inflation
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
More precisely one can refer to 
\emph on
future
\emph default
-eternal inflation if the origin of inflation is also being discussed.
 In this book I will use the term 
\series bold
eternal inflation
\series default
 only in the strict sense that inflating domains can be found at an arbitrarily
 late time to the future.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In some models, the various thermalized regions may also differ from each
 other in observable cosmological parameters or even in values of the coupling
 constants observed in low-energy physics.
 There are two problems with such models: First, a model that allows a wide
 range of parameters to be observed in various regions of the universe has
 little predictive power, since we cannot determine which region we happen
 to inhabit.
 Second, the existence of a (typically infinite) multitude of regions of
 space that are too far from us to be ever observable and/or the assumption
 of the 
\shape italic
a priori
\shape default
 unobservable many-universe ensemble make it impossible to test these theories
 directly by experimental observations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A similar situation is found in the recently discovered 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

landscape of string theory.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 It was realized already in the late 1980s
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lerche:1986cx"
literal "true"

\end_inset

