\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Garcia-Bellido:1994ci,Vilenkin:1994ua,Vilenkin:1995yd"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 One hopes that this procedure not only provides results that are in principle
 testable by observation, but also indirectly confirms the existence of
 the otherwise unobservable regions of space.
 This was the program outlined in those early works on eternal inflation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, one runs into an immediate difficulty when one tries to extract
 statistical predictions for cosmological observables in this setting.
 The difficulty is due to an infinite volume of regions where an observer
 may be located.
 Indeed, an eternally inflating universe contains an infinite, inhomogeneous,
 and topologically complicated spacelike hypersurface (the reheating surface)
 near which observers may be expected to appear with a constant density
 per unit 3-volume.
 Hence, the total number of observers in the universe is infinite.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the landscape scenarios, one encounters a kind of infinity that is in
 some sense even more ill-behaved than in the random-walk inflationary scenarios.
 Not only each pocket universe may contain infinitely many observers, but
 also the number of different pocket universes in the entire spacetime is
 infinite.
 Pocket universes of different types are not statistically equivalent to
 each other because they have different rates of nucleation of other pocket
 universes as well as different interior physics.
 There seems to be no natural ordering on the set of all pocket universes
 throughout the spacetime, since most of the pocket universes are spacelike
 separated.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In both these contexts — random-walk models and the landscape models — one
 can view eternal inflation as a stochastic process that generates a topological
ly complicated and noncompact locus of points where observers may appear.
 A 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

random location
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of an observer within that locus is a mathematically undefined concept,
 similarly to the concept of an integer number 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

uniformly chosen
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 among all the integers, or a real number 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

uniformly chosen
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 among all the reals.
 This is the root cause of the technical and conceptual difficulties known
 collectively as the 
\series bold
measure problem
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
measure problem
\end_layout

\end_inset

 in multiverse cosmology.
 Nevertheless, one may try to formulate a 
\emph on
prescription
\emph default
 for calculating observer-weighted probabilities of events.
 Such a prescription, also called a 
\series bold
measure
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
measure
\end_layout

\end_inset

, should in some sense correspond to the intuitive notion of probability
 of observation at a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

random
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 location in the spacetime.
 These issues are discussed in Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Predictions-and-cutoffs"

\end_inset

.
