\begin_layout Standard
We begin with the story of inflation.
 While the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hot Big Bang
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 cosmological scenario has been widely accepted after the detection of the
 cosmic microwave background (CMB) radiation and explanation of the nucleosynthe
sis, several poorly explained and contradictory facts remained.
 The main problems of the standard hot cosmology were the horizon problem
 and the flatness problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The horizon problem stems from the fact that the observed CMB is highly
 isotropic, with relative temperature variation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim10^{-5}$
\end_inset

 (see, 
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default
, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Smoot:1992td"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 The CMB radiation is coming from the last scattering surface, which at
 the time of decoupling consisted of a large number of causally disconnected
 horizon-size regions, each region spanning about 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 of today's sky.
 However, observations of the high degree of homogeneity of the CMB temperature
 suggest that all these regions had had a nearly equal temperature at the
 time of last scattering.
 This absence of large-scale fluctuations is difficult to explain unless
 we assume rather unnatural-looking, extremely uniform initial conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The flatness problem is also in a sense a problem of initial conditions:
 the universe must initially have been unnaturally close to flat.
 The density parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 evolves in such a way that any deviation from 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=1$
\end_inset

 grows with time, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|\Omega-1\right|\propto t^{2-\frac{4}{3\left(1+w\right)}}\propto a^{1+3w},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 which can also be expressed through the temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|\Omega-1\right|\propto T^{-\left(1+3w\right)}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Since the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 at present is of order 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, it must have been extremely close to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 at early times.
 For instance, at Planck temperatures 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\text{P}}\sim10^{19}$
\end_inset

 GeV with 
\begin_inset Formula $w=1/3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\text{now}}=3$
\end_inset

 K one obtains the estimate 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|\Omega_{P}-1\right|=\left|\Omega_{\text{now}}-1\right|\left(\frac{T_{\text{now}}}{T_{\text{P}}}\right)^{-2}\lesssim10^{-60}.\label{OmegaConstr}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 If one assumes a more natural initial condition for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, for example, that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\sim1$
\end_inset

 at Planck time, then one finds that the universe would have either collapsed
 within a few Planck times if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega>1$
\end_inset

, or cooled down to the present temperature of 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 K within 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-11}$
\end_inset

 sec if 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega<1$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DickePeebles:1979"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 It is hard to explain this exceptional fine-tuning of the initial matter
 density.
