\begin_layout Section
The inflationary paradigm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For simplicity, we consider a homogeneous cosmology with flat spatial sections
 and a spacetime metric of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g_{\mu\nu}dx^{\mu}dx^{\nu}=dt^{2}-a^{2}(t)\left(dx^{2}+dy^{2}+dz^{2}\right)\equiv dt^{2}-a^{2}(t)d\mathbf{x}^{2},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t)$
\end_inset

 is called the scale factor.
 Cosmological inflation is a regime of fast expansion of the universe with
 the expansion rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{a}/a=H\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 given by a slowly changing function of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 (so that the change of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 during one Hubble time is negligible, 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{H}H^{-1}\ll H$
\end_inset

).
 Then the scale factor is approximately exponentially growing with time,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a\left(t\right)\sim\exp\left(\int H\left(t\right)dt\right).\label{ExpInfl}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The spacetime with this scale factor is similar to the de Sitter space
 of constant curvature 
\begin_inset Formula $R\approx12H^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 More precisely, 
\series bold
inflation
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
inflation
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is defined as a period of accelerated expansion, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{a}(t)>0$
\end_inset

.
 This condition allows the Hubble rate 
\begin_inset Formula $H(t)$
\end_inset

 to decrease as long as it does not decrease too quickly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The earliest working proposal of an inflationary model can be found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Starobinsky:1979ty,Starobinsky:1980te"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 In that scenario, a period of inflation was driven by a modification of
 gravity where the Einstein-Hilbert action term, 
\begin_inset Formula $R\sqrt{-g}$
\end_inset

, was replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(R+\alpha R^{2}\right)\sqrt{-g}$
\end_inset

 with a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 However, this pioneering work
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As well as several others, such as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BroutEnglertGunzig:1979b,Kazanas:1980,Sato:1981"
literal "true"

\end_inset

