\begin_inset Formula $\gamma<1$
\end_inset

, inflation draws the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 nearer to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 If the total expansion factor 
\begin_inset Formula $a/a_{0}$
\end_inset

 (the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

amount of inflation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) is large enough, 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

at least 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp\left(60\right)$
\end_inset

, which is called 60 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
foldings
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-foldings
\end_layout

\end_inset

, then for a generic initial condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{0}\sim1$
\end_inset

 the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 at the end of inflation will be as close to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

