\begin_layout Standard
Eternal inflation, or the property that inflation never ends in the whole
 spacetime, is a generic property of inflationary models.
 The mechanism of eternal inflation is based on the effect of quantum fluctuatio
ns on the average values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and on the metric in horizon-size volumes.
 This is essentially the same physical effect as that which is assumed to
 be responsible for generating the observed, 
\emph on
classical
\emph default
 cosmological perturbations out of 
\emph on
quantum
\emph default
 fluctuations in the vacuum state.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The classical evolution of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 (neglecting quantum fluctuations) is described by Eq.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "IntroSlowRoll"

\end_inset

).
 However, in the de Sitter space the behavior of quantum fluctuations of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 depends crucially on whether their wavelength is above or below the horizon
 size.
 The evolution of the super-horizon scale fluctuations is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

frozen
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and they are measured by observers inside a horizon-sized region as classical
 corrections to the average value of the field in the region.
 With the expansion of space, quantum fluctuations with sub-horizon wavelengths
 are stretched to super-horizon scales and shift the average field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\phi\sim H/\left(2\pi\right)$
\end_inset

 per Hubble time 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the evolution of the average field amounts to a random walk with character
istic step 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\phi$
\end_inset

, imposed on the deterministic change of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

