\begin_layout Standard
The general idea of eternally inflating spacetime was first introduced and
 developed in the context of slow-roll inflation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Linde:1982ur,Vilenkin:1983xq,Starobinsky:1986fx,Linde:1986fd,Goncharov:1987ir"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 A prototypical model contains a minimally coupled, canonical scalar field
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 (the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

inflaton
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) with an effective interaction potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\phi)$
\end_inset

 that is sufficiently flat in some range of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 When the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 has values in this range, the spacetime is approximately de Sitter with
 the Hubble rate 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\dot{a}}{a}=\sqrt{\frac{8\pi}{3M_{\text{P}}^{2}}V(\phi)}\equiv H(\phi).\label{eq:Einstein1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 remains approximately constant on timescales of several Hubble times (
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t\gtrsim H^{-1}$
\end_inset

), while the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 follows the attractor trajectory, which is approximately given by the slow-roll
 trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{sr}}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Quantum fluctuations of the scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 in de Sitter background grow linearly with time
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vilenkin:1982wt,Linde:1982uu,Starobinsky:1982ee"
literal "true"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle\hat{\phi}^{2}(t+\Delta t)\rangle-\langle\hat{\phi}^{2}(t)\rangle=\frac{H^{3}}{4\pi^{2}}\Delta t,\label{eq:delta-phi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

at least for time intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 of order several 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Due to the quasi-exponential expansion of spacetime during inflation, Fourier
 modes of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 are quickly stretched to super-Hubble length scales.
 However, quantum fluctuations with super-Hubble wavelengths cannot maintain
 quantum coherence and become essentially classical
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Linde:1982uu,Starobinsky:1982ee,Vilenkin:1983xp,Brandenberger:1984wt,Guth:1985ya"
literal "true"

\end_inset

; this issue is discussed in more detail in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Physical-justifications"

\end_inset

 below.
 The resulting field evolution 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(t)$
\end_inset

 can be visualized
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bardeen:1983qw,Vilenkin:1983xq,Vilenkin:1983xp"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 as a Brownian motion with a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

random jump
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of typical step size 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\phi\sim H/(2\pi)$
\end_inset

 during a time interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t\sim H^{-1}$
\end_inset

, superimposed onto the deterministic slow-roll trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{sr}}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 A statistical description of this 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

random walk
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

-type evolution 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(t)$
\end_inset

 is reviewed in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Eternal-inflation-from"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can distinguish two possible regimes of evolution depending on whether
 the deterministic change of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 in one Hubble time is smaller or larger than a typical random fluctuation.
 If the deterministic change 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\phi}_{\text{sr}}H^{-1}$
\end_inset

 dominates the fluctuations, the slow roll evolution proceeds essentially
 unmodified.
 In the opposite regime, 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\phi}_{\text{sr}}H^{-1}\ll\delta\phi$
\end_inset

, the random walk dominates the evolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, which means that steps toward larger and smaller values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 are almost equally probable.
 A range of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 where the random walk dominates (called the 
\series bold
fluctuation-dominated range
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
fluctuation-dominated range
\end_layout

\end_inset

) is present in many inflationary models.
 If the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is approximately homogeneous throughout a horizon-sized region (
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
region
\series default
) and has a value in the fluctuation-dominated range, the 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region will expand to form several horizon-sized regions, most of which
 would again contain values of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 within the fluctuation-dominated range.
 One may say that a fluctuation-dominated 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reproduces itself
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Linde:1986fd"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 It is important that the self-reproduction occurs regardless of the values
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 in neighbor 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions because the neighbor regions are beyond the horizon (the well-known
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

no-hair
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 property of de Sitter space
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gibbons:1977mu,Hawking:1981fz,Hawking:1982my"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 We will use interchangeably the terms 
\series bold
self-reproducing regime
\series default
 and 
\series bold
fluctuation-dominated range
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

jumps
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 at points separated in space by many Hubble distances are essentially uncorrela
ted; this is another manifestation of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

no-hair
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 property.
 Thus the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 becomes extremely inhomogeneous on large (super-horizon) scales after many
 Hubble times, even though the field values remain approximately homogeneous
 within each Hubble volume (
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In models of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

new
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 inflation, the fluctuation-dominated range is near the flat top of the
 potential where the deterministic change of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is small.
 In 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

chaotic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 models it is usually a range of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 bounded from below by some value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{fluct}}$
\end_inset

, and from above by the Planck boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{P}}$
\end_inset

, which leads to the existence of the fluctuation-dominated range 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{fluct}}<\phi<\phi_{\text{P}}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{fluct}}<\phi_{\text{P}}$
\end_inset

 and to the absence of the fluctuation-dominated range otherwise.
 For the power-law potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\phi\right)=\lambda\phi^{n}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\ll1$
\end_inset

 (in Planck units), one obtains 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{fluct}}\sim\lambda^{-1/\left(n+2\right)}\ll\phi_{\text{P}}\sim\lambda^{-1/n}$
\end_inset

, so the fluctuation-dominated range is present in such models.
 Rather than consider a specific model of inflation, we will keep the discussion
 general and assume that a fluctuation-dominated range exists.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the fluctuations of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 have ultimately quantum origin, their semi-classical character leads, through
