\begin_layout Standard
The hypothesis of cosmological inflation was invoked to explain several
 outstanding puzzles in observational data
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Guth:1980zm"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 However, some observed quantities (such as the cosmological constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 or elementary particle masses) may be expectation values of slowly-varying
 effective fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a}$
\end_inset

.
 Within the phenomenological approach, we are compelled to consider also
 the fluctuations of the fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a}$
\end_inset

 during inflation, on the same footing as the fluctuations of the inflaton
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, in a generic scenario of eternal inflation, all the fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a}$
\end_inset

 arrive at the reheating surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 with values that can be determined only statistically.
 Observers appearing at different points in space may thus measure different
 values of the cosmological constant, elementary particle masses, spectra
 of primordial density fluctuations, and other cosmological parameters that
 may depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to note that inhomogeneities in observable quantities are
 created on scales far exceeding the Hubble horizon scale.
 Such inhomogeneities are not directly accessible to astrophysical experiments.
 Nevertheless, the study of the global structure of eternally inflating
 spacetime is not merely of academic interest.
 Fundamental questions regarding the cosmological singularities, the beginning
 of the universe and of its ultimate fate, as well as the issue of the cosmologi
cal initial conditions all depend on knowledge of the global structure of
 the spacetime as predicted by the theory, whether or not this global structure
 is directly observable (see 
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Garriga:1999hf,Garriga:2001ch"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 In other words, the fact that some theories predict eternal inflation influence
s our assessment of the viability of these theories.
 In particular, the problem of initial conditions for inflation
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
initial conditions for inflation
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is significantly alleviated when eternal inflation is present.
 For instance, it was noted early on that the presence of eternal self-reproduct
ion in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

chaotic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 inflationary scenario
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Linde:1983gd"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 essentially removes the need for the fine-tuning of the initial conditions
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Linde:1986fc,Linde:1986fd"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 More recently, constraints on initial conditions were studied in the context
 of self-reproduction in models of quintessence
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Martin:2004ba"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-inflation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Helmer:2006tz"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the values of the observable parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a}$
\end_inset

 are random, it is natural to ask for the probability distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a}$
\end_inset

 that would be measured by a randomly chosen observer.
 Understandably, this question has been the main theme of much of the work
 on eternal inflation.
 Obtaining an answer to this question promises to establish a more direct
 contact between scenarios of eternal inflation and experiment.
 For instance, if the probability distribution for the cosmological constant
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 were peaked near the experimentally observed, puzzlingly small value (see
 
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Carroll:2000fy"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for a review of the cosmological constant problem), the smallness of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 would be explained as due to observer selection effects rather than to
 fundamental physics.
 Considerations of this sort necessarily involve some anthropic reasoning;
 however, the relevant assumptions are minimal.
 The basic goal of theoretical cosmology is to select physical theories
 of the early universe that are most compatible with astrophysical observations,
 including the observation of our existence.
 It appears reasonable to assume that the civilization of Planet Earth evolved
 near a randomly chosen star compatible with the development of life, within
 a randomly chosen galaxy where such stars exist.
 Many models of inflation generically include eternal inflation and hence
 predict the formation of infinitely many galaxies where civilizations like
 ours may develop.
 It is then also reasonable to assume that our civilization is typical among
 all the civilizations that evolved in galaxies formed at any time anywhere
 in the universe.
 This assumption is called the 
\series bold
principle of mediocrity
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
principle of mediocrity
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To use the principle of mediocrity for extracting statistical predictions
 from a model of eternal inflation, one proceeds as follows
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vilenkin:1995yd,Vilenkin:1998kr"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 In the example with the fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a}$
\end_inset

 described above, the question is to determine the probability distribution
 for the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a}$
\end_inset

 that a random observer will measure.
 Presumably, the values of the fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a}$
\end_inset

 do not directly influence the emergence of intelligent life on planets,
 although they may affect the efficiency of structure formation or nucleosynthes
is.
 Therefore, we may assume a fixed, 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a}$
\end_inset

-dependent mean number of civilizations 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\text{civ}}(\chi_{a})$
\end_inset

 per galaxy and proceed to ask for the probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{G}(\chi_{a})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a}$
\end_inset

 near a randomly chosen galaxy.
 The observed probability distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a}$
\end_inset

 will then be
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P(\chi_{a})=P_{G}(\chi_{a})\nu_{\text{civ}}(\chi_{a}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 One may use the standard 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hot Big Bang
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 cosmology to determine the average number 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{G}(\chi_{a})$
\end_inset

 of suitable galaxies per unit volume in a region where reheating occurred
 with given values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a}$
\end_inset

; in any case, this task does not appear to pose difficulties of principle.
 Then the computation of 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{G}(\chi_{a})$
\end_inset

 is reduced to determining the volume-weighted probability distribution
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}(\chi_{a})$
\end_inset

 for the fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a}$
\end_inset

 within a randomly chosen 3-volume along the reheating surface.
 The probability distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a}$
\end_inset

 will be expressed as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P(\chi_{a})=\mathcal{V}(\chi_{a})\nu_{G}(\chi_{a})\nu_{\text{civ}}(\chi_{a}).\label{eq:probability}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

However, defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}(\chi_{a})$
\end_inset

 turns out to be far from straightforward since the reheating surface in
 eternal inflation is an infinite 3-surface with a complicated geometry
 and topology.
 The lack of a natural, unambiguous, unbiased measure on the infinite reheating
 surface is known as the measure problem in eternal inflation.
 Existing approaches and measure prescriptions are discussed in Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Predictions-and-cutoffs"

\end_inset

 where two main alternatives (the volume-based and worldline-based measures)
 are presented (Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Predictions-of-observable"

\end_inset

).
 I will give arguments in favor of using the volume-based measure for computing
 the probability distribution of values 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a}$
\end_inset

 measured by a random observer.
 The volume-based measures have been applied to obtain statistical predictions
 for the gravitational constant in Brans-Dicke theories
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Garcia-Bellido:1993wn,Garcia-Bellido:1994vz"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, cosmological constant (dark energy)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Garriga:1998px,Garriga:1999bf,Garriga:1999hu,Garriga:2002tq,Garriga:2003hj,Garriga:2005ee,Clifton:2007bn"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, particle physics parameters
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Tegmark:2003ug,Tegmark:2005dy,Hall:2006ff"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, and the amplitude of primordial density perturbations
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Susperregi:1996hs,Garriga:1999hu,Feldstein:2005bm,Garriga:2005ee"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The worldline-based measure was also used to predict the cosmological constant
 and other observables 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bousso:2006ev,Bousso:2007er,Bousso:2007kq,Bousso:2009ks"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 A detailed exposition of these applications is beyond the scope of this
 introductory book; the reader is referred to the cited literature for further
 information.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The issue of statistical predictions has recently come to the fore in conjunctio
n with the discovery of the string theory landscape.
 According to various estimates, one expects to have between 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{500}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{1500}$
\end_inset

 possible vacuum states of string theory
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lerche:1986cx,Bousso:2000xa,Susskind:2003kw,Kachru:2003aw,Denef:2004ze"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The string vacua differ in the geometry of spacetime compactification and
 have different values of the effective cosmological constant (or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dark energy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 density).
 Transitions between vacua may happen via the well-known Coleman-De Luccia
 tunneling mechanism
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Coleman:1980aw"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Once the dark energy dominates in a given region, the spacetime becomes
 locally de Sitter.
 Then the tunneling process will create infinitely many disconnected 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

daughter
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 bubbles of other vacua.
 Observers like us may appear within any of the habitable bubbles.
 Since the fundamental theory does not specify a single 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

preferred
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 vacuum, it remains to try determining the probability distribution of vacua
 as found by a randomly chosen observer.
 The volume-based and worldline-based measures can be extended to scenarios
 with multiple bubbles, as discussed in more detail below in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Predictions-in-discrete"

\end_inset

.
 Some recent results obtained using these measures are reported in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Schwartz-Perlov:2006hi,Aguirre:2006ak,Linde:2006nw,Bousso:2007kq"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Ultimately, one hopes to choose the correct measure prescription by analyzing
 the general features of measure prescriptions in judiciously chosen toy
 models, and also by computing specific predictions for observable parameters
 and comparing them with observed values.
 Future research will show whether this approach proves to be fruitful.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Physical justifications of the semiclassical picture
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Physical-justifications"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The standard framework of inflationary cosmology asserts that vacuum quantum
 fluctuations with super-horizon wavelengths become classical inhomogeneities
 of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and of the metric.
 The calculations of cosmological density perturbations generated during
 inflation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Mukhanov:1981xt,Mukhanov:1982nu,Hawking:1982cz,Starobinsky:1982ee,Guth:1982ec,Bardeen:1983qw,Kodama:1985bj,Mukhanov:1990me"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 also assume that a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

classicalization
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of quantum fluctuations takes place via the same mechanism.
 This assumption, while not always made explicit, is manifest in the calculation
s because one obtains the statistical average 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \delta\phi^{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 of 
\emph on
classical
\emph default
 fluctuations on super-Hubble scales by computing the 
\emph on
quantum
\emph default
 expectation value 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle 0\right|\hat{\phi}^{2}\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 in a suitable vacuum state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 While this approach is widely accepted in the cosmology literature, a growing
 body of research is devoted to the explicit analysis of the quantum-to-classica
l transition during inflation (see 
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Brandenberger:1984cz"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for an early review of that line of work).
 Since a detailed analysis would be beyond the scope of the present text,
 and since the quantum-to-classical transition in cosmology is still under
 active investigation, I merely outline the main ideas and arguments relevant
 to this issue.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A standard phenomenological explanation of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

classicalization
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the perturbations is as follows.
 For simplicity, we restrict our attention to a slow-roll inflationary scenario
 with one scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 In the slow roll regime, one can approximately regard 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 as a massless scalar field in de Sitter background spacetime
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Goncharov:1987ir"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 In a more fundamental approach, one can take into account the scalar metric
 fluctuations sourced by the fluctuations of the scalar field and again
 obtain an effective description of both fluctuations in terms of a single
 auxiliary scalar field (sometimes called the 
\series bold
Mukhanov-Sasaki
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Mukhanov-Sasaki field
\end_layout

\end_inset

 field
\series default
) propagating in a fixed classical background.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This standard theory of cosmological perturbations can be found 
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

in the technical reviews 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kodama:1985bj,Mukhanov:1990me"
literal "true"

\end_inset

; see also 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Maldacena:2002vr"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for a more modern derivation, and the books 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Mukhanov:2005:PPC,MukhanovWinitzki:2007:IQFG"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for a more pedagogical exposition.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Therefore, it is sufficient to consider a scalar field (here denoted by
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

) in a 
\emph on
fixed
\emph default
 de Sitter-like background.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Due to the exponentially fast expansion of de Sitter spacetime, super-horizon
 Fourier modes of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 are in squeezed quantum states with exponentially large (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim e^{Ht}$
\end_inset

) squeezing parameters
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Polarski:1995jg,Kiefer:1998jk,Kiefer:1998pb,Kiefer:1998qe,Kiefer:1999sj,Kiefer:2006je"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Such highly squeezed states have a macroscopically large uncertainty in
 the field value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and thus quickly decohere due to interactions with gravity and with other
 fields.
 The resulting mixed state is  equivalent to a statistical ensemble with
 a Gaussian distributed value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore one may compute the statistical average 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \delta\phi^{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 as the quantum expectation value 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle 0\right|\hat{\phi}^{2}\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and interpret the fluctuation 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\phi$
\end_inset

 as a classical 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

noise.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another heuristic description of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

classicalization
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Goncharov:1987ir"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 is that the quantum commutators of the creation and annihilation operators
 of the field modes, 
\begin_inset Formula $[\hat{a},\hat{a}^{\dagger}]=1$
\end_inset

, are much smaller than the expectation values 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle a^{\dagger}a\right\rangle \gg1$
\end_inset

 and are thus negligible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The backreaction of fluctuations of the scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 on the metric is treated in the same way.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The backreaction effects of the long-wavelength fluctuations of a scalar
 field during inflation have been investigated extensively (see 
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Abramo:1997hu,Afshordi:2000nr,Abramo:2001db,Abramo:2001dc,Abramo:2001dd,Geshnizjani:2003cn,Geshnizjani:2004tf"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since the phenomenon of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

classicalization
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 applies to the fluctuations of the Mukhanov-Sasaki field, the same phenomenon
 applies to perturbations of the metric effectively described by that field.
 At the same time, the metric perturbations can be viewed, in an appropriate
 local coordinate system, as fluctuations of the local expansion rate 
\begin_inset Formula $H(\phi(\mathbf{x},t))$
\end_inset

 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Starobinsky:1982ee,Goncharov:1987ir,Frolov:2002va"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for further details).
 One thus arrives at the picture of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

locally de Sitter
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 spacetime with the metric
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:locally de Sitter"

\end_inset

), where the Hubble rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{a}/a=H(\phi)$
\end_inset

 fluctuates on super-horizon length scales and locally follows the fluctuating
 value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 via the 
\emph on
classical
\emph default
 Einstein equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Einstein1"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The picture as outlined is certainly phenomenological and does not provide
 a description of the quantum-to-classical transition in the field and metric
 perturbations at the level of field theory or quantum gravity.
 For instance, a fluctuation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 leading to a local 
\emph on
increase
\emph default
 of the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $H(\phi)$
\end_inset

 necessarily violates the null energy condition (
\series bold
NEC
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
null energy condition
\end_layout

\end_inset

)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Borde:1997pp,Winitzki:2001fc,Vachaspati:2003de"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 However, it is clear that the dynamics of a scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 cannot violate the NEC either at classical level or at the level of the
 expectation value of the quantum energy-momentum tensor
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vachaspati:2003de"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The cosmological implications of such NEC-violating fluctuations (see 
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

the scenario of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

island cosmology
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dutta:2005gt,Piao:2005na,Dutta:2005if"
literal "true"

\end_inset

) cannot be understood quantitatively within the framework of the phenomenologic
al picture as outlined here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A more fundamental approach to describing the quantum-to-classical transition
 of perturbations was developed using non-equilibrium quantum field theory
 and the influence functional formalism
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Morikawa:1987ci,Morikawa:1989xz,Hu:1994ep,Calzetta:1995ys"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 In this approach, decoherence of a pure quantum state of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 into a mixed state is entirely due to the self-interaction of the field
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, it is predicted that no decoherence would occur for a free
 field with 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\phi)=\frac{1}{2}m\phi^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This result is dramatically at variance with the accepted paradigm of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

classicalization
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as outlined above.
 Firstly, due to the absence of decoherence as computed in the influence
 functional approach, the model of inflation with 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\phi)=\frac{1}{2}m\phi^{2}$
\end_inset

 would have generated 
\emph on
no
\emph default
 classical perturbations at all.
 This is in contrast with the present consensus where this model is a successful
 match with the observed CMB fluctuations
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Komatsu:2008hk,Dunkley:2008ie,Kinney:2008wy,Xia:2008ex"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Secondly, if the source of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

noise
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is the coupling between different perturbation modes of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, the typical amplitude of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

noise
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 will be second-order in the perturbation.
 This is several orders of magnitude smaller than the amplitude of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

noise
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 found in the standard approach.
 Accordingly, it is claimed
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Matacz:1996gk,Matacz:1996fv"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 that the amplitude of cosmological perturbations generated by inflation
 is several orders of magnitude smaller than the results currently accepted
 as standard, and that the shape of the perturbation spectrum depends on
 the details of the process of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

classicalization
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kubotani:1997xa"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, the results obtained so far via the influence functional techniques
 are in sharp contradiction with the widely accepted phenomenological picture
 of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

classicalization
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as outlined above.
 It is possible that the influence functional techniques were used so far
 to derive a real but subdominant, second-order effect, — an effect of decoheren
ce due to self-interaction of the inflaton field, — while the main effect
 responsible for generating the classical cosmological perturbations is
 due to interaction with gravity, which has not yet been derived in the
 influence functional approach.
 The mismatch is presently not clarified in the literature, which emphasizes
 the need for a better understanding of the nature of the quantum-to-classical
 transition for cosmological perturbations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, let us mention a different line of work which supports the standard
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

classicalization
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 picture.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vilenkin:1983xp,Woodard:2005cw,Tsamis:2005hd,Woodard:2006pw,Miao:2006pn,Prokopec:2006ue"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, calculations of (renormalized) quantum expectation values such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\hat{\phi}^{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\hat{\phi}^{4}\rangle$
\end_inset

, etc., were performed for field operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi}$
\end_inset

 in a 
\emph on
fixed
\emph default
 de Sitter background (
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

ignoring the backreaction on the metric).
 The results were compared with the statistical averages
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int P(\phi,t)\phi^{2}d\phi,\quad\int P(\phi,t)\phi^{4}d\phi,\quad\text{etc.},\label{eq:averages phi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,t)$
\end_inset

 describes the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

random walk
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 in the Fokker–Planck approach (see Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Eternal-inflation-from"

\end_inset

).
 It was shown that the leading late-time asymptotics of the quantum expectation
 values coincide with the corresponding statistical averages
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:averages phi"

\end_inset

).
 Furthermore, an explicit picture of decoherence due to interaction in a
 two-field model was obtained in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Prokopec:2006fc"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, where an explicit expression of the density matrix for perturbation modes
 was computed.
 It was shown that decoherence of a perturbation mode occurs several (of
 order 3) 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-foldings after the mode crosses the Hubble horizon scale.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These results appear to validate the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

random walk
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 approach, albeit in a limited context, namely in the absence of backreaction
 on the metric and/or without a detailed underlying picture of quantum fluctuati
ons of the metric.
 In the rest of this book, we assume the validity of this approach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Stochastic approach to inflation 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Stochastic approach"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
stochastic approach to inflation
\series default
 is a semiclassical, statistical description of the spacetime resulting
 from quantum fluctuations of the inflaton field(s) and their backreaction
 on the metric.
 This approach originated in the early works
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vilenkin:1983xq,Starobinsky:1986fx,Rey:1986zk,Sasaki:1987gy,Nakao:1988yi,Kandrup:1988sc,Nambu:1988je,Nambu:1989uf,Mijic:1990qx,Salopek:1990re,Linde:1993nz,Linde:1993xx"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 In this approach, the spacetime remains everywhere classical 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Also note: Shandera et al.
 and also Creminelli et al.
 have shown that the stochastic approach cannot be used if the speed of
 sound is too small, because then the action for perturbations cannot be
 adequately represented by second-order terms.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 but its geometry is determined by a stochastic process.
 In the next subsections I review the main tools used in the stochastic
 approach for calculations in the context of random-walk type, slow-roll
 inflation.
 Models involving tunneling-type eternal inflation are considered later
 in Chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Bubble-nucleation-models"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Eternal inflation of random walk type
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Eternal-inflation-from"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The salient features of random walk type eternal inflation can be understood
 by considering a simple slow-roll inflationary model with a single scalar
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and a potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\phi)$
\end_inset

.
 The slow-roll evolution equation is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{\phi}=-\frac{1}{3H}\frac{dV}{d\phi}=-\frac{1}{4\pi}\frac{dH}{d\phi}\equiv v(\phi),\label{eq:v def 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $H(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is defined by Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Einstein1"

\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $v(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is a model-dependent function describing the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

velocity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\phi}$
\end_inset

 of the deterministic evolution of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, expressed as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 The slow-roll trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{sr}}(t)$
\end_inset

, which is a solution of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:v def 1"

\end_inset

), is (approximately) an attractor for trajectories starting with a wide
 range of initial conditions, as we described in the previous chapter.
 If a higher precision is desired, we may use the exact attractor curve
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}(t)$
\end_inset

 to determine the function 
\begin_inset Formula $v(\phi)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to the discussion in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Physical-justifications"

\end_inset

, the super-horizon modes of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 are assumed to undergo a rapid quantum-to-classical transition.
 Therefore one regards the spatial average of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 on scales of several 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{-1}$
\end_inset

 as a 
\emph on
classical
\emph default
 field variable.
 The spatial averaging can be described with the help of a suitable window
 function,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \phi(\mathbf{x})\right\rangle \equiv\int W(\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{y})\phi(\mathbf{y})d^{3}\mathbf{y}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It is implied that the window function 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 decays quickly on physical distances 
\begin_inset Formula $a\left|\mathbf{x}\right|$
\end_inset

 of order several 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 From now on, let us denote the volume-averaged field also by 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 (no other field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 will be used).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The influence of quantum fluctuations leads to random 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

jumps
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 superimposed on top of the deterministic evolution of the volume-averaged
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(t,\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

.
 This may be described by a 
\series bold
Langevin equation
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Langevin equation
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of the form
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Starobinsky:1986fx"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{\phi}(t,\mathbf{x})=v(\phi)+N(t,\mathbf{x}),\label{eq:Langevin}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N(t,\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 stands for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

noise
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and is assumed to be a Gaussian random function with known correlator
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Starobinsky:1986fx,Bellini:1996uh,Casini:1998wr,Winitzki:1999ve"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle N(t,\mathbf{x})N(\tilde{t},\tilde{\mathbf{x}})\right\rangle =C(t,\tilde{t},\left|\mathbf{x}-\tilde{\mathbf{x}}\right|;\phi).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

An explicit form of the correlator 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 depends on the specific window function 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 used for averaging the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 on Hubble scales.
 However, the window function 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is merely a phenomenological device used in lieu of a complete 
\emph on
ab initio
\emph default
 derivation of the stochastic inflation picture.
 One expects, therefore, that results of calculations should be robust with
 respect to the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, any uncertainty due to the choice of the window function
 must be regarded as an imprecision inherent in the method.
 For instance, a robust result in this sense is an exponentially fast decay
 of correlations on time scales 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t\gtrsim H^{-1}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C(t,\tilde{t},\left|\mathbf{x}-\tilde{\mathbf{x}}\right|;\phi)\propto\exp\left(-2H(\phi)\left|t-\tilde{t}\right|\right),\label{eq:C decay}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and similarly a fast decay at large distances; both results hold for a wide
 class of smooth window functions
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:1999ve"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For a wide class of window functions, the asymptotic behavior of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:1999ve"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
...***
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Hence, as expected, correlations quickly decay on scales of several Hubble
 sizes.
 The precise form of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 might be important for numerical simulations of the spacetime a la Linde.
 (This is discussed in the above paper and probably doesn't belong here.)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the purposes of the present consideration, we only need to track the
 evolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(t,\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 along a single comoving worldline 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=\text{const}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we will not need an explicit form of 
\begin_inset Formula $C(t,\tilde{t},\left|\mathbf{x}-\tilde{\mathbf{x}}\right|;\phi)$
\end_inset

 but merely the value at coincident points 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\tilde{t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=\tilde{\mathbf{x}}$
\end_inset

, which is computed in the slow-roll inflationary scenario as
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Starobinsky:1986fx"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C(t,t,0;\phi)=\frac{H^{2}(\phi)}{4\pi^{2}}=\sqrt{2D(\phi)H(\phi)}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

(This represents the fluctuation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:delta-phi"

\end_inset

) accumulated during one Hubble time, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t=H^{-1}$
\end_inset

.) Due to the property
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:C decay"

\end_inset

), one may neglect correlations on time scales 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t\gtrsim H^{-1}$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

noise
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 field.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Taking these correlations into account leads to a picture of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

color noise
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Matarrese:2003ye,Liguori:2004fa"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 In what follows, we only consider the simpler picture of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

white noise
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as an approximation adequate for the issues at hand.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Thus, the evolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 on time scales 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t\gtrsim H^{-1}$
\end_inset

 can be described by a finite-difference form of the Langevin equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Langevin"

\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi(t+\Delta t)-\phi(t)=v(\phi)\Delta t+\sqrt{2D(\phi)\Delta t}\,\xi(t),\label{eq:Langevin FD}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D(\phi)\equiv\frac{H^{3}(\phi)}{8\pi^{2}}\label{eq:D def}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 is a normalized random variable representing 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

white noise,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left\langle \xi\right\rangle  & =0,\quad\left\langle \xi^{2}\right\rangle =1,\label{eq:xi def 1}\\
\left\langle \xi(t)\xi(t+\Delta t)\right\rangle  & =0\quad\text{for}\quad\Delta t\gtrsim H^{-1}.
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Langevin FD"

\end_inset

) is interpreted as describing a Brownian motion 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(t)$
\end_inset

 with the systematic 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

drift
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $v(\phi)$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

diffusion coefficient
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\phi)$
\end_inset

.
 In a typical slow-roll inflationary scenario, there will be a range of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 where the noise dominates over the deterministic drift, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v(\phi)\Delta t\ll\sqrt{2D(\phi)\Delta t},\quad\Delta t\equiv H^{-1}.\label{eq:diffusion dominated}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Such a range of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
diffusion-dominated regime
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
diffusion-dominated regime
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 near the end of inflation, the opposite inequality holds because the amplitude
 of the noise is very small since the observational constraints indicate
 that the amplitude of cosmological density fluctuations is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\delta\rho}{\rho}\sim\frac{\sqrt{2D(\phi)H(\phi)}}{v(\phi)}\sim10^{-5}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 where the inequality
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:diffusion dominated"

\end_inset

) holds constitute the 
\series bold
deterministic regime
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
deterministic regime
\end_layout

\end_inset

 where the random jumps can be neglected and the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 follows the slow-roll trajectory.
 The ranges of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 that correspond to the deterministic regime or to the fluctuation-dominated
 regime can be determined when a specific form of the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is given or, alternatively, when the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $v(\phi)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\phi)$
\end_inset

 are known.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fokker–Planck equations: comoving distribution
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Fokker-Planck-equations"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A useful description of the statistical properties of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(t)$
\end_inset

 is furnished by the probability density 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,t)d\phi$
\end_inset

 of having a value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 As in the case of the Langevin equation, the values 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(t)$
\end_inset

 are measured along a single, randomly chosen comoving worldline 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=\text{const}$
\end_inset

.
 The probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,t)$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
comoving
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
comoving probability distribution
\end_layout

\end_inset

 probability distribution and satisfies the Fokker–Planck (FP) equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vanKampen:1981:SPiPC,Risken:1989:TFPE"
literal "true"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{t}P=\partial_{\phi}\left[-v(\phi)P+\partial_{\phi}\left(D(\phi)P\right)\right].\label{eq:FP c}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $v(\phi)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\phi)$
\end_inset

 are in general model-dependent and need to be calculated in each particular
 scenario.
 These calculations require only the knowledge of the deterministic inflationary
 evolution, 
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

in the slow-roll approximation (
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\text{sr}}(\phi)=\dot{\phi}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\phi}$
\end_inset

 must be expressed as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

) and the mode functions of the quantized scalar perturbations for computing
 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\phi)$
\end_inset

.
 For ordinary slow-roll inflation with an effective potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\phi)$
\end_inset

, the results are well-known expressions
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:v def 1"

\end_inset

) and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:D def"

\end_inset

).
 The corresponding expressions for models of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-inflation were derived in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Helmer:2006tz"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 using the quantum theory of perturbations in 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-inflation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Garriga:1999vw"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 In general, we can determine 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 by computing the quantum average
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
2D\Delta t\equiv\left\langle 0\right|\left\langle \delta\dot{\hat{\phi}}\Delta t\right\rangle _{L}^{2}\left|0\right\rangle ,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \delta\dot{\hat{\phi}}\Delta t\right\rangle _{L}$
\end_inset

 is the (quantum) fluctuation of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 averaged on distance scales 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 that correspond to effective 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

classicalization
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the fluctuations.
 In the case of minimally coupled field, 
\begin_inset Formula $L\sim H^{-1}$
\end_inset

 while for non-canonical fields having nontrivial speed of sound, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{s}\neq1$
\end_inset

, as has 
\begin_inset Formula $L\sim c_{s}H^{-1}$
\end_inset

 as shown in
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Helmer:2006tz"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The FP equation similar to Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FP c"

\end_inset

) first appeared in the paper
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vilenkin:1983xq"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, although the main topic of that paper was the creation of the universe
 in quantum cosmology.
 The formalism of FP equations was subsequently developed by many authors
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Starobinsky:1986fx,Goncharov:1987ir,Nambu:1987ef,Nakao:1988yi,Nambu:1988je,Nambu:1989uf,Mijic:1990qx,Stewart:1991dy,Linde:1993nz,Linde:1993xx,Mijic:1994vv,Starobinsky:1994bd"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

physicist's
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 derivation of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FP c"

\end_inset

) is as follows.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

physical level of rigor
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in treating stochastic equations consists of treating the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

white noise
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 as a Gaussian random variable and using a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

single step
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the Brownian motion, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\phi\propto\sqrt{\Delta t}\xi$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, we explicitly introduce a quantity that is proportional
 to the square root of the time step 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

.
 Then we expand all expressions up to first order in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 and take the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 at the end of the calculations.
 This procedure yields results that are equivalent to the Ito interpretation
 of the stochastic calculus.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let us introduce the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

propagator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi_{1},\phi_{2},t_{1},t_{2})$
\end_inset

 signifying the probability density of having the value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{2}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{2}$
\end_inset

 if we had 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi_{1},\phi_{2},t_{1}-\Delta t,t_{2})$
\end_inset

 is expressed through 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi_{1},\phi_{2},t_{1},t_{2})$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P(\phi_{1},\phi_{2},t_{1}-\Delta t,t_{2})=\int P(\tilde{\phi},\phi_{2},t_{1},t_{2})\,\text{Prob}(\Delta\phi=\tilde{\phi}-\phi_{1})d\tilde{\phi},\label{eq:FP 1 pre 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Prob}(\Delta\phi=x)dx$
\end_inset

 is the probability density of obtaining a value 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 for the random quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\phi$
\end_inset

 expressed by Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Langevin FD"

\end_inset

).
 The quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\phi$
\end_inset

 depends on the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

white noise
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\equiv\xi(t)$
\end_inset

, for which we may introduce explicitly the normal Gaussian distribution
 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\xi)$
\end_inset

.
 Then we may write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \int P(\tilde{\phi},\phi_{2},t_{1},t_{2})\,\text{Prob}(\Delta\phi=\tilde{\phi}-\phi_{1})\,d\tilde{\phi}\nonumber \\
 & =\int P(\phi_{1}+\Delta\phi(\xi),\phi_{2},t_{1},t_{2})\,p(\xi)d\xi.\label{eq:FP 1 equ 2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Now we substitute Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Langevin FD"

\end_inset

) for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\phi$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta\phi(\xi)=v\Delta t+\xi\sqrt{2D\Delta t}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Note that we evaluated 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\phi)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v(\phi)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t(\phi)\equiv H^{-1}$
\end_inset

 at the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

old
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 value, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\equiv\phi(t)$
\end_inset

, rather than at the new value 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\phi}\equiv\phi(t+\Delta t)$
\end_inset

.
 For brevity we simply wrote 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 above, implying 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\phi)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v(\phi)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{-1}(\phi)$
\end_inset

.
 Now we transform Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FP 1 equ 2"

\end_inset

) by expanding 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

