\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

.
 The derivation of the FP equation proceeds by taking the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 in the Langevin equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Langevin FD"

\end_inset

), promoting it from a difference equation to a stochastic 
\emph on
differential
\emph default
 equation.
 Although the stochastic differential equation appears to describe fluctuations
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 that scale as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\Delta t}$
\end_inset

 for arbitrarily small 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

, we know that these fluctuations are not actually semiclassical until a
 few 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-folding times, that is, until 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t\gtrsim H^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Accordingly, the Langevin and the FP equations can be used only to describe
 features of the distribution at time scales at least 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t\gtrsim H^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 It is, however, technically more convenient to consider continuous-time
 Brownian motion with infinitesimal steps, using either Langevin or FP equations.
 It is sufficient that these equations reproduce correct results for steps
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t\gtrsim H^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 In order to quantify this artificial distinction between continuous and
 discrete Brownian motion, we may introduce a parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t=\left(\varepsilon H\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 (This parameter is related to the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 introduced in the early derivations of the stochastic approach, 
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Starobinsky:1986fx,Nambu:1987ef"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.) As explained above, fluctuations can be approximately treated as classical
 white noise only on timescales 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t\gtrsim H^{-1}$
\end_inset

, or more precisely, with values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp(\varepsilon)\gg1$
\end_inset

.
 We find by examining the derivation of the FP equation that the resulting
 equation is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 For this reason, we conclude that a description in terms of the finite-differen
ce Langevin equation is adequately translated into a FP equation.
 
\end_layout

