\begin_layout Standard
Presently we focus on scenarios with a single scalar field; however, the
 formalism of FP equations can be straightforwardly extended to multi-field
 models as well as to models with non-canonical kinetic terms (see 
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vilenkin:1999kd,Rigopoulos:2005bq,Helmer:2006tz"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 For instance, the FP equation for a two-field model is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{t}P=\partial_{\phi\phi}\left(DP\right)+\partial_{\chi\chi}\left(DP\right)-\partial_{\phi}\left(v_{\phi}P\right)-\partial_{\chi}\left(v_{\chi}P\right),\label{eq:FP 2 field}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\phi,\chi)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\phi}(\phi,\chi)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\chi}(\phi,\chi)$
\end_inset

 are appropriate coefficients.
 The volume distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{V}(\phi,\chi,t)$
\end_inset

 is defined analogously.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To specify the solution uniquely, the FP equations must be supplemented
 by boundary conditions at both ends of the inflating range of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 (this issue was considered in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Linde:1993nz,Linde:1993xx"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 At the reheating boundary (
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

), one may imposes the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

exit
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 boundary conditions,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{\phi}\left[D(\phi)P\right]_{\phi=\phi_{*}}=0,\quad\partial_{\phi}\left[D(\phi)P_{V}\right]_{\phi=\phi_{*}}=0.\label{eq:exit BC}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

These boundary conditions express the fact that random jumps are very small
 at the end of inflation and cannot move the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 away from 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Another, simpler possibility is to impose the absorbing boundary condition,
 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi_{*},t)=0$
\end_inset

.
 It is usually the case that the solutions of the FP equations are insensitive
 to the precise choice of the boundary conditions at the reheating boundary.
 While a different choice of boundary conditions will distort the solution
 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,t)$
\end_inset

 near the boundary points, this distortion is negligible away from these
 points
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Linde:1993xx"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\phi)$
\end_inset

 reaches Planck energy scales at some Planck boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{\text{P}}$
\end_inset

, a boundary condition must be imposed also at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{\text{P}}$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, one can use the absorbing boundary condition,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P(\phi_{\text{P}})=0,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which means that Planck-energy regions with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{\text{P}}$
\end_inset

 disappear from consideration
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Linde:1993nz,Linde:1993xx"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Since the Planck boundary condition is imposed 
\emph on
ad hoc
\emph default
 rather than derived from fundamental considerations, we would need to verify
 that the conclusions do not depend sensitively on the choice of boundary
 condition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gauge dependence issues
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Gauge-dependence-issues"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An important feature of the FP equations is their dependence on the choice
 of the time coordinate (or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gauge
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as it is frequently called in this context).
 One can consider a replacement of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t\rightarrow\tau,\quad d\tau\equiv T(\phi)dt,\label{eq:t tau}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

understood in the sense of integrating along comoving worldlines 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=\text{const}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\phi)>0$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary function of the field.
 For instance, a possible choice is 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\phi)\equiv H(\phi)$
\end_inset

, which makes the new time variable dimensionless, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tau=\int Hdt=\ln a.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This time variable is called 
\series bold
scale factor time
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
scale factor time
\end_layout

\end_inset

 or 
\series bold
\emph on
e
\emph default
-folding time
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-folding time
\end_layout

\end_inset

 since it measures the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-foldings along a comoving worldline.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,\tau)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{V}(\phi,\tau)$
\end_inset

 are defined as before, except that one considers the 3-volumes along hypersurfa
ces of equal 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 These distributions satisfy FP equations similar to Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FP c"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FP V"

\end_inset

).
 With the replacement
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:t tau"

\end_inset

), the coefficients of the new FP equations are modified as follows
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:1995pg"
literal "true"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D(\phi)\rightarrow\frac{D(\phi)}{T(\phi)},\quad v(\phi)\rightarrow\frac{v(\phi)}{T(\phi)},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

while the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

growth
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 term 
\begin_inset Formula $3HP_{V}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FP V"

\end_inset

) is replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $3HT^{-1}P_{V}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As an example, let us show the FP equations written in the 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-folding time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\equiv\ln a$
\end_inset

.
 The comoving FP equation is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{\tau}P=\partial_{\phi\phi}\left[\frac{D}{H}P\right]-\partial_{\phi}\left[\frac{v}{H}P\right],\label{eq:FP efolding}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

while the FP equation for the volume-weighted distribution is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{\tau}P_{V}=\partial_{\phi\phi}\left[\frac{D}{H}P_{V}\right]-\partial_{\phi}\left[\frac{v}{H}P_{V}\right]+3P_{V}.\label{eq:FP V efolding}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It is important to note that these two equations are essentially equivalent:
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,\tau)$
\end_inset

 is a solution of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FP efolding"

\end_inset

) then 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{V}(\phi,\tau)=e^{3\tau}P(\phi,\tau)$
\end_inset

 is a solution of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FP V efolding"

\end_inset

), and 
\emph on
vice versa
\emph default
.
 This equivalence is easily understood: The volume-weighted distribution
 on surfaces of equal 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, that is, of equal scale factor, is the same as the comoving distribution
 since the growth of volume along a surface of equal scale factor is everywhere
 the same by construction.
 However, comoving and volume-weighted distributions in other time gauges
 are not equivalent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Changing the time gauge may significantly alter the qualitative behavior
 of the solutions of the FP equations.
 For instance, stationary distributions defined through the proper time
 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-folding time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\ln a$
\end_inset

 were found to have radically different behavior
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Linde:1993xx,Garcia-Bellido:1994ci,Vilenkin:1995yd"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 This sensitivity to the choice of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

time gauge
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is unavoidable since hypersurfaces of equal 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 may preferentially select regions with certain properties.
 It is easy to see that most of the physical volume in equal-
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 hypersurfaces is filled with regions that have gained expansion by remaining
 near the top of the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\phi)$
\end_inset

, while hypersurfaces of equal scale factor will instead under-represent
 those regions.
 Thus, a statement such as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

most of the volume in the universe has values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 with high 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\phi)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is largely gauge-
\emph on
dependent
\emph default
.
 This is to be expected since the FP equation describes the distribution
 of properties along equal-
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 hypersurfaces, while these hypersurfaces defined for different time gauges
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 are not statistically equivalent but differ from each other in a systematic
 way.
 Hence, as a rule, any solution or any property of the FP equation is gauge-depe
ndent.
 Exceptions are found only when one considers some results obtained by solving
 
\emph on
time
\emph default
-
\emph on
independent
\emph default
 FP equations, more precisely, FP equations that do not contain the time
 variable and can be reformulated in terms of gauge-independent coefficients
 such as 
\begin_inset Formula $D/v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v/H$
\end_inset

.
 We will give examples of such cases below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the e-folding gauge we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}=\gamma+3$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

In the early works on eternal inflation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Linde:1993nz,Linde:1993xx,Garcia-Bellido:1994ci,Garcia-Bellido:1994vz"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, the late-time asymptotic distribution of volume 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{V}^{(\tilde{\gamma})}(\phi)$
\end_inset

 along hypersurfaces of equal proper time [see Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:late-time V"

\end_inset

)] was interpreted as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stationary
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 distribution of field values in the universe.
 However, the high sensitivity of this distribution to the choice of the
 time variable makes this interpretation unsatisfactory.
 Also, it was noted
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Tegmark:2004qd"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 that equal-proper time volume distributions predict an unacceptably small
 probability for the currently observed CMB temperature.
 The reason for this result is the extreme bias of the proper-time gauge
 towards over-representing regions where reheating occurred very recently
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Linde:1994gy,Vilenkin:1995yd"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 This is a manifestation of the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

youngness paradox
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (see Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:The-Youngness-paradox"

\end_inset

).
 One might ask whether hypersurfaces of equal scale factor or some other
 choice of time gauge would provide less biased answers.
 However, it turns out that there exists no 
\emph on
a priori
\emph default
 choice of the time gauge 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 that provides precisely unbiased equal-
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 probability distributions for all potentials 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\phi)$
\end_inset

 in models of slow-roll inflation (see Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Predictions-in-continuous"

\end_inset

 for details).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although the FP equations necessarily involve a dependence on gauge, they
 do provide a useful statistical picture of the distribution of fields in
 the universe.
 The FP techniques can also be used for deriving several gauge-independent
 results.
 For instance, the presence of eternal inflation is a gauge-independent
 statement (see also Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Presence-of-eternal"

\end_inset

): if the largest eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 is positive in one gauge of the form
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:t tau"

\end_inset

), then 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}>0$
\end_inset

 in every other gauge (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2001np"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for a rigorous proof).
 Using the FP approach, one can also compute the fractal dimension of the
 inflating domain 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Aryal:1987vn,Winitzki:2001np"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and the probability of exiting inflation through a particular point 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 of the reheating boundary in the configuration space (in case there exists
 more than one such point, such as in multi-field models).
 These computations yield gauge-invariant results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We postpone the consideration of the fractal structure of the spacetime
 to Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Global-structure-of"

\end_inset

.
 Presently we will show how to determine the exit probabilities 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vilenkin:1999kd,Helmer:2006tz"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Let us assume for simplicity that there are two possible exit points 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{E}$
\end_inset

, and that the initial distribution is concentrated at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P(\phi,t=0)=\delta(\phi-\phi_{0}),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{E}<\phi_{0}<\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Since we are considering the probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,t)$
\end_inset

 along a single comoving worldline, the appropriate FP equation is Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FP c"

\end_inset

).
 This equation can be rewritten as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conservation law,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{t}P=\partial_{\phi}J,\quad J(\phi)\equiv\partial_{\phi}(DP)-vP,\label{eq:cons law}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 plays the role of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

current.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Using the conservation law
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:cons law"

\end_inset

), one finds that the probability of exiting inflation through 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{E}$
\end_inset

 during a time interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[t,t+dt]$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
dp_{\text{exit}}(\phi_{E}) & =J(\phi_{E})dt\equiv\left.\left(\partial_{\phi}\left(DP\right)-vP\right)\right|_{\phi=\phi_{E}}dt\nonumber \\
 & =-v(\phi_{E})P(\phi_{E},t)dt.
\end{align}

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $v(\phi_{E})<0$
\end_inset

 and we used the boundary condition
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:exit BC"

\end_inset

).
 Hence, the total probability of exiting through 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{E}$
\end_inset

 at any time is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{\textrm{exit}}(\phi_{E})=\int_{0}^{\infty}dp_{\text{exit}}(\phi_{E})=-v(\phi_{E})\int_{0}^{\infty}P(\phi_{E},t)dt.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Introducing an auxiliary function 
\begin_inset Formula $F(\phi)$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F(\phi)\equiv-v(\phi)\int_{0}^{\infty}P(\phi,t)dt,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and integrating Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:cons law"

\end_inset

) in 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 one can show that 
\begin_inset Formula $F(\phi)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the gauge-invariant equation, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{\phi}\left[\partial_{\phi}\left(\frac{D}{v}F\right)-F\right]=\delta(\phi-\phi_{0}).\label{eq:for p exit}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is in accord with the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\textrm{exit}}(\phi_{E})=F(\phi_{E})$
\end_inset

 is a gauge-invariant quantity.
 Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:for p exit"

\end_inset

) with the boundary conditions
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F(\phi_{*})=0,\quad\left.\partial_{\phi}(\frac{D}{v}F)\right|_{\phi=\phi_{E}}=0,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

can be straightforwardly integrated and yields explicit expressions for
 the exit probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\text{exit}}(\phi_{E})$
\end_inset

 as a function of the initial value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Helmer:2006tz"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for some specific calculations).
 The exit probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\text{exit}}(\phi_{*})$
\end_inset

 can be determined similarly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the same way one can try to use the volume distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{V}(\phi,t)$
\end_inset

 to compute the total volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{*}(t_{0})$
\end_inset

 reheated up to a given time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 One finds
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V_{*}(t_{0})=-v(\phi_{*})\int_{0}^{t_{0}}P_{V}(\phi_{*},t)dt.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

However, one generally finds that 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{V}(\phi_{*},t)$
\end_inset

 grows exponentially at late times, so this integral cannot be evaluated
 in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the multi-field situation, 
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

with fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{1}$
\end_inset

, ..., 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{N}$
\end_inset

, where the reheating boundary is 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 with various possible values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{i}$
\end_inset

, one may be interested in the total physical volume reheated at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 and with given values of the fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 One may also compute the comoving exit probability at various points of
 the reheating boundary.
 Those computations are analogous to the computations in one-field scenarios.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consideration of the exit probability can motivate the choice of the
 Ito factor ordering for the FP equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vilenkin:1999kd"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Namely, it can be shown that only the Ito factor ordering gives gauge-independe
nt results when one computes the exit probability.
 An arbitrary factor ordering can be described by introducing a parameter
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and by replacing
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{\phi\phi}(DP)\rightarrow\partial_{\phi}(D^{\theta}\partial_{\phi}(D^{1-\theta}P))
\end{equation}

\end_inset

in the FP equation.
 With an arbitrary gauge, 
\begin_inset Formula $d\tau\equiv Tdt$
\end_inset

, the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $D,v$
\end_inset

 are replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $D/T,v/T$
\end_inset

 and so Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:for p exit"

\end_inset

) becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{\phi}\left[\left(\frac{D}{T}\right)^{\theta}\partial_{\phi}\left(\left(\frac{D}{T}\right)^{1-\theta}\frac{T}{v}F\right)-F\right]=\delta(\phi-\phi_{0}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now it is clear that the above equation depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 (
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

is gauge-dependent) as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 However, we expect that the exit probability is gauge-independent since
 it is defined as the probability of finishing inflation at a given value
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 for a randomly chosen comoving observer, which is clearly independent of
 the choice of coordinates.
 Motivated by this consideration, we choose the Ito factor ordering (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=0$
\end_inset

) as shown in Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Langevin FD"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FP c"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Interpretation of FP equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Langevin and the Fokker–Planck equations are, in principle, equivalent
 descriptions of the same stochastic process, and we will focus on the FP
 description because it is more convenient to work with.
 It is important to note also that the boundary conditions (at the reheating
 and Planck boundaries) can be imposed straightforwardly in the FP description,
 but cannot be easily described in the framework of the Langevin equation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The issue of gauge dependence is also most conveniently investigated in
 the FP formalism.
 Let us now consider the FP equations with an arbitrary time gauge 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First we comment on the backward FP equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:backward FP"

\end_inset

).
 I would like to emphasize that this equation,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-\partial_{t}P(\phi,\phi_{f},t,t_{f})=\hat{L}_{\phi}P(\phi,\phi_{f},t,t_{f}),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

does 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 (despite its appearance) describe the evolution of the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,\phi_{f},t,t_{f})$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

backward in time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 with a fixed future value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{f}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 As is well known, the backward diffusion equation is ill-defined because
 of instabilities; an arbitrarily small uncertainty in the fixed future
 value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{f}$
\end_inset

 will lead to an arbitrarily large variation in the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 at earlier times.
 Therefore, one cannot actually solve the backward FP equation in a directly
 constructive way (
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

numerically).
 One must always solve the 
\emph on
forward
\emph default
 FP equation, and then one may use the fact that its solution also satisfies
 the backward FP equation.
 The proper interpretation of the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,\phi_{f},t,t_{f})$
\end_inset

 is always a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

forward
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 one, 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is the probability of future values 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{f}$
\end_inset

 given past values 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now turn to the forward FP equations.
 As noted above, the comoving distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,\tau)$
\end_inset

 admits two interpretations.
 On the one hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,\tau)$
\end_inset

 is the probability of the field having a value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 along a single, randomly chosen comoving trajectory; on the other hand,
 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,\tau)$
\end_inset

 is the fraction of comoving volume where the field has the value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, within an equal-
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 hypersurface.
 (The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

comoving 3-volume
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of a subdomain 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of an equal-
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 hypersurface is defined as the 3-volume of the subdomain 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}$
\end_inset

 of the hypersurface 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=0$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{0}$
\end_inset

 consists of points whose comoving worldlines pass through 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equivalence of these interpretations can be seen from the following
 argument.
 Consider a large but finite domain of volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 within the hypersurface 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=0$
\end_inset

 and a very dense grid of comoving trajectories starting out from this domain.
 The total number 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 of these trajectories may be chosen as finite but very large, and the initial
 volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 can be subdivided into 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 tiny regions of comoving volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}/N$
\end_inset

 situated around each of the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 comoving lines.
 If the initial volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 is sufficiently large so that all the statistically possible histories
 are sufficiently well sampled, then the number of lines that reach a value
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 at a time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is very close to 
\begin_inset Formula $NP(\phi,\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the comoving volume of the subdomain of the equal-
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 hypersurface having the value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}P(\phi,\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore in the statistical limit 
\begin_inset Formula $N\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, the fraction of the comoving volume containing the field value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 at the time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,\tau)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,\tau)$
\end_inset

 is the statistical distribution of the comoving volume along an equal-
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 hypersurface, then the comoving volume of the subdomain with the value
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 will be 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}P(\phi,\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 We denote this subdomain by 
\begin_inset Formula $S(\phi,\tau)$
\end_inset

 and consider a comoving trajectory randomly chosen from the total comoving
 volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The probability of this trajectory passing through the subdomain 
\begin_inset Formula $S(\phi,\tau)$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}P(\phi,\tau)/V_{0}=P(\phi,\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,\tau)$
\end_inset

 is the probability of the field having the value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 along a randomly chosen trajectory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note that there 
\emph on
do
\emph default
 exist correlations between the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 at nearby comoving trajectories.
 However, these correlations are not reflected by the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,\tau)$
\end_inset

 since it specifies only the total volume, but not the location, of regions
 with the field value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 If the initial comoving volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 is sufficiently large (many Hubble volumes), the distribution of the field
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 along a randomly chosen comoving trajectory will be 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,\tau)$
\end_inset

 despite the correlations between nearby trajectories.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Turning now to the distribution of the physical volume 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{V}(\phi,\tau)$
\end_inset

, we note that there is now only one interpretation, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{V}(\phi,\tau)$
\end_inset

 is the total proper 3-volume of the subdomain with the field value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 within an equal-
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 hypersurface.
 (As before, we consider only the comoving future of a large but finite
 initial volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{0}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=0$
\end_inset

.) It appears to be impossible to interpret 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{V}(\phi,\tau)$
\end_inset

 directly in terms of observations made on a single randomly chosen comoving
 trajectory.
 The distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{V}(\phi,\tau)$
\end_inset

 describes a branching diffusion process with a possibly unlimited growth,
 and its interpretation necessarily has to involve a potentially very large
 ensemble of trajectories.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An interesting alternative description of the inflationary spacetime can
 be given using the path integral formalism
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shtanov:1994nt"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The path integral is used to describe Brownian random walk, as is standard
 in the theory of stochastic processes.
 While the description of Brownian motion in terms of path integrals is
 entirely equivalent to that by FP equations, some aspects of the evolution
 may be more easily understood, for instance, by visualizing the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

most likely
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 trajectory.
 One can compute the saddle point approximation to the path integral in
 hopes of achieving a qualitative understanding of the behavior of trajectories.
 It has been shown that the most likely trajectories during eternal inflation
 spend a long time in fluctuation-dominated regime and subsequently quickly
 reach reheating.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
C.
 Armendariz-Picon and V.
 F.
 Mukhanov (1998), unpublished; R.
 Abramo, C.
 Armendariz-Picon, and V.
 F.
 Mukhanov (2000), unpublished.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Such results cannot be obtained in the FP equation approach since the FP
 equation furnishes no global information about the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 along the entire trajectory.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another kind of information not furnished by the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,t)$
\end_inset

 is the information about correlations of field values between neighbor
 points, as already noted above.
 The pairwise distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi_{1},\phi_{2},t)$
\end_inset

 of field values at 
\emph on
two
\emph default
 fixed comoving points 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{2}$
\end_inset

 has been considered 
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Scannapieco:2002qd,Creminelli:2008es"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and can be also obtained as a solution of a modified FP equation.
 Correlations between neighbor points may be used, for example, to determine
 the mean curvature of the reheating surface at superhorizon scales.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
S.
 Winitzki (2002), unpublished.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We will not treat these advanced applications here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Methods of solution; approximations
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Methods-of-solution"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In principle, one can solve the FP equations forward in time by a numerical
 procedure, starting from a given initial distribution at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us thus concentrate on available analytical methods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once the initial and boundary conditions for the FP equation are specified,
 one may write the general solution of the FP equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FP c"

\end_inset

) as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P(\phi,t)=\sum_{\lambda}C_{\lambda}P^{(\lambda)}(\phi)\,e^{\lambda t},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the sum is performed over all the eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 of the differential operator
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{L}^{\dagger}P\equiv\partial_{\phi}\left[-v(\phi)P+\partial_{\phi}\left(D(\phi)P\right)\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the corresponding eigenfunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{(\lambda)}$
\end_inset

 are defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{L}^{\dagger}P^{(\lambda)}(\phi)=\lambda P^{(\lambda)}(\phi).\label{eq:stationary FP 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The constants 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed through the initial distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,t_{0})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By an appropriate change of variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\rightarrow z$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi)\rightarrow F(z)$
\end_inset

, the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 may be brought into a manifestly self-adjoint form
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Nakao:1988yi,Nambu:1988je,Matarrese:1988hc,Nambu:1989uf,Mijic:1990qx,Winitzki:1995pg"
literal "true"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{L}\,\rightarrow\,\frac{d^{2}}{dz^{2}}-U(z).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

potential
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U(z)$
\end_inset

 and the new variable 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 are defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
z\equiv z(\phi) & \equiv\int^{\phi}\frac{d\phi}{\sqrt{D(\phi)}},\quad\partial_{\phi}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{D}}\partial_{z},\label{eq:x new def}\\
P^{(\lambda)}(\phi) & \equiv\psi^{(\lambda)}(z)D^{-3/4}(\phi)\,\exp\left[\frac{1}{2}\int^{\phi}\frac{v_{*}(\phi)}{D(\phi)}d\phi\right],\label{eq:new P psi def}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the replacement 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\rightarrow\phi(z)$
\end_inset

 is implied in the last line.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\lambda}(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is being multiplied by a strictly positive function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, so the positivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x)$
\end_inset

 will entail the positivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{(\lambda)}(\phi)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

Under the replacements
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:x new def"

\end_inset

)-(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:new P psi def"

\end_inset

), Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:stationary FP 1"

\end_inset

) is transformed into
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi_{,zz}-U(z)\psi=\lambda\psi,\label{eq:psi FP}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $U(z)$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

potential
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 defined as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 through the relation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U(z)\equiv\frac{3}{16}\frac{\left(D_{,\phi}\right)^{2}}{D}-\frac{D_{,\phi\phi}}{4}-\frac{vD_{,\phi}}{2D}+\frac{v_{,\phi}}{2}+\frac{v^{2}}{4D}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:psi FP"

\end_inset

) is the self-adjoint form of the stationary FP equation and is formally
 equivalent to a stationary Schrödinger equation for a particle in a one-dimensi
onal 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

potential
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U(z)$
\end_inset

 with the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

energy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $E\equiv-\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Then one can show that all the eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 are nonpositive; in particular, the (algebraically) largest eigenvalue
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{\max}\equiv-\gamma<0$
\end_inset

 is nondegenerate and the corresponding eigenfunction 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{(\lambda_{\max})}(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is everywhere positive
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:1995pg,Helmer:2006tz"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Hence, this eigenfunction describes the late-time asymptotic distribution
 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,t)$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P(\phi,t)\propto P^{(\lambda_{\max})}(\phi)\,e^{-\gamma t}.\label{eq:late-time c}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{(\lambda_{\max})}(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stationary
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 per comoving volume at late times.
 The exponential decay of the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,t)$
\end_inset

 means that at late times most of the comoving volume (except for an exponential
ly small fraction) has finished inflation and entered reheating.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another, equivalent way to make the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 self-adjoint without changing variables is to introduce the scalar product
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle f_{1},f_{2}\right\rangle =\int f_{1}(\phi)f_{2}(\phi)M(\phi)d\phi,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M(\phi)\equiv D_{0}(\phi)\exp\left[-\int^{\phi}\frac{v_{0}(\phi)}{D_{0}(\phi)}d\phi\right].\label{eq:scalar product M def}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

One can then verify that the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 is formally self-adjoint with this scalar product,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle f_{1},\hat{L}^{\dagger}f_{2}\rangle=\langle\hat{L}^{\dagger}f_{1},f_{2}\rangle.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 This points to another way of showing that the spectrum of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 is bounded from above.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similar considerations apply to the volume-weighted distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{V}$
\end_inset

.
 One can represent the general solution of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FP V"

\end_inset

) by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{V}(\phi,t)=\sum_{\tilde{\lambda}}C_{\tilde{\lambda}}P_{V}^{(\tilde{\lambda})}(\phi)e^{\tilde{\lambda}t},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
[\hat{L}^{\dagger}+3H(\phi)]P_{V}^{(\tilde{\lambda})}(\phi)=\tilde{\lambda}P_{V}^{(\tilde{\lambda})}(\phi).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By the same method as for the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

, it is possible to show that the spectrum of eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 of the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}^{\dagger}+3H(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is bounded from above and that the largest eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\lambda}_{\max}\equiv\tilde{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 admits a nondegenerate, everywhere positive eigenfunction 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{V}^{(\tilde{\gamma})}(\phi)$
\end_inset

.
 However, the largest eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 may be either positive or negative.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}>0$
\end_inset

, the late-time behavior of 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{V}(\phi,t)$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{V}(\phi,t)\propto P_{V}^{(\tilde{\gamma})}(\phi)e^{\tilde{\gamma}t},\label{eq:late-time V}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which means that the total physical volume of all the inflating regions
 grows with time.
 This is the behavior expected in eternal inflation: the number of independently
 inflating domains increases without limit.
 Thus, the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}>0$
\end_inset

 is a criterion for the presence of eternal self-reproduction of inflating
 domains.
 The corresponding distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{V}^{(\tilde{\gamma})}(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stationary
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 distribution
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Linde:1993nz,Linde:1993xx,Garcia-Bellido:1994ci,Garcia-Bellido:1995kc"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}\leq0$
\end_inset

, eternal inflation does not occur and the entire spatial slice will almost
 surely (
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

with probability 1) enter the reheating stage after a finite time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

new
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 inflationary type and has a global maximum at say 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

, the eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 can be estimated (under the usual slow-roll assumptions on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

) as follows
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:1995pg"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 One approximates the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\phi)$
\end_inset

 near its maximum by a parabola,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
V(\phi)\approx V(\phi_{0})-\frac{1}{2}\left|V^{\prime\prime}(\phi_{0})\right|\phi^{2}+O(\phi^{3}),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and reduces the FP equation to a Schrödinger equation with a harmonic potential
 near 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The known spectrum of this Schrödinger operator allows one to obtain an
 estimate (in Planck units) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma\approx-\frac{\left|V^{\prime\prime}(\phi_{0})\right|}{8\pi V(\phi_{0})}H(\phi_{0})<0,\quad\tilde{\gamma}\approx3H(\phi_{0})>0.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Numerical calculations confirm that these estimates are precise.
 Therefore, we find 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}>0$
\end_inset

, meaning that eternal inflation is generic in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

new
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 inflationary scenario.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us comment on the possibility of obtaining solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,t)$
\end_inset

 in practice.
 With the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\phi)=\lambda\phi^{4}$
\end_inset

, the full time-dependent FP equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FP c"

\end_inset

) can be solved analytically via a nonlinear change of variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\rightarrow\phi^{-2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hodges:1989zz,Matarrese:1988hc,Yi:1991ub"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 This exact solution, as well as an approximate solution 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,t)$
\end_inset

 for a general potential, can be also obtained using the saddle-point evaluation
 of a path-integral expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,t)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shtanov:1994nt"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 In some cases the eigenvalue equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}^{\dagger}P^{(\lambda)}=\lambda P^{(\lambda)}$
\end_inset

 may be reduced to an exactly solvable Schr
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
"o
\end_layout

\end_inset

dinger equation.
 These cases include potentials of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\phi)=\lambda e^{\mu\phi}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\phi)=\lambda\phi^{-2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\phi)=\lambda\cosh^{-2}(\mu\phi)$
\end_inset

; see 
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:1995pg"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for other examples of exactly solvable potentials.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the reduction of the FP equation to a self-adjoint form (
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

to the Schrödinger equation) is useful in the theoretical analysis, it is
 only rarely the case that a Schrödinger equation is exactly solvable.
 Except for such rare cases, one has to resort to approximations.
 We will briefly outline the available results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One important approximation applies to the evolution in the deterministic
 regime where fluctuations are subdominant and the field approximately follows
 its deterministic, slow-roll trajectory.
 In that case, one may neglect the second-derivative term in the FP equation.
 For instance, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FP V"

\end_inset

) becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{t}P_{V}\approx-\partial_{\phi}\left[v(\phi)P_{V}\right]+3H(\phi)P_{V},\label{eq:FP V sr}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which may be solved by the method of characteristics.
 Let us consider the corresponding time-independent FP equation,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-\partial_{\phi}\left[v(\phi)P_{V}^{(\lambda)}\right]+3H(\phi)P_{V}^{(\lambda)}=\lambda P_{V}^{(\lambda)}.\label{eq:FP V ti 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This linear equation can be integrated to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{V}^{(\lambda)}(\phi)=\frac{1}{v(\phi)}\exp\left[\int_{\phi_{0}}^{\phi}\frac{3H(\phi)-\lambda}{v(\phi)}d\phi\right],\label{eq:FP det sol 0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 is an integration constant.
 We note that the factors in the expression above have a clear physical
 interpretation: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\exp\left[\int_{\phi_{0}}^{\phi}\frac{3H(\phi)}{v(\phi)}d\phi\right]=\frac{\left[a(\phi)\right]^{3}}{\left[a(\phi_{0})\right]^{3}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a(\phi)\equiv\exp\left[\int_{\phi_{0}}^{\phi}\frac{H(\phi)}{\dot{\phi}_{\text{sr}}}d\phi\right]=\exp\left[\int H(t)dt\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 is the scale factor accumulated during the slow-roll evolution from 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

, while the integral
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{\phi_{0}}^{\phi}\frac{1}{v(\phi)}d\phi=\int_{\phi_{0}}^{\phi}\frac{d\phi}{\dot{\phi}_{\text{sr}}}=\int dt=t_{\text{sr}}(\phi)-t_{\text{sr}}(\phi_{0})
\end{equation}

\end_inset

yields the (deterministic) duration of time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{\text{sr}}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the slow-roll evolution.
 Hence we may write approximately
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{V}^{(\lambda)}(\phi)\approx\frac{\text{const}}{v(\phi)}\left[a(\phi)\right]^{3}e^{-\lambda t_{\text{sr}}(\phi)}.\label{eq:FP det sol}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that the analogous approximation for the comoving-volume FP equation
 will not contain the volume expansion factor 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we have entirely disregarded diffusion; in this approximation, the
 initial distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{V}(\phi,t=t_{0})$
\end_inset

 is shifted towards 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 without any spreading.
 If the initial distribution is concentrated at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{V}(\phi,t_{0})=\delta(\phi-\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

, the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{V}(\phi,t)$
\end_inset

 will remain a 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

-function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 at later times, meaning that the initial region with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 traverses the deterministic regime and reheats during a fixed time interval.
 In reality, fluctuations are small but present, so the traversal time 
\begin_inset Formula $t(\phi_{*})-t(\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 is a random variable that fluctuates around a certain mean value.
 This mean value is only 
\emph on
approximately
\emph default
 equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{\text{sr}}(\phi_{*})-t_{\text{sr}}(\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A more precise approximate method for determining the 
\emph on
comoving
\emph default
 distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,t)$
\end_inset

 in the deterministic regime was used in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Martin:2005ir,Gratton:2005bi,Martin:2005hb"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and consists of a perturbative expansion,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi(t)=\phi_{0}(t)+\delta\phi_{1}(t)+\delta\phi_{2}(t)+...,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is to be applied to the stochastic 
\emph on
Langevin
\emph default
 equation, rather than to the FP equation.
 The result is (at the lowest order) a Gaussian approximation with a time-depend
ent mean and variance
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Martin:2005ir"
literal "true"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P(\phi,t) & \approx\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma^{2}(t)}}\exp\left[-\frac{\left(\phi-\phi_{0}(t)\right)^{2}}{2\sigma^{2}(t)}\right],\label{eq:P Gaussian}\\
\sigma^{2}(t) & \equiv\frac{H^{\prime2}(\phi_{\text{sr}})}{\pi}\int_{\phi_{\text{sr}}}^{\phi_{\text{in}}}\frac{H^{3}}{H^{\prime3}}d\phi,\\
\phi_{0}(t) & \equiv\phi_{\text{sr}}(t)+\frac{H^{\prime\prime}}{2H^{\prime}}\sigma^{2}(t)+\frac{H^{\prime}}{4\pi}\left[\frac{H_{\text{in}}^{3}}{H_{\text{in}}^{\prime2}}-\frac{H^{3}}{H^{\prime2}}\right],
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{sr}}(t)$
\end_inset

 is the slow-roll trajectory and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{in}}$
\end_inset

 is the initial value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 While methods based on the Langevin equation do not take into account boundary
 conditions or volume weighting effects, the formula
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:P Gaussian"

\end_inset

) provides an adequate approximation to the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,t)$
\end_inset

 in a useful range of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, as shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Martin:2005hb"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 This formula shows how the initial distribution spreads and also gives
 a correction to the slow-roll traversal time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An analogous approximation for the deterministic regime can be developed
 also in the FP formalism, whose advantage over the Langevin description
 is that the boundary conditions as well as volume weighting can be taken
 into account.
 One notes that Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FP V"

\end_inset

) in the deterministic regime contains a small parameter (which is not the
 same as the slow-roll parameter), 
\begin_inset Formula $DH/v^{2}\ll1$
\end_inset

, and that the small parameter multiplies the highest-derivative term in
 that equation.
 Therefore, a WKB-like asymptotic perturbation theory can be applied.
 We will illustrate this technique by computing the volume-weighted average
 of the traversal time 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle t(\phi_{*})-t(\phi_{q})\right\rangle _{V}$
\end_inset

 spent in the deterministic regime, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{q}$
\end_inset

 is the approximate beginning of the deterministic regime and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 is the reheating boundary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The slow-roll conditions
