status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
slow-roll conditions
\end_layout

\end_inset

 can be rewritten in terms of the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\phi)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v(\phi)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $H(\phi)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|\frac{v}{H}\right|\ll1,\quad v'\ll H,\quad\frac{D'}{D}\ll\frac{H}{v}.\label{eq:SR conditions}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that the ratios 
\begin_inset Formula $H/v$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $D/v$
\end_inset

 of the kinetic coefficients are independent of the choice of time parametrizati
on.
 Therefore, below we will express all relevant results in terms of these
 gauge-independent ratios.
 In terms of the slow-roll parameters
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
slow-roll parameters
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon,\eta$
\end_inset

 as usually introduced, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varepsilon=\frac{1}{16\pi}\left(\frac{V'}{V}\right)^{2}=36\pi\left(\frac{v}{H}\right)^{2},\quad\eta=\frac{1}{8\pi}\frac{V''}{V}=\frac{3v'}{H}+\varepsilon.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Thus, the small quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $h/H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v'/H$
\end_inset

 are analogous to the slow-roll parameters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the deterministic regime where the random motion is negligible, we have
 additionally 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{DH}{v^{2}}\ll1.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Indeed, the observed primordial cosmological inhomogeneity of order 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-5}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
10^{-5}\sim\frac{H^{2}}{\dot{\phi}}\sim\left.\sqrt{\frac{DH}{v^{2}}}\right|_{\phi_{*}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Thus, the gauge-invariant combination 
\begin_inset Formula $DH/v^{2}$
\end_inset

 characterizing the relative importance of diffusion is of order 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-10}$
\end_inset

 during the last 60 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-foldings of inflation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Diffusion dominates for the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{DH}{v^{2}}\gg1.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Therefore, we may define the boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{q}$
\end_inset

 of the diffusion-dominated regime by an order-of-magnitude relation,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{DH}{v^{2}}\right|_{\phi_{q}}\sim1.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that the reheating boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 is also defined through an order-of-magnitude relation,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{v}{H}\right|_{\phi_{*}}\sim1.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For definiteness we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{q}<\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Since we are interested in describing the evolution only within the range
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 where self-reproduction is absent, we may impose boundary conditions at
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 that express the absence of diffusion at these points,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\partial_{\phi}\left(DP_{V}\right)\right|_{\phi=\phi_{q},\phi_{*}}=0.\label{eq:no diff BC}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

While these boundary conditions will distort the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{V}(\phi,t)$
\end_inset

 near the points 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{q},\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

, this distortion is negligible away from these points.
 Let us consider the Green's function 
\begin_inset Formula $G(\phi,\phi_{0},t)$
\end_inset

 for Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FP V"

\end_inset

) with the boundary conditions
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:no diff BC"

\end_inset

).
 The Green's function can be represented as the solution of Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FP V"

\end_inset

), (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:no diff BC"

\end_inset

) with the initial condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.G(\phi,\phi_{0},t)\right|_{t=0}=\delta(\phi-\phi_{0}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The Green's function 
\begin_inset Formula $G(\phi,\phi_{0},t)$
\end_inset

 can be visualized as the time-dependent volume distribution that results
 from an initial unit volume with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

.
 For the purposes of the present calculation we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 is near 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{q}$
\end_inset

 but not equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{q}$
\end_inset

.
 The infinitesimal probability of reaching 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 within the time interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[t,t+dt\right]$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v(\phi_{*})G(\phi_{*},\phi_{0},t)dt.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Additionally, we need to take into account that new regions are continuously
 injected at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 with exponentially growing volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\propto e^{\lambda t}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

We can calculate the infinitesimal probability of reaching 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 within the time interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[t,t+dt\right]$
\end_inset

 when starting within the time interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[t_{0},t_{0}+dt_{0}\right]$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v(\phi_{*})G(\phi_{*},\phi_{0},t-t_{0})dt\,dt_{0}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Thus, the average traversal time for regions that reached 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 within the time interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[t,t+dt\right]$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \Delta t\right\rangle =\frac{\int_{-\infty}^{t}dt_{0}\left(t-t_{0}\right)v(\phi_{*})G(\phi_{*},\phi_{0},t-t_{0})}{\int_{-\infty}^{t}dt_{0}v(\phi_{*})G(\phi_{*},\phi_{0},t-t_{0})}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The mean traversal time (which we have denoted for brevity by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \Delta t\right\rangle $
\end_inset

) is actually independent of the arrival time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 because, after the substitution 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{t}\equiv t-t_{0}$
\end_inset

, it can be identically rewritten as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \Delta t\right\rangle =\frac{\int_{0}^{\infty}\tilde{t}d\tilde{t}\,G(\phi_{*},\phi_{0},\tilde{t})}{\int_{0}^{\infty}d\tilde{t}\,G(\phi_{*},\phi_{0},\tilde{t})}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 It is convenient to introduce the Laplace transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(\phi,\phi_{0};\omega)\equiv\int_{0}^{\infty}d\tilde{t}\,G(\phi,\phi_{0},\tilde{t})e^{-\omega\tilde{t}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then the expectation value of the traversal time is found as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \Delta t\right\rangle =-\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial\omega}\right|_{\omega=0}\ln g(\phi_{*},\phi_{0};\omega).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 can be also used to estimate the spread of the traversal time,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \Delta t^{2}\right\rangle -\left\langle \Delta t\right\rangle ^{2}=\left.\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial\omega^{2}}\right|_{\omega=0}\ln g(\phi_{*},\phi_{0};\omega).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 By integrating Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FP V"

\end_inset

) with respect to time, one can derive the differential equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\phi;\omega)$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{\phi\phi}\left(Dg\right)-\partial_{\phi}\left(vg\right)+\left(3H-\omega\right)g=-\delta(\phi-\phi_{0}).\label{eq:g equ}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This equation is valid as long as the integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{\infty}G(\phi_{*},\phi_{0},t)e^{-\omega t}dt$
\end_inset

 converges, which is expected to be the case at least for all positive 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 since the range 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\phi_{q},\phi_{*}\right]$
\end_inset

 does not support self-reproduction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We find that the logarithmic generating function of traversal time is the
 Green's function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\phi,\phi_{0};\omega)$
\end_inset

 of the stationary FP equation with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 To obtain an analytic formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\phi,\phi_{0};\omega)$
\end_inset

, we apply the adiabatic approximation.
 It is convenient to change variables so that the term with first derivative
 vanishes from Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ"

\end_inset

).
 To this end, we introduce the auxiliary function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\phi,\phi_{0};\omega)$
\end_inset

 as follows,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(\phi,\phi_{0};\omega)=\frac{1}{D(\phi)}\exp\left[\frac{1}{2}\int_{\phi_{0}}^{\phi}\frac{v}{D}d\phi\right]f(\phi,\phi_{0};\omega).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\phi,\phi_{0};\omega)$
\end_inset

 is derived from Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ"

\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f^{\prime\prime}-\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{v}{D}\right)^{\prime}f-\frac{v^{2}}{4D^{2}}f+\frac{(3H-\omega)}{D}f=-D(\phi_{0})\delta(\phi-\phi_{0}),\label{eq:f equ}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we denote 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}\equiv\partial_{\phi}f$
\end_inset

 (the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 enter as parameters).
 We may rewrite Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:f equ"

\end_inset

) as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f^{\prime\prime}-Q^{2}(\phi)f & =-D(\phi_{0})\delta(\phi-\phi_{0}),\\
Q(\phi) & \equiv\sqrt{\frac{v^{2}}{4D^{2}}+\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{v}{D}\right)^{\prime}+\frac{\omega-3H}{D}}.\label{eq:Q def}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:f equ"

\end_inset

) contains only terms 
\begin_inset Formula $f''$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, we can now apply the WKB approximation.
 Due to Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SR conditions"

\end_inset

), the dominant term in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:f equ"

\end_inset

) is 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{2}/(4D^{2})$
\end_inset

, at least for moderate values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

; we recall that at the end of the calculation we will need to set 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=0$
\end_inset

 in order to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \Delta t\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \Delta t^{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the dominant eigenvalue of the FP equation in the entire inflationary
 range including self-reproduction.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is of order 
\begin_inset Formula $3H_{\max}^{\beta}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\max}$
\end_inset

 is the largest available value of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 However, even with 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\sim\lambda$
\end_inset

 the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega/D$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:f equ"

\end_inset

) is much smaller than the leading term 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{2}/(4D^{2})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{2}>0$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Q def"

\end_inset

).
 The WKB approximation gives the general solutions of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:f equ"

\end_inset

) away from 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 as a linear combination of growing and decaying exponentials,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(\phi)\approx\frac{C_{1}\exp\left[\int Q(\phi)d\phi\right]}{\sqrt{Q(\phi)}}+\frac{C_{2}\exp\left[-\int Q(\phi)d\phi\right]}{\sqrt{Q(\phi)}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The delta-function source in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:f equ"

\end_inset

) means that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lim_{\delta\phi\rightarrow0}\left[f^{\prime}(\phi_{0}+\delta\phi)-f^{\prime}(\phi_{0}-\delta\phi)\right]=-D(\phi_{0}).\label{eq:f prime cond}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since the boundary conditions fix the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\phi,\phi_{0};\omega)$
\end_inset

 at the endpoints 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

, it is clear that the correct solution is represented (with an exponentially
 good precision) by a growing exponential for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{q}<\phi<\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 and by a decaying exponential for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}<\phi<\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore we may write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f(\phi,\phi_{0};\omega) & \approx\frac{C_{0}}{\sqrt{Q(\phi)}}\exp\left[-\int_{\phi}^{\phi_{0}}Qd\phi\right],\quad\phi_{q}<\phi<\phi_{0};\\
f(\phi,\phi_{0};\omega) & \approx\frac{C_{0}}{\sqrt{Q(\phi)}}\exp\left[-\int_{\phi_{0}}^{\phi}Qd\phi\right],\quad\phi_{0}<\phi<\phi_{*}.
\end{align}

\end_inset

The value of the integration constant 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{0}$
\end_inset

 is fixed by the condition
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:f prime cond"

\end_inset

), which yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C_{0}=\frac{D(\phi_{0})}{2\sqrt{Q(\phi_{0})}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Using this value, the approximate solution 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\phi,\phi_{0};\omega)$
\end_inset

 can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & g(\phi,\phi_{0};\omega)\nonumber \\
 & \approx\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{\sqrt{Q(\phi_{0})Q(\phi)}}\frac{D(\phi_{0})}{D(\phi)}\exp\left[\frac{1}{2}\int_{\phi_{0}}^{\phi}\frac{v}{D}d\phi-\int_{\phi_{0}}^{\phi}Qd\phi\right].\label{eq:g approx 1}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We need to compute only the values 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\omega}\ln g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\omega}\partial_{\omega}\ln g$
\end_inset

, so the result
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g approx 1"

\end_inset

) can be simplified further.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is dominated by the term 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{2}/(4D^{2})$
\end_inset

, the exponential function in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g approx 1"

\end_inset

) contains a difference of almost equal terms.
 In order to compute the spread of the traversal time, we need to expand
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln g(\phi,\phi_{0};\omega)$
\end_inset

 up to terms quadratic in 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 To make expanding 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(\phi)$
\end_inset

 from Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Q def"

\end_inset

) easier, we rewrite
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
Q(\phi) & =\frac{v}{2D}\sqrt{1+\frac{4\omega D}{v^{2}}+2W(\phi)},\\
W(\phi) & \equiv\frac{v'D-D'v-6DH}{v^{2}},
\end{align}

\end_inset

where we introduced an auxiliary function 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\phi)$
\end_inset

 for convenience.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|W\right|\ll1$
\end_inset

 due to the slow-roll conditions and the smallness of diffusion, 
\begin_inset Formula $DH\ll v^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Neglecting terms quadratic in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 and in 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

, but keeping terms of order 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{2}$
\end_inset

, we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
Q(\phi) & \approx\frac{v}{2D}\left(1+W\right)+\frac{\omega}{v}\left(1-W\right)-\frac{\omega^{2}D}{v^{3}};\\
\ln\sqrt{Q} & \approx\frac{1}{2}\ln\frac{v}{2D}+\frac{W}{2}+\omega\frac{D}{v^{2}}\left(1-2W\right).
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, computing 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln g$
\end_inset

 from Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g approx 1"

\end_inset

) and expanding up to terms quadratic in 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

, we derive an approximate expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln g(\phi_{*},\phi_{0};\omega)$
\end_inset

.
 In that expression, we may neglect also the linear terms of order 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 when evaluated at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 (but not at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

).
 The result is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\ln g & (\phi_{*},\phi_{0};\omega)\approx\ln\frac{D(\phi_{0})}{v(\phi_{*})}-\frac{W(\phi_{0})+W(\phi_{*})}{2}+\int_{\phi_{0}}^{\phi_{*}}\frac{3H}{v}d\phi\nonumber \\
 & -\omega\frac{D(\phi_{0})}{v^{2}(\phi_{0})}-\omega\int_{\phi_{0}}^{\phi_{*}}\frac{d\phi}{v(\phi)}\left(1-W\right)+\omega^{2}\int_{\phi_{0}}^{\phi_{*}}\frac{D}{v^{3}}d\phi.
\end{align}

\end_inset

It follows that the expectation value of the traversal time is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left\langle \Delta t\right\rangle  & =-\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial\omega}\right|_{\omega=0}\ln g\nonumber \\
 & \approx\frac{D(\phi_{0})}{v^{2}(\phi_{0})}+\int_{\phi_{0}}^{\phi_{*}}\frac{d\phi}{v(\phi)}\left(1-W\right),\label{eq:delta t ans}
\end{align}

\end_inset

while the spread in the traversal time is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \Delta t^{2}\right\rangle -\left\langle \Delta t\right\rangle ^{2}=2\int_{\phi_{0}}^{\phi_{*}}\frac{D}{v^{3}}d\phi.\label{eq:Delta t sq ans}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the deterministic slow-roll traversal time (disregarding diffusion)
 would be
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta t_{\text{sr}}=\int_{\phi_{0}}^{\phi_{*}}\frac{d\phi}{v(\phi)}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 We have thus obtained 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \Delta t\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 up to the leading-order correction to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t_{\text{sr}}$
\end_inset

; a further development of adiabatic perturbation theory (using higher-order
 WKB approximation and further expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

) yields higher-order corrections to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t_{\text{sr}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The formula
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:delta t ans"

\end_inset

) shows that the traversal time is shortened when 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda>0$
\end_inset

.
 When this effect becomes large, one needs to take into account higher-order
 terms in 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

, which we have neglected in the present calculation; of course, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \Delta t\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 cannot actually become negative even at large 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As an example, we may estimate the mean traversal time and its spread in
 a model with 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\phi)=\frac{1}{2}m^{2}\phi^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[It turns out that the spread is always much smaller than the traversal
 time, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.]
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The regime of self-reproduction is located between the Planck boundary,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{Pl}}\sim m^{-1}$
\end_inset

, and the no-diffusion boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{q}\sim m^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

; inflation ends at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{*}\sim1$
\end_inset

 when the slow-roll condition is violated.
 Omitting constant factors of order 1, working in Planck units, and assuming
 
\begin_inset Formula $m\ll1$
\end_inset

, we estimate the kinetic coefficients as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h\sim m^{\beta}\phi^{\beta},\quad D\sim m^{2+\beta}\phi^{2+\beta},\quad v\sim-m^{\beta}\phi^{\beta-1}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The dominant eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is determined by the self-reproduction regime near the Planck boundary,
 thus we may set 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 to a constant value below the Planck scale, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\lesssim1$
\end_inset

.
 We are interested in the traversal time from 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}=\phi_{q}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}<\phi_{q}$
\end_inset

.
 Using Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:delta t ans"

\end_inset

) where we can disregard 
\begin_inset Formula $W\ll1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\lesssim\phi_{q}$
\end_inset

, we obtain the estimates 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left\langle \Delta t\right\rangle  & \sim m^{-\beta/2}+\max\left(m^{-\beta},m^{-1-\beta/2}\right)-\lambda\max\left(m^{2-2\beta},m^{-1-\beta}\right),\nonumber \\
\left\langle \Delta t^{2}\right\rangle -\left\langle \Delta t\right\rangle ^{2} & \sim\max\left(m^{2-2\beta},m^{-1-\beta}\right).
\end{align}

\end_inset

When 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta<-1$
\end_inset

, the term proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:delta t ans"

\end_inset

) dominates, and we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \Delta t\right\rangle <0$
\end_inset

, which means that the approximation used in the present calculation breaks
 down.
 Therefore, we only consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta>-1$
\end_inset

.
 By treating the cases 
\begin_inset Formula $-1<\beta<2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $2<\beta<3$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta>3$
\end_inset

 separately, one can show that the mean square spread of the traversal time,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\left\langle \Delta t\right\rangle ^{2}-\left\langle \Delta t\right\rangle ^{2}}$
\end_inset

, is always much smaller than the mean traversal time 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \Delta t\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $m\ll1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The approximations considered so far are applicable to the deterministic
 regime.
 An adiabatic approximation can be constructed also for the regime of high
 diffusion.
 We proceed as in the construction of the WKB approximation.
 Replacing for convenience 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta D$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is a formal parameter, we substitute into Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:stationary FP 1"

\end_inset

) the ansatz
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{V}^{(\lambda)}(\phi)=\exp\left[\frac{1}{\theta}\int^{\phi}\left(W_{0}(\phi)+\theta W_{1}(\phi)+\theta^{2}W_{2}+...\right)d\phi\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 and proceed to expand the result in powers of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 For the lowest terms, we obtain the equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
DW_{0}^{2}-vW_{0} & =0,\\
2D^{\prime}W_{0}+DW_{0}^{\prime}-v^{\prime}+3H-\lambda & =\left(2DW_{0}-v\right)W_{1},\\
D^{\prime\prime}+2D^{\prime}W_{1}+D(W_{1}^{2}+W_{1}^{\prime}) & =\left(2DW_{0}-v\right)W_{2},
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the prime stands for 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\phi}$
\end_inset

.
 We find two solutions, 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{0}=v/D$
\end_inset

.
 These two solutions correspond to the two independent WKB branches.
 The other equations can be solved straightforwardly for 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{2}$
\end_inset

, etc., in each branch separately.
 For instance, in the 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 branch we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
W_{1}=\frac{3H-\lambda-v^{\prime}}{v},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which reproduces the approximate solution
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FP det sol 0"

\end_inset

).
 This procedure will yield all other corrections in a systematic way.
