\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eternal points"

\end_inset

In this section we use the method of FP equations to solve the problem of
 determining whether eternal inflation is present in a given model of inflation
 of random-walk type.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The hallmark of eternal inflation is the unbounded growth the total number
 of independent inflating regions.
 The total proper 3-volume of the inflating domain also grows without bound
 at late times, at least when computed along hypersurfaces of equal proper
 time or equal scale factor.
 However, the proper 3-volume is a gauge-dependent quantity, and one may
 construct complete spacelike foliations whose 3-volume decreases with time
 even in an everywhere expanding universe
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2005ya"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Clearly, the volume growth computed using an 
\emph on
arbitrary
\emph default
 family of equal-time hypersurfaces cannot be used as a criterion for the
 presence of eternal inflation.
 However, a weaker condition is adequate: Eternal inflation is present if
 and only if there 
\emph on
exists
\emph default
 a choice of time slicing with an unbounded growth of the 3-volume of inflating
 domains.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Equivalently, eternal inflation is present if a finite comoving volume gives
 rise to infinite physical volume
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Tegmark:2004qd"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Thus, the presence or absence of eternal inflation is a gauge-
\emph on
independent
\emph default
 statement.
 One may, of course, use a particular gauge (such as the proper time or
 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-folding time) for calculations, since the result is known to be gauge-independe
nt.
 For instance, it can be shown that eternal inflation is present if and
 only if the 3-volume grows in the 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-folding time slicing
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2005ya"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another way to formulate the condition for the presence of eternal inflation
 is that an infinite number of reheated 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions may result from 
\emph on
finitely
\emph default
 many initially inflating 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions.
 It is then clear that the initial conditions for inflation cease to play
 a significant role in the resulting universe.
 As long as the spacetime contains even a single 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region that supports inflation, no matter how unlikely it is to realize
 the favorable initial conditions for inflation, an 
\emph on
infinite
\emph default
 number of reheated (and potentially inhabitable) 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions will be created to the future of the initial 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region.
 Assuming that there is a finite nonzero probability for the emergence of
 life in any reheated 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region, it follows that eternal inflation generates an infinite number
 of regions containing life.
 A non-inflating initial region in the spacetime will give rise at most
 to a finite number of inhabitable regions.
 In this sense, it may be said that the inhabitable parts of the universe
 are dominated by the products of eternal inflation, and that eternal inflation
 removes the problem of fine-tuning of the initial conditions for inflation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The presence of eternal inflation has been analyzed in many specific scenarios.
 For instance, eternal inflation is generic in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

chaotic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Linde:1984st,Linde:1986fc,Linde:1986fd"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

new
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vilenkin:1983xp"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 inflationary models.
 It is normally sufficient to establish the existence of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

diffusion-dominated
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 regime, that is, a range of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 where the typical amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\phi\sim H$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

jumps
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is larger than the typical slow-roll increment of the field, 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\phi}_{\text{sr}}\Delta t$
\end_inset

, during one Hubble time 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t=H^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 For models of scalar-field inflation, this condition is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H^{2}\gg\left|\frac{dH}{d\phi}\right|.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Such a range of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is present in most slow-roll models of inflation.
 (For an example of an inflationary scenario where eternal inflation is
 generically 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 present, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chen:2006hs"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.) The range of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 where diffusion dominates must be sufficiently wide to support eternal
 inflation; heuristically, 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions must not leave the diffusion-dominated range too efficiently.
 A strict formal criterion for the presence of eternal inflation is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}>0$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 is the largest eigenvalue of the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}^{\dagger}+3H(\phi)$
\end_inset

, as explained in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Methods-of-solution"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The causal structure of the eternally inflating spacetime and the topology
 of the reheating surface can be visualized using the construction of 
\series bold
eternal points
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
eternal points
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2001np"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Eternal points are comoving worldlines 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=\text{const}$
\end_inset

 that forever remain within the inflating domain, 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

they strictly 
\emph on
never
\emph default
 enter the reheating epoch.
 These worldlines correspond to places where the reheating surface reaches
 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\infty$
\end_inset

 in a spacetime diagram (see Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cap:reheating-surface-1"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will now show using topological arguments
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2001np"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 that the presence of inflating domains at arbitrarily late times entails
 the existence of infinitely many eternal points.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a non-vanishing, if small, probability that the entire comoving
 region will thermalize at a certain finite time, because fluctuations of
 the scalar field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 could have accidentally cooperated to drive 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 toward the end point of inflation 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 everywhere in the region.
 One could say in that case that eternal inflation has not been realized
 in that region.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Here we do not consider the possibility of spontaneous return of thermalized
 regions to inflation in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

recycling universe
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 scenarios
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Garriga:1997ef"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 or in the landscape of string theory.
 These features will be considered in the following chapter, in the framework
 of tunneling models.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If, on the other hand, eternal inflation has been realized, then for an
 arbitrarily late time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 there will be regions that are still inflating at that time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In that case, there must exist some comoving worldlines that never enter
 a thermalized domain.
 To demonstrate this, one could choose a monotonically increasing sequence
 of time instances, 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}=nH^{-1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0,1,2,...$
\end_inset

; for each 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 there must exist a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 surrounded by a horizon-sized domain that will be still inflating at time
 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 (As 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

 grows, these domains become progressively smaller in comoving coordinates,
 due to expansion of space.) An infinite sequence of points 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 on a finite (compact) comoving volume of 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

-dimensional space must have accumulation points, 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

there must be at least one point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{*}$
\end_inset

 such that any arbitrarily small (comoving) neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{*}$
\end_inset

 contains infinitely many points 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 from the sequence.
 It is clear that the comoving world-line at an accumulation point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{*}$
\end_inset

 cannot reach thermalization at any finite time: if it did, there would
 exist a comoving neighborhood around 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{*}$
\end_inset

 which thermalized at that time, and this contradicts the construction of
 the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, accumulation points 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{*}$
\end_inset

 are eternal points, and we may define the set 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 of all such points, as a set drawn on the spatial section of the comoving
 volume at initial time.
 (One could also imagine an infinitely dense grid of comoving world-lines
 starting at the initial surface, with the set 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 consisting of all world-lines that never reach thermalization.) As we have
 shown, eternal points exist, 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

the set 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 for a comoving region is not empty, if eternal inflation has been realized
 in that region.
 However, it is important to note that the 3-volume of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is equal to zero (
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 has measure zero).
 This is the same as to say that a randomly chosen point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 will reach reheating with probability 1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Different histories and different choices of the initial comoving volume
 will generate different sets 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is a stochastically generated set, one may characterize it probabilistically,
 by finding probabilities for the set 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 to have certain properties.
 The underlying stochastic process is the random walk of the inflaton 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and, since it is a stationary stochastic process that does not explicitly
 depend on time, probabilities of any properties of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 depend only on 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, below we will denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 the probability of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 being non-empty if the initial comoving 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region has a given value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 of the inflaton field.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
During stochastic evolution, there will be (infinitely many) times when
 the inflaton returns to the value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 in some horizon-sized domain; each time the distribution of properties
 of the subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 within those domains will be the same as that for the whole set 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 In this way, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 naturally acquires fractal structure.
 The fractal dimension of this set can be understood as the fractal dimension
 of the inflating domain
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Aryal:1987vn,Winitzki:2001np,Winitzki:2005ya"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and is invariant under any 
\emph on
smooth
\emph default
 coordinate transformations in the spacetime
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2001np"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fractal set 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 can be thought of as an infinite-time limit of the (fractal) inflating
 domain considered in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Aryal:1987vn,Vilenkin:1992uf,Linde:1993xx"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Since the 3-volume of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 vanishes, we need a slightly different definition of fractal dimension
 than that of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Aryal:1987vn"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The definition of fractal dimension we would like to use is the so-called
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

box fractal dimension
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, which in our case is equivalent to the Hausdorff-Besicovitch fractal dimension
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Feder:1988:F"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
box fractal dimension
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
box fractal dimension
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is defined for a non-empty subset 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of a finite region of a 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

-dimensional space.
 Rectangular coordinates are chosen in the region to divide it into a regular
 lattice of 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

-dimensional cubes with side length 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

.
 (The cubical shape of the lattice is not essential to the definition of
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

box fractal dimension
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.) Then, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

coarse-grained volume
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(l\right)$
\end_inset

 of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is defined as the total volume of all cubes of the lattice that contain
 at least one point from the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 If the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 has fractal dimension less than 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, one expects 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(l\right)$
\end_inset

 to decay at 
\begin_inset Formula $l\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 as some power of 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

.
 The fractal dimension is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\textrm{dim}S=d-\lim_{l\rightarrow0}\frac{\ln V\left(l\right)}{\ln l}.\label{eq:fd-def}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For example, if the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 consists of a finite number of line segments, then the coarse-grained volume
 at scale 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 will be equal to the volume of narrow tubes of width 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 surrounding the line segments
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Definition-of-fractal-dim"

\end_inset

