\begin_layout Subsection
A nonlinear diffusion equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Xequ"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Eternal points are generated by the same stochastic process that drives
 eternal inflation.
 The existence of eternal points can be used as another gauge-invariant
 criterion for the presence of eternal inflation.
 In this section we will give an introduction to the methods developed by
 the author for the analysis of this issue.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our focus is the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\phi)$
\end_inset

 of having at least one eternal point in an initial Hubble-size region where
 the field has value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 As we will now show, this probability satisfies the equation
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This equation was first derived in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2001np"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 A similar equation was recently rederived using a different approach in
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dubovsky:2008rf"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{L}_{\phi}X-3H\left(1-X\right)\ln\left(1-X\right)=0\label{eq:X equ 00}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with zero boundary conditions, 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\phi_{*})=0$
\end_inset

 at the reheating boundary and 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\phi_{\text{P}}=0)$
\end_inset

 at the Planck boundary (if any).
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{L}_{\phi}\equiv D(\phi)\partial_{\phi\phi}+v(\phi)\partial_{\phi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 is the Fokker–Planck operator used in the 
\emph on
backward
\emph default
 FP equation.
 Note that Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ 00"

\end_inset

) is nonlinear due to the presence of the logarithmic term; this equation
 is of reaction-diffusion type.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We remark that 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\phi)\equiv0$
\end_inset

 is trivially a solution of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ 00"

\end_inset

).
 However, this solution is not physically relevant if eternal inflation
 is present, since in that case the probability of having eternal points
 is certainly nonzero.
 As will be demonstrated below, the presence of eternal inflation is 
\emph on
equivalent
\emph default
 to the existence of a nontrivial solution 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\phi)\not\equiv0$
\end_inset

 of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ 00"

\end_inset

).
 We will begin by deriving that equation and showing its independence of
 time parametrization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It will be convenient to work with the complementary probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}\left(\phi\right)=1-X\left(\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 and to use the proper time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 as the time variable.
 We recall that the random walk of the inflaton field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is described by a Langevin equation which can be written as a difference
 equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Langevin FD"

\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi\left(t+\Delta t\right)=\phi\left(t\right)+v\left(\phi\right)\Delta t+\xi\sqrt{2D\left(\phi\right)\Delta t}.\label{eq:lang}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The evolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 in a horizon-size domain with field value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 gives rise to independent random walks of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 in each of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

daughter
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 horizon-size subdomains that were formed out of the original domain.
 After one 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-folding, 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

after time 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t=H^{-1}$
\end_inset

, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $N\equiv\exp\left(3H\Delta t\right)\approx20$
\end_inset

 daughter subdomains of approximately horizon size.
 The stochastic process corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 assigns a probability density 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(\xi_{1},...,\xi_{N}\right)d\xi_{1}...d\xi_{N}$
\end_inset

 for various sets of values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{i}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,...,N$
\end_inset

) in the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 daughter subdomains.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}(\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 of having 
\emph on
no
\emph default
 eternal points in the region is equal to the probability of having no eternal
 points in any of its 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 daughter subdomains.
 The evolution in inflating daughter subdomains proceeds independently,
 so the probability of having no eternal points in each of them is described
 by the same function 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}\left(\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 evaluated at new values 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(t+\Delta t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 (Although the daughter subdomains have slightly varying 
\begin_inset Formula $H\left(\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 and are not exactly of horizon size, the correction due to this is negligible.)
 This argument gives an integral equation,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \bar{X}\left(\phi_{0}\right)=\int d\xi_{1}...d\xi_{N}P\left(\xi_{1},...,\xi_{N}\right)\nonumber \\
 & \times\prod_{i=1}^{N}\bar{X}\left(\phi_{0}+v\left(\phi_{0}\right)\Delta t+\xi_{i}\sqrt{2D\left(\phi_{0}\right)\Delta t}\right).\label{eq:xd1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Here we use the Ito interpretation of the Langevin equation, where 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 are evaluated at the initial point of the step, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since correlations between different daughter subdomains are small, we can
 approximate the probability density of 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{i}$
\end_inset

 by a product of independent identical distributions, 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(\xi_{1},...,\xi_{N}\right)=P\left(\xi_{1}\right)\cdots P\left(\xi_{N}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:xd1"

\end_inset

) becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{X}\left(\phi_{0}\right)=\left[\int d\xi P\left(\xi\right)\bar{X}\left(\phi_{0}+v\Delta t+\xi\sqrt{2D\Delta t}\right)\right]^{\exp\left(3H\Delta t\right)}.\label{eq:xd2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Rather than trying to solve Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:xd2"

\end_inset

), we consider its limit for small values of 
\begin_inset Formula $H\Delta t$
\end_inset

.
 Although the Langevin description of the random walk given by Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lang"

\end_inset

) is valid only for times 
\begin_inset Formula $H\Delta t\gtrsim1$
\end_inset

, we will formally consider it to be valid at all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 and take a partial derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial/\partial\Delta t$
\end_inset

 of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:xd2"

\end_inset

) at 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t=0$
\end_inset

.
 The same formal limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 is used to derive the FP equations in the stochastic approach of inflation,
 and the same limits of validity apply to the new nonlinear diffusion equation
 that will result from the present argument.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We find
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\partial\bar{X}\left(\phi_{0}\right)}{\partial\Delta t} & =0=3H\bar{X}\ln\bar{X}\nonumber \\
 & +\lim_{\Delta t\to0}\int d\xi P\left(\xi\right)\frac{d\bar{X}\left(\phi_{0}+v\Delta t+\xi\sqrt{2D\Delta t}\right)}{d\phi}\nonumber \\
 & \times\left(v+\frac{\xi\sqrt{2D}}{2\sqrt{\Delta t}}\right).
\end{align}

\end_inset

We now expand 
\begin_inset Formula $d\bar{X}/d\phi$
\end_inset

 in Taylor series around 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 and use the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 is a normalized random variable,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int d\xi P\left(\xi\right)=1,\quad\left\langle \xi\right\rangle =0,\quad\left\langle \xi^{2}\right\rangle =1,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

to obtain an equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D\frac{d^{2}\bar{X}}{d\phi^{2}}+v\frac{d\bar{X}}{d\phi}+3H\bar{X}\ln\bar{X}=0.\label{eq:Xequ}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Xequ"

\end_inset

) is equivalent to Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ 00"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation needs to be supplemented with suitable boundary conditions
 at end of inflation and/or at Planck boundaries.
 For a region which is near the end of inflation 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

, the probability of having eternal points is zero, so 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\phi_{*})=0$
\end_inset

.
 Domains reaching Planck boundaries 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{P}}$
\end_inset

 disappear from consideration, so we may assume that they will not contain
 eternal points and set 
\begin_inset Formula $X=0$
\end_inset

 at those boundaries.
 Physically meaningful solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\phi)$
\end_inset

 have the meaning of probability and so should vary between 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the additional requirements are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0\leq X(\phi)\leq1;\quad X(\phi_{*})=0;\quad X(\phi_{\text{P}})=0.\label{eq:XequBC}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is straightforward to verify that Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Xequ"

\end_inset

), unlike previous FP equations, is a gauge-invariant equation.
 A change of time variable, 
\begin_inset Formula $t\to t'$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $dt'/dt=T\left(t,\phi\right),$
\end_inset

 will divide the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $D\left(\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v\left(\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 as well as the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $3H\left(\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

growth
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 term by 
\begin_inset Formula $T\left(t,\phi\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This extra factor 
\begin_inset Formula $T\left(t,\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 cancels and thus Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Xequ"

\end_inset

) remains unchanged.
 This feature is to be expected since the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}\left(\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 is defined in a gauge-invariant way and should be described by a gauge-invarian
t equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An analogous nonlinear diffusion equation can be derived for models of inflation
 with multiple scalar fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{k}$
\end_inset

, namely
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D\frac{\partial}{\partial\phi^{k}}\frac{\partial\bar{X}}{\partial\phi_{k}}+v_{k}\frac{\partial\bar{X}}{\partial\phi_{k}}+3H\bar{X}\ln\bar{X}=0,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v_{k}\left(\phi\right)\equiv-\frac{1}{4\pi}\frac{\partial H}{\partial\phi^{k}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

are the new drift coefficients (in the proper time gauge).
 Boundary conditions will be 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}\left(\phi\right)=1$
\end_inset

 along thermalization boundaries and Planck boundaries (if any).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The qualitative behavior of the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}\left(\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 for a chaotic type inflationary model is illustrated in Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:xplot"

\end_inset

.
 An approximate WKB solution in the fluctuation-dominated regime can be
 obtained if we disregard the drift term 
\begin_inset Formula $v\left(\phi\right)\bar{X}'$
\end_inset

 and write an ansatz
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{X}\left(\phi\right)=Ae^{-W\left(\phi\right)},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is approximately constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is a slowly changing function, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|W''\right|\ll(W')^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\phi)$
\end_inset

 then satisfies approximately the equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D\left(W'\right)^{2}-3HW=0.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The solution is
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $6\pi^{2}$
\end_inset

, which corrects a misprint in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
