\begin_layout Subsection
The existence of solutions of nonlinear equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is not easy to demonstrate directly the existence of nontrivial solutions
 of reaction-diffusion equations such as Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Xequ"

\end_inset

).
 However, there is a connection between solutions of such nonlinear equations
 and solutions of the linearized equations.
 Rigorous results are available in the mathematical literature on nonlinear
 functional analysis and bifurcation theory.
 In this and the following sections we will present the techniques that
 can be applied to Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Xequ"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For convenience, here we will use the 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-folding time parametrization, which is the same as rewriting Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Xequ"

\end_inset

) as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{D}{H}\bar{X}_{,\phi\phi}+\frac{v}{H}\bar{X}_{,\phi}+3\bar{X}\ln\bar{X}=0.\label{eq:X equ phi 01}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We begin with a heuristic argument; a rigorous demonstration will follow.
 Let us consider the situation when eternal inflation is barely allowed.
 One will then expect that the probability of having eternal points is very
 small, 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

there exists a nontrivial solution of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ phi 01"

\end_inset

) that approximately satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}(\phi)\approx1$
\end_inset

.
 The solution can be linearized in the neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}\approx1$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}=1-\chi(\phi)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi(\phi)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the linear FP equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\hat{L}+3\right]\chi=0,\quad\hat{L}\equiv\frac{D}{H}\partial_{\phi\phi}+\frac{v}{H}\partial_{\phi}.\label{eq:chi equ}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The FP operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}+3$
\end_inset

 is adjoint to the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\hat{L}^{\dagger}+3\right]P\equiv\partial_{\phi\phi}\left(\frac{D}{H}P\right)-\partial_{\phi}(\frac{v}{H}P)+3P,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which enters the FP equation for the 3-volume distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi,t)$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-folding time parametrization.
 If eternal inflation is allowed in a given model, the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}^{\dagger}+3$
\end_inset

 has a positive eigenvalue.
 The largest eigenvalue of that operator is zero in the borderline case
 when eternal inflation is just about to set in.
 The spectrum of the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}+3$
\end_inset

 is the same as that of the adjoint operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}^{\dagger}+3$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, in the borderline case the largest eigenvalue of the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}+3$
\end_inset

 will be zero, and there will exist a nontrivial, everywhere nonnegative
 solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi$
\end_inset

 of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:chi equ"

\end_inset

).
 Thus, heuristically one can expect that a nontrivial solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}(\phi)\not\equiv1$
\end_inset

 will exist away from the borderline case, 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

when the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}+3$
\end_inset

 has a positive eigenvalue.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following the approach of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Creminelli:2008es"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, one can imagine a family of inflationary models parametrized by a label
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, such that eternal inflation is allowed when 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega<1$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=1$
\end_inset

 is a borderline case (called a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

phase transition
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 point in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Creminelli:2008es"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 Then Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ phi 01"

\end_inset

) will have only the trivial solution, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}(\phi)\equiv1$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 The case 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=1$
\end_inset

 where eternal inflation is on the borderline of existence is the 
\emph on
bifurcation point
\emph default
 for the solutions of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ phi 01"

\end_inset

).
 At the bifurcation point, a nontrivial solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}(\phi)\not\equiv1$
\end_inset

 appears, branching off from the trivial solution.
 A rigorous theory of bifurcation can be developed using methods of nonlinear
 functional analysis (see 
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

chapter 9 of the book
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Stakgold:1979:GF"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 In this chapter we will prove that a nontrivial solution of a nonlinear
 equation, such as Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ phi 01"

\end_inset

), exists if and only if the dominant eigenvalue of the linearized operator
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}+3$
\end_inset

 with zero boundary conditions is positive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we establish the necessary condition: The largest eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}+3$
\end_inset

 with zero boundary conditions is positive if a nontrivial solution of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ phi 01"

\end_inset

) exists.
 The sufficient condition and the uniqueness of the solution of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ phi 01"

\end_inset

) requires a more involved analysis and will be proved in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Sufficient-condition"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is a nontrivial solution of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ phi 01"

\end_inset

).
 The spectrum of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}^{\dagger}+3$
\end_inset

 is bounded from above, and there exists an eigenfunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(\phi)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}^{\dagger}\psi=\gamma\psi$
\end_inset

 with zero boundary conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(\phi_{1})=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(\phi_{2})=0$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is the largest eigenvalue.
 We need to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma>0$
\end_inset

.
 It is known that the eigenfunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is everywhere positive, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(\phi)>0$
\end_inset

, as a ground state of a self-adjoint operator.
 Then the following integral must be positive, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I_{1}\equiv\int_{\phi_{1}}^{\phi_{2}}\left(1-\bar{X}\left(\phi\right)\right)\psi\left(\phi\right)d\phi>0.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 are left and right boundaries, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}>\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma=\frac{1}{I_{1}}\int_{\phi_{1}}^{\phi_{2}}\left(1-\bar{X}\right)[\hat{L}^{\dagger}+3]\psi\,d\phi,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

we would obtain the desired inequality 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma>0$
\end_inset

 if we prove that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I_{2}\equiv\int_{\phi_{1}}^{\phi_{2}}\left(1-\bar{X}\right)[\hat{L}^{\dagger}+3]\psi\,d\phi>0.\label{eq:hitr}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Integrating Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:hitr"

\end_inset

) by parts and using boundary conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}\left(\phi_{1,2}\right)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(\phi_{1,2})=0$
\end_inset

, we find
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
I_{2} & =\int_{\phi_{1}}^{\phi_{2}}\psi\,[\hat{L}+3]\left(1-\bar{X}\right)d\phi+\left.D\left(\phi\right)\psi\frac{d\bar{X}}{d\phi}\right|_{\phi_{1}}^{\phi_{2}}\nonumber \\
 & =\int_{\phi_{1}}^{\phi_{2}}\psi\,[\hat{L}+3]\left(1-\bar{X}\right)d\phi.
\end{align}

\end_inset

Using Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ phi 01"

\end_inset

), we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & [\hat{L}+3]\left(1-\bar{X}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =-\frac{D}{H}\bar{X}_{,\phi\phi}-\frac{v}{H}\bar{X}_{,\phi}+3\left(1-\bar{X}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =3\left(1-\bar{X}+\bar{X}\ln\bar{X}\right)\geq0.
\end{align}

\end_inset

It follows that the integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int\psi\,[\hat{L}+3]\left(1-\bar{X}\right)d\phi$
\end_inset

 is positive: its integrand is nonnegative and not everywhere zero.
 This proves Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:hitr"

\end_inset

), so 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 must be positive.
 This concludes the proof of the necessary condition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There remains a technical difference between the eigenvalue problem for
 the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}+3$
\end_inset

 with 
\emph on
zero
\emph default
 boundary conditions and the same eigenvalue problem with the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

no-diffusion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 boundary conditions normally used in the stochastic approach,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial\phi}\right|_{\phi_{*}}\left[D(\phi)P(\phi)\right]=0.\label{eq:no diff bc}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It was also demonstrated in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2001np"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 that the eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}+3$
\end_inset

 with the boundary conditions
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:no diff bc"

\end_inset

) is positive if a nontrivial solution of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ 00"

\end_inset

) exists.
 In principle, the eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}+3$
\end_inset

 with zero boundary conditions is not the same as the eigenvalue of the
 same operator with the boundary conditions
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:no diff bc"

\end_inset

).
 One can have a borderline case when one of these two eigenvalues is positive
 while the other is negative.
 In this case, the two criteria for the presence of eternal inflation (based
 on the positivity of the two different eigenvalues) will disagree.
 However, the alternative boundary conditions are imposed at reheating,
 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

in the regime of very small fluctuations where the value of the eigenfunction
 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is exponentially small compared with its values in the fluctuation-dominated
 range of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, the difference between the two eigenvalues is always exponentially
 small (it is suppressed at least by the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-3N}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-foldings in the deterministic slow-roll regime before reheating).
 Therefore, we may interpret the discrepancy as a limitation inherent in
 the stochastic approach to inflation.
 In other words, one cannot use the stochastic approach to establish the
 presence of eternal inflation more precisely than with the accuracy 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-3N}$
\end_inset

.
 Barring an extremely fine-tuned borderline case, this accuracy is perfectly
 adequate for establishing the presence or absence of eternal inflation.
\end_layout

