 monotonically grows, and also 
\begin_inset Formula $h(X)/X$
\end_inset

 decreases monotonically for all relevant 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, while
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sup_{X\in\left(0,1\right)}\frac{h(X)}{X}=3+A.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Under these numerous conditions, we can demonstrate the existence and uniqueness
 of positive solutions using techniques of nonlinear functional analysis
 (see chapter
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

9 of the book 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Stakgold:1979:GF"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first rewrite Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ rewritten"

\end_inset

) as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X=[-\hat{L}+A]^{-1}h(X)\equiv\hat{T}[X],\label{eq:X equ T}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $[-\hat{L}+A]^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is the Green's function of the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $-\hat{L}+A$
\end_inset

 with zero boundary conditions at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}^{(1,2)}$
\end_inset

.
 We have introduced the nonlinear operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ T"

\end_inset

) in order to exhibit the iteration structure, 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\hat{T}[X]$
\end_inset

, of this equation.
 We will now demonstrate the existence and uniqueness of positive solutions
 to this equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea of the construction is to find an initial function 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}>0$
\end_inset

 such that the consecutive iterations of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ T"

\end_inset

) yield an 
\emph on
increasing
\emph default
 sequence of functions, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{n+1}(\phi)=\hat{T}[X_{n}]$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{n+1}\geq X_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 To compare functions, let us write for brevity 
\begin_inset Formula $f\geq g$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\phi)\geq g(\phi)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\in(\phi_{*}^{(1)},\phi_{*}^{(2)})$
\end_inset

.
 We will also show that the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{n}$
\end_inset

 is bounded from above and hence has a limit, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\infty}(\phi)$
\end_inset

, which is a solution of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ T"

\end_inset

).
 Then we will prove that this solution is unique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we note that the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

monotonically increasing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the sense that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}[f]\geq\hat{T}[g]$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\geq g$
\end_inset

.
 This property can be verified by considering 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{T}[f]-\hat{T}[g]=[-\hat{L}+A]^{-1}(h(f)-h(g)).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)$
\end_inset

 monotonically grows (by construction) for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $h(f)-h(g)>0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $f>g$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, the Green's function 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{L}(\phi,\phi')$
\end_inset

 of the positive operator 
\begin_inset Formula $-\hat{L}+A$
\end_inset

 is positive, 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{L}(\phi,\phi')>0$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
[-\hat{L}+A]^{-1}f(\phi)=\int d\phi^{\prime}G_{L}(\phi,\phi^{\prime})f(\phi')>0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

if 
\begin_inset Formula $f>0$
\end_inset

.
 To demonstrate that 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{L}>0$
\end_inset

, we first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{L}$
\end_inset

 cannot be equal to zero except at the boundaries.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{L}(\phi,\phi')=0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi'=\phi_{1}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 within the open interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi_{*}^{(1)},\phi_{*}^{(2)})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{L}(\phi,\phi_{1}^{\prime})$
\end_inset

 for fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi'=\phi_{1}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 can be thought of as a solution of the equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
[-\hat{L}+A]\,G_{L}(\phi,\phi_{1}^{\prime})=\delta(\phi-\phi')\label{eq:Gl def}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with boundary conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{L}(\phi_{*}^{(1,2)},\phi_{1}^{\prime})=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{L}(\phi_{1},\phi_{1}^{\prime})=0$
\end_inset

.
 One of the intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}\equiv(\phi_{*}^{(1)},\phi_{1})$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}\equiv(\phi_{1},\phi_{*}^{(2)})$
\end_inset

 does not contain 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us, without loss of generality, assume that it is 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}$
\end_inset

 that does not contain 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{L}(\phi,\phi_{1}^{\prime})$
\end_inset

 satisfies a homogeneous equation,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
[-\hat{L}+A]\,G_{L}(\phi,\phi_{1}^{\prime})=0,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with zero boundary conditions at the boundaries of the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Any such solution would be an eigenfunction of 
\begin_inset Formula $-\hat{L}+A$
\end_inset

 with zero boundary conditions at the boundaries of 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 However, the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $-\hat{L}+A$
\end_inset

 has all positive eigenvalues with zero boundary conditions on the interval
 
\begin_inset Formula $(\phi_{*}^{(1)},\phi_{*}^{(2)})$
\end_inset

 while its eigenvalues with zero boundary conditions on a smaller interval
 are strictly larger.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $-\hat{L}+A$
\end_inset

 has no zero eigenfunctions, so 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{L}(\phi,\phi_{1}^{\prime})=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\in I_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 However, 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{L}(\phi,\phi_{1}^{\prime})$
\end_inset

 is a solution of second-order differential equation and so cannot be identicall
y equal to zero throughout an 
\emph on
interval
\emph default
 of values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{L}$
\end_inset

 has the same sign and is nonzero everywhere.
 It remains to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{L}$
\end_inset

 is everywhere positive rather than everywhere negative.
 The positivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{L}$
\end_inset

 follows if we consider the eigenfunction 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}(\phi)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $-\hat{L}+A$
\end_inset

 with the smallest eigenvalue, which is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma+A$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
[-\hat{L}+A]\,f_{0}(\phi)=\left(\gamma+A\right)f_{0}(\phi).\label{eq:eigenfunction f0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Such an eigenfunction 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}(\phi)$
\end_inset

 can be chosen everywhere positive and is nondegenerate.
 Now we need to choose a different scalar product in the space of functions,
 in such a way that the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 is self-adjoint
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
self-adjointness
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle f_{1},f_{2}\right\rangle \equiv\int_{\phi_{*}^{(1)}}^{\phi_{*}^{(2)}}d\phi\,f_{1}(\phi)f_{2}(\phi)\frac{1}{M(\phi)},\label{eq:scalar product for adjoint}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is defined by Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:scalar product M def"

\end_inset

).
 Taking this scalar product of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{L}(\phi,\phi')$
\end_inset

 and using Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Gl def"

\end_inset

), we find 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left\langle \left(\gamma+A\right)f_{0},G_{L}\right\rangle  & =\langle(-\hat{L}+A)\,f_{0},G_{L}\rangle\nonumber \\
 & =\langle f_{0},(-\hat{L}+A){\,G}_{L}\rangle\nonumber \\
 & =\int_{\phi_{*}^{(1)}}^{\phi_{*}^{(2)}}\negmedspace f_{0}(\phi)\delta(\phi-\phi')d\phi=f_{0}(\phi')>0.
\end{align}

\end_inset

Since the integral of 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{L}$
\end_inset

 with a positive function 
\begin_inset Formula $(\gamma+A)f_{0}$
\end_inset

 is positive, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{L}(\phi,\phi')>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, we need to find an initial function 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}(\phi)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}[X_{0}]\geq X_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 This function can be chosen as 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta f_{0}(\phi)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta>0$
\end_inset

 is a sufficiently small constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is the positive eigenfunction satisfying Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eigenfunction f0"

\end_inset

).
 Then we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h(\beta f_{0})=K(\beta f_{0})+A\beta f_{0}=\left[K^{\prime}(0)+A\right]\beta f_{0}+O(\beta^{2}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We may choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 sufficiently small so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta f_{0}<1$
\end_inset

 and that the terms 
\begin_inset Formula $O(\beta^{2})$
\end_inset

 in the above equation are negligible; then we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{T}[\beta f_{0}]=[-\hat{L}+A]^{-1}h(\beta f_{0})\approx\frac{K^{\prime}(0)+A}{\gamma+A}\beta f_{0}>\beta f_{0},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we used the relationships 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K^{\prime}(0)=3=\sup_{x\in(0,1)}\frac{K(x)}{x}\equiv\gamma_{*}>\gamma.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that the coincidence of the values 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{\prime}(0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{*}$
\end_inset

 is related to the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $K(x)/x$
\end_inset

 is monotonically decreasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 starting from 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having found 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}\equiv\beta f_{0}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}[X_{0}]>X_{0}$
\end_inset

 and using the increasing property of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}$
\end_inset

, we find that the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{n+1}\equiv\hat{T}[X_{n}]$
\end_inset

 is increasing, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{n+1}>X_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We need to prove that the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{n}$
\end_inset

 is bounded from above.
 Consider the constant function 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\phi)=1$
\end_inset

; it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $[-\hat{L}+A]c=Ac$
\end_inset

 for any constant 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $[-\hat{L}+A]^{-1}c=A^{-1}c$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{T}[1]=[-\hat{L}+A]^{-1}h(1)=1.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}$
\end_inset

 is an increasing operator, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}<1$
\end_inset

, it follows by induction that all 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{n}<1$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{n}$
\end_inset

 has a limit, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\infty}(\phi)$
\end_inset

, since that sequence is increasing and bounded from above.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\infty}(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is a solution of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\infty}=\hat{T}[X_{\infty}]$
\end_inset

 and hence is a positive solution of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:nl-1"

\end_inset

) that never reaches 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Uniqueness of this positive solution can be demonstrated as follows.
 First we note that the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\infty}(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is the 
\emph on
minimal
\emph default
 positive solution; for suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is any solution, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is positive since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f=[-\hat{L}+A]^{-1}h(f)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

while 
\begin_inset Formula $h(f)>0$
\end_inset

 and the Green's function is also positive.
 Then we can show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f>\beta f_{0}$
\end_inset

 for sufficiently small 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 A positive solution 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\phi)$
\end_inset

 cannot have zero derivatives and at the same time zero values at the boundaries.
 Hence, the derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 are nonzero at the boundaries.
 Then there exists a sufficiently small 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f>\beta f_{0}\equiv X_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows from 
\begin_inset Formula $f>X_{0}$
\end_inset

 and from the increasing property of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{T}[f]>\hat{T}[X_{0}]\equiv X_{1}$
\end_inset

, and so by induction 
\begin_inset Formula $f>X_{n}$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $f\geq X_{\infty}$
\end_inset

; in other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 is the minimal positive solution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It remains to show that there are no other positive solutions larger than
 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\infty}(\phi)$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 are two different positive solutions such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}>f_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 is self-adjoint with respect to the scalar product
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:scalar product for adjoint"

\end_inset

), we can perform the following computation,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
0 & =\langle\hat{L}f_{1},f_{2}\rangle-\langle f_{1},\hat{L}f_{2}\rangle=-\left\langle {K(f}_{1}),f_{2}\right\rangle +\left\langle f_{1},K(f_{2})\right\rangle \nonumber \\
 & =\int_{\phi_{*}^{(1)}}^{\phi_{*}^{(2)}}\frac{d\phi}{M(\phi)}f_{1}f_{2}\left(\frac{K(f_{2})}{f_{2}}-\frac{K(f_{1})}{f_{1}}\right).
\end{align}

\end_inset

This is a contradiction since 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}>f_{1}$
\end_inset

 while the function 
\begin_inset Formula $K(x)/x$
\end_inset

 is strictly monotonically decreasing for all relevant 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

, so the last integrand is everywhere positive.
 Therefore, we cannot have another solution 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f>X_{\infty}$
\end_inset

, so the positive solution 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 is unique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conclusion is that Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:nl-1"

\end_inset

) has unique positive solutions not reaching 
\begin_inset Formula $X=1$
\end_inset

 as long as the largest eigenvalue of the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}^{\dagger}+3$
\end_inset

 with zero boundary conditions is positive.
 This eigenvalue is exponentially close to the lowest eigenvalue of the
 operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}^{\dagger}+3$
\end_inset

 with boundary conditions
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:no diff bc"

\end_inset

).
 The proof depends on certain technical properties of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

 defined by Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:K for X equ"

\end_inset

), namely 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K(0)=K(1)=0,\quad K^{\prime}(0)=3=\sup_{x\in(0,1)}\frac{K(x)}{x},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

on the monotonic behavior of 
\begin_inset Formula $K(x)/x$
\end_inset

, and on the fact that solutions do not reach 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\phi)=1$
\end_inset

 and so there exists a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x)\equiv K(x)+Ax$
\end_inset

 is a monotonically increasing function for all relevant values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

