\begin_layout Standard
A compelling question in the context of eternal inflation is how to make
 statistical predictions of observed parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a}$
\end_inset

 in theories where the values of these parameters are stochastically distributed
 in the spacetime.
 As discussed in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Physical-relevance"

\end_inset

, considerations of this type necessarily involve some form of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

principle of mediocrity.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The approach taken so far is to attempt to predict the probability distribution
 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\chi_{a})$
\end_inset

 of measuring 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a}$
\end_inset

 for a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

randomly chosen
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 observer, and subsequently compare the observed actual value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a}$
\end_inset

 with the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\chi_{a})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In inflationary cosmology, observers appear only near the reheating surface
 in spacetime.
 If eternal inflation is present, the reheating surface contains infinitely
 many causally disconnected and (possibly) statistically inequivalent domains.
 Thus, in the context of eternal inflation there is no naturally defined
 mathematical measure on the set of all observers since it is a countably
 infinite set.
 Hence, one needs an 
\emph on
ad hoc
\emph default
 prescription in order to 
\emph on
define
\emph default
 the probability distribution.
 We call such a prescription an 
\series bold
observer-based measure
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
observer-based measure
\end_layout

\end_inset

, as is now common in the cosmological literature.
 On a more formal level, one needs to consider the ensemble of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

possible observers
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and to define a probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\chi_{a})$
\end_inset

 for quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a}$
\end_inset

 that have different values on different observers from this ensemble.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Existing proposals for an observer-based measure fall in two major classes,
 which may be designated as 
\series bold
