 This prescription in most cases does not require a cutoff since the number
 of observers along a single comoving worldline is almost surely finite.
 Therefore, we will refer to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 worldline-based measure rather than distinguish between different versions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A principal difference between the worldline-based and volume-based measures
 is in their dependence on the initial state.
 When considering the volume-based measure, one starts from a finite initial
 spacelike 3-volume and restricts attention to the comoving future of that
 initial region.
 (Final results are insensitive to the choice of this 3-surface in spacetime
 or to its geometry.) The initial state consists of the initial values of
 the fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a}$
\end_inset

 within the initial volume, and possibly a label 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the type of the initial bubble.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Naturally, it is assumed that the initial state is in the self-reproduction
 regime: For random-walk type models, the initial 3-volume is undergoing
 inflation rather than reheating and, for tunneling models, the initial
 3-volume is not situated within a terminal bubble.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 When considering the worldline-based measure, one also assumes knowledge
 of these data at the initial point of a worldline.
 It turns out that the worldline-based measure always yields results that
 depend sharply on the initial state (except for the case of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

nonterminal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 landscape, 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

a landscape scenario without terminal vacua).
 A theory of initial conditions is necessary to obtain a specific prediction
 from the worldline-based measure.
 In contrast, probabilities obtained using any of the volume-based measures
 are always independent of the initial conditions.
 This agrees with the concept of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stationarity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of a self-reproducing universe as discussed in the earlier works 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Linde:1993nz,Linde:1993xx,Garcia-Bellido:1994ci,Vilenkin:1995yd"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 where it was proposed that the universe as a whole forgets the initial
 state and continues forever producing reheated regions and inflating in
 a self-similar way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At this time, there is no consensus as to which of the two classes of measures
 is the physically relevant one.
 I regard the two measures as reasonable answers to 
\emph on
different
\emph default
 questions.
 The first question is to determine the probability distribution for observed
 values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a}$
\end_inset

, given that the observer is randomly chosen from all the observers present
 in the entire spacetime.
 Since we have no knowledge as to our position in the spacetime, the total
 duration of inflation in our past, or the total number of bubble nucleations
 preceding the most recent one, it appears reasonable to include in the
 ensemble all the observers that will ever appear anywhere in the spacetime.
 An answer to the first question is thus provided by a volume-based measure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second question is posed in a rather different manner.
 In the context of tunneling-type eternal inflation, upon discovering the
 type of our bubble we may wish to leave a message to a future civilization
 that may arise in our place after an unspecified number of consecutive
 bubble nucleations.
 The analogous situation in the context of random-walk type inflation is
 a hypothetical observer located within an inflating region of spacetime
 who wishes to communicate with future civilizations that will eventually
 appear when inflation is finished in that region.
 The only available means of communication is by leaving a message in a
 sealed box.
 The message might contain the probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\chi_{a})$
\end_inset

 for parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{a}$
\end_inset

 that we expect the future civilization to observe.
 In this case, the initial state is 
\emph on
known
\emph default
 at the time of writing the message.
 It is clear that the message can be discovered only by future observers
 near the worldline of the box.
 It is then natural to consider the ensemble of observers appearing along
 that worldline; this ensemble certainly depends on the initial state, 
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

on the nucleation rates of various bubbles in the initial bubble.
 In that case, the correct message to be left in the box is 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\chi_{a})$
\end_inset

 computed according to the worldline-based measure with the known initial
 state.
 It is natural in that case that 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\chi_{a})$
\end_inset

 depends on the initial state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Calculations using the worldline-based measure usually do not require regulariza
