\begin_layout Standard
One way to choose between the competing measure prescriptions is to examine
 their predictions for various paradoxical answers.
 At least two sources of problems for the measure prescriptions have been
 uncovered (for more discussion, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Aguirre:2006ak"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One possible problem is the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

youngness
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 paradox
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Linde:1994gy,Vilenkin:1998kr,Tegmark:2004qd,Bousso:2007nd"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 It is manifested in some volume-based measures, notably in the equal-time
 cutoff by proper time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, by the predominance of universes where inflation ended very recently
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Tegmark:2004qd"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Indeed, a tiny and improbable fluctuation that delays reheating by a time
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t$
\end_inset

 is rewarded by a huge additional expansion factor, 
\begin_inset Formula $\propto\exp\left(3H_{\text{big}}\delta t\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\text{big}}$
\end_inset

 is a fiducial value of the highest Hubble rate available in the model.
 While 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\text{big}}$
\end_inset

 must be below the Planck scale 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\text{P}}$
\end_inset

, values such as 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\text{big}}\approx10^{-6}M_{\text{P}}$
\end_inset

 are already sufficient to predict that the most likely temperature of the
 CMB is much higher than the observed 
\begin_inset Formula ${2.7}^{\circ}$
\end_inset

K.
 For this reason, measure prescriptions exhibiting the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

youngness
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 paradox are considered to be unsatisfactory.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Generically, every equal-time cutoff suffers from the youngness paradox
 because of the dependence on the delay time 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t$
\end_inset

 inherent in the probability distribution obtained from the FP equation.
 Interestingly, it was found that the scale factor cutoff has a negligible
 youngness bias 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeSimone:2008if,DeSimone:2008bq"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 In order to cure the equal-time cutoff from the youngness paradox, a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stationarity measure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 was proposed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Linde:2007nm"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

-prescription 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vilenkin:1995yd"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, the spherical cutoff 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vilenkin:1998kr"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 as well as the comoving cutoff 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Garriga:2005av"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and the RV measure 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2008yb"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 are also free from the youngness paradox.
 Worldline-based measures 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bousso:2006ev"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 by construction cannot suffer from the youngness paradox.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another pathology that appears in the results of several measure prescription
 is the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Boltzmann brain
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problem
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dyson:2002pf,Albrecht:2004ke,Page:2006dt,Linde:2006nw,Bousso:2006xc,Vilenkin:2006qg,Page:2006ys,Bousso:2007nd,Gott:2008ii"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The root of the problem is the thermal property of de Sitter space that
 behaves as a thermal bath
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gibbons:1977mu"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 with the Gibbons-Hawking temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\frac{1}{2\pi}H$
\end_inset

.
 Thermal fluctuations are able to produce any classical system, for instance,
 an Earth-like planet with observers on it, with an exceedingly small but
 
\emph on
nonzero
\emph default
 probability per unit spacetime 4-volume.
 Such rare events will nevertheless occur in eternally inflating de Sitter
 spacetime, somewhere in the infinite interior of every recyclable bubble.
 Hence, one can expect that infinitely many observers will be created who
 do not see a universe full of galaxies around them, but instead find themselves
 surrounded by empty de Sitter space.
 An extreme case is an isolated brain nucleating out of thermal fluctuations
 in empty space (a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Boltzmann brain
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 It appears reasonable to reject a multiverse measure that predicts a large
 probability of us being Boltzmann brains rather than ordinary observers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
