\begin_layout Plain Layout
In many cosmological scenarios the fundamental theory does not predict with
 certainty the values of observable cosmological parameters, such as the
 effective cosmological constant and the masses of elementary particles.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A common feature of these cosmological models is the presence of 
\emph on
eternal inflation
\emph default
, 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

the absence of a global end to inflation in the entire spacetime (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Linde:1993xx,Guth:2000ka,Winitzki:2006rn"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for reviews).
 Eternal inflation gives rise to infinitely many causally disconnected regions
 of the spacetime where the cosmological observables may have significantly
 different values.
 In the context of the string-theoretic landscape, eternal inflation entails
 the nucleation of (potentially) infinitely many nested bubbles of different
 vacuum types.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The program outlined in the early works
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Garcia-Bellido:1994ci,Vilenkin:1994ua,Vilenkin:1995yd"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, which dealt with eternal inflation of random walk type, was to calculate
 the probability distribution of the cosmological parameters as measured
 by an observer randomly located in the spacetime.
 The main difficulty in obtaining such probability distributions is due
 to the infinite volume of regions where an observer may be located.
 An eternally inflating universe contains an infinite, inhomogeneous, and
 topologically complicated spacelike hypersurface (the reheating surface)
 where observers may be expected to appear with a constant density per unit
 3-volume.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the landscape scenarios, one encounters a kind of infinity that is in
 some sense more ill-behaved than in the random-walk inflationary scenarios.
 Not only each pocket universe may contain infinitely many observers, but
 also the number of different pocket universes in the entire spacetime is
 infinite.
 Pocket universes of different types are not statistically equivalent to
 each other because they have different rates of nucleation of other pocket
 universes.
 There seems to be no natural ordering on the set of all pocket universes
 throughout the spacetime, since most of the pocket universes are spacelike
 separated.
 To emphasize the mutual causal independence of pocket universes, one calls
 such a spacetime a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

multiverse.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In summary, eternal inflation is a stochastic process that generates a topologic
ally complicated and noncompact locus of points where observers may appear.
 A 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

random location
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of an observer within that locus is a mathematically undefined concept,
 similarly to the concept of an integer number 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

uniformly chosen
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 among all the integers, or a real number 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

uniformly chosen
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 among all the reals.
 This is the root cause of the technical and conceptual difficulties known
 collectively as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

measure problem
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in multiverse cosmology (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Guth:2000ka,Aguirre:2006ak,Winitzki:2006rn,Vilenkin:2006xv,Guth:2007ng,Linde:2007nm"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for reviews).
 Nevertheless, one may try to formulate a prescription for calculating probabili
ties of observer-based events.
 Such a prescription, also called a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

measure,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 should in some sense correspond to the intuitive notion of probability
 of observation at a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

random
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 location in the spacetime.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As I described in the previous chapters, eternal inflation gives rise to
 infinitely many causally disconnected regions of the spacetime where the
 cosmological observables may have significantly different values.
 One hopes to obtain probability distribution of the cosmological parameters
 as measured by an observer randomly located in the spacetime.
 The main difficulty in obtaining such probability distributions is due
 to the infinite volume of regions where an observer may be located.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the universe is cold and empty during inflationary evolution, observers
 may appear only after reheating.
 The standard cosmology after reheating is tightly constrained by current
 experimental knowledge.
 Hence, the average number of observers produced in any freshly-reheated
 spatial domain is a function of cosmological parameters in that domain.
 Calculating that function is, in principle, a well-defined astrophysical
 problem that does not involve any infinities.
 Therefore we focus on the problem of obtaining the probability distribution
 of cosmological observables at reheating.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set of all spacetime points where reheating takes place is a spacelike
 three-dimensional hypersurface
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Borde:1993xh,Vilenkin:1995yd,Creminelli:2008es"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 called the 
\series bold
reheating surface
\series default

\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
reheating surface
\end_layout

\end_inset

 in spacetime.
 The hallmark feature of eternal inflation is that a 
\emph on
finite
\emph default
, initially inflating spatial 3-volume typically gives rise to a reheating
 surface having an 
\emph on
infinite
\emph default
 3-volume (see Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cap:reheating-surface-1"

\end_inset

).
 The geometry and topology of the reheating surface is quite complicated.
 For instance, the reheating surface contains infinitely many future-directed
 spikes around never-thermalizing comoving worldlines or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

eternal points
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2001np,Winitzki:2005fy,Vanchurin:2006xp"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 It is known that the set of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spikes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 has a well-defined fractal dimension that can be computed in the stochastic
 approach.
 Since the reheating surface is a highly inhomogeneous, noncompact 3-manifold
 without any symmetries, the notion of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

random location
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on such a surface is mathematically ill-defined.
 This feature of eternal inflation is at the root of the technical and conceptua
l difficulties known collectively as the measure problem.
