\begin_layout Standard
To motivate the RV measure, we first visualize the measure problem as follows.
 It is convenient to consider an initial inflating spacelike region 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of horizon size (an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) and the portion 
\begin_inset Formula $R\equiv R(S)$
\end_inset

 of the reheating surface that corresponds to the comoving future of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 If the 3-volume of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 were finite, the volume-weighted average of any observable quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 at reheating would be defined simply by averaging 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle Q\right\rangle \equiv\frac{\int_{R}Q\sqrt{\gamma}d^{3}x}{\int_{R}\sqrt{\gamma}d^{3}x},\label{eq:Q average}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is the induced metric on the 3-surface 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 This would have been the natural prescription for the observer-based average
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

; all higher moments of the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle Q^{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle Q^{3}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, etc., would have been well-defined as well.
 However, in the presence of eternal inflation
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Various equivalent conditions for the presence of eternal inflation were
 examined in more detail in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Presence-of-eternal"

\end_inset

.
 Here I adopt the condition that 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is nonzero for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 in the inflating range.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 the 3-volume of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is infinite with a nonzero probability 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the initial value of the inflaton field at 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 has been computed in slow-roll inflationary models
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2001np"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 where typically 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\phi_{0})\approx1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 not too close to reheating.
 In other words, the volume of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is infinite with a probability close to 1.
 In that case, the straightforward average
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Q average"

\end_inset

) of a fluctuating quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $Q(x)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is mathematically undefined since 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{R}\sqrt{\gamma}d^{3}x=\infty$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{R}Q\sqrt{\gamma}d^{3}x=\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The average 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle Q\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 can be computed only after imposing a volume cutoff on the reheating surface,
 making its volume finite in a controlled way.
 What has become known in cosmology as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

measure problem
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is the difficulty of coming up with a physically motivated cutoff prescription
 (informally called a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

measure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) that makes volume averages 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle Q\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 well-defined.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Volume cutoffs are usually implemented by restricting the infinite reheating
 domain 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 to a large but finite subdomain having a volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

.
 Then one defines the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

regularized
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q|\mathcal{V})$
\end_inset

 of an observable 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 by gathering statistics about the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 over the finite volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

.
 More precisely, 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q|\mathcal{V})\mathcal{V}dQ$
\end_inset

 is the 3-volume of regions (within the finite domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

) where the observable 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 has values in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[Q,Q+dQ\right]$
\end_inset

.
 The final probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q)$
\end_inset

 is then defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(Q)\equiv\lim_{\mathcal{V}\rightarrow\infty}p(Q|\mathcal{V}),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

provided that the limit exists.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A cutoff prescription is a specific choice of the compact subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 and of the way 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 approaches infinity when the cutoff is removed.
 Several cutoffs have been proposed in the literature, differing in the
 choice of the compact subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 and in the way 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 approaches infinity.
 It has been found early on (
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Linde:1993xx,Vilenkin:1995yd"
literal "true"

\end_inset

) that probability distributions, such as 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q)$
\end_inset

, depend sensitively on the choice of the cutoff.
 This is the root of the measure problem.
 Since a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

natural
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 mathematically consistent definition of the measure is absent, one judges
 a cutoff prescription viable if its predictions are not obviously pathological.
 Possible pathologies include the dependence on choice of spacetime coordinates
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:1995pg,Linde:1995uf"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

youngness paradox
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Linde:1994gy,Vilenkin:1998kr"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Boltzmann brain
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problem
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dyson:2002pf,Albrecht:2004ke,Page:2006dt,Linde:2006nw,Vilenkin:2006qg,Page:2006ys,Bousso:2007nd,Gott:2008ii"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The presently viable cutoff proposals fall into two rough classes that may
 be designated as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

worldline-based
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

volume-based
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 measures (a more fine-grained classification of measure proposals can be
 found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Aguirre:2006ak,Vanchurin:2006xp"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

worldline
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

holographic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 measure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bousso:2006ev,Bousso:2006ge"
literal "true"

\end_inset

