\begin_layout Standard
In the RV cutoff, the reheating surface is not being restricted to an artificial
ly chosen domain.
 Instead, one simply selects only those initial regions 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 that, 
\emph on
by rare chance
\emph default
, evolve into compact reheating surfaces 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 having a finite, fixed volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Vol}(R)=\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

.
 The ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal E}_{\mathcal{V}}$
\end_inset

 of such initial regions 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a nonempty subset of the ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal E}$
\end_inset

 of all initial regions 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 The volume-weighted probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q|{\cal E}_{\mathcal{V}})$
\end_inset

 of a cosmological observable 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 in the ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal E}_{\mathcal{V}}$
\end_inset

 can be determined through ordinary sampling of the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 over the finite volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

.
 The RV cutoff defines the probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q)$
\end_inset

 as the limit of 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q|{\cal E}_{\mathcal{V}})$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, provided that the limit exists.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To develop an approach for practical computations in the RV cutoff, let
 us first consider the probability density 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi_{0})d\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 of having 
\emph on
finite
\emph default
 volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Vol}(R)\in[\mathcal{V},\mathcal{V}+d\mathcal{V}]$
\end_inset

 of the reheating surface 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 that results from a single 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region with initial value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 This distribution is normalized to the probability of the event 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Vol}(R)<\infty$
\end_inset

, namely
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{0}^{\infty}\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi_{0})d\mathcal{V}=\textrm{Prob}\left(\text{Vol}(R)<\infty\right)=1-X(\phi_{0}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The probability density 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 is nonzero since 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\phi_{0})<1$
\end_inset

.
 I call this 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

finitely produced reheated volume
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (FPRV) distribution.
 This and related distributions constitute the mathematical basis of the
 RV cutoff.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Below I will use the Fokker–Planck (or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

diffusion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) formalism to derive equations from which the FPRV distributions can be
 in principle computed for models of slow-roll inflation with a single scalar
 field.
 Generalizations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 to multiple-field or non-slow-roll models are straightforward since the
 Fokker–Planck formalism is already developed in those contexts (
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Helmer:2006tz,Tolley:2008na"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now define the FPRV distribution for some cosmological observable
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 at reheating.
 Consider the probability density 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V},\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}};\phi_{0},Q_{0})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}$
\end_inset

 are values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 in the initial 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 is the total reheating volume, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}$
\end_inset

 is the portion of the reheating volume where the observable 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 has a particular value 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{R}$
\end_inset

.
 The distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V},\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}};\phi_{0},Q_{0})$
\end_inset

 as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}$
\end_inset

 at fixed and large 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 is sharply peaked around a mean value 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \left.\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}\right|_{\mathcal{V}}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 corresponding to the average volume of regions with 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=Q_{R}$
\end_inset

 within the total reheated volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, although the full distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V},\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}};\phi_{0},Q_{0})$
\end_inset

 could be in principle determined, it suffices to compute the mean value
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \left.\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}\right|_{\mathcal{V}}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 One can then expect that the limit 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(Q_{R})\!\equiv\!\lim_{\mathcal{V}\rightarrow\infty}\!\frac{\left\langle {\!\left.\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}\right|}_{\mathcal{V}}\right\rangle }{\mathcal{V}}\!=\!\lim_{\mathcal{V}\rightarrow\infty}\!\!\frac{\!\int_{0}^{\infty}\!\!\rho\left(\mathcal{V},\mathcal{V}_{Q};\phi_{0},Q_{0}\right)\!\mathcal{V}_{Q}d\mathcal{V}_{Q}}{\mathcal{V}\,\mbox{Prob}(\text{Vol}(R)=\mathcal{V})}\label{eq:pQ RV}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

exists and is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 (Below I will justify this statement more formally.) The function 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q_{R})$
\end_inset

 is then interpreted as the mean fraction of the reheated volume where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=Q_{R}$
\end_inset

.
 In this way, the RV cutoff yields the volume-weighted distribution for
 any cosmological observable 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 at reheating.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To obtain a more visual picture of the RV cutoff, consider a large number
 of initially identical 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions having different evolution histories to the future.
 A small subset of these initial 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions will generate 
\emph on
finite
\emph default
 reheating surfaces.
 An even smaller subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions will have the total reheated volume equal to a given value 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

.
 Conditioning on a finite value 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 of the reheating volume, one obtains a well-defined statistical ensemble
 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\mathcal{V}}$
\end_inset

 of initial 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions.
 For large 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

, the ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\mathcal{V}}$
\end_inset

 can be pictured as a set of initial 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions that happen to be located very close to some eternally inflating
 worldlines but do not actually contain any such worldlines (see Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cap:reheating-surface-2"

\end_inset

).
 In this way, the ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\mathcal{V}}$
\end_inset

 samples the total reheating surface near the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spikes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 where an infinite reheated 3-volume is generated from a finite initial
 3-volume.
 It is precisely near these 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spikes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that one would like to sample the distribution of observable quantities
 along the reheating surface.
 Therefore, one expects that the ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\mathcal{V}}$
\end_inset

 (in the limit of large 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

) provides a representative sample of the infinite reheating surface, despite
 the small probability of the event 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Vol}(R)=\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

.
 In this sense, the ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\mathcal{V}}$
\end_inset

 at large 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 is designed to yield a controlled approximation to the infinite reheating
 surfaces 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
