\begin_layout Standard
The RV cutoff proposed here has several attractive features.
 By construction, the RV cutoff is coordinate-invariant; indeed, only the
 intrinsically defined 3-volume within the reheating surface 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is used, rather than the 3-volume within a coordinate-dependent 3-surface.
 The results of the RV cutoff are also independent of initial conditions.
 This independence is demonstrated more formally below and can be understood
 heuristically as follows.
 The evolution of regions 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 conditioned on a large (but finite) value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Vol}(R)$
\end_inset

 is dominated by trajectories that spend a long time in the high-
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 inflationary regime and thereby gain a large volume.
 These trajectories forget about the conditions at their initial points
 and establish a certain equilibrium distribution of values of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 on the reheating surface.
 Hence, one can expect that the distribution of observables within the reheating
 domain 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 will be independent of the initial conditions in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

youngness paradox
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 arises in some volume-based prescriptions because 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions with delayed reheating are rewarded by an exponentially large additiona
l volume expansion.
 However, the RV measure groups together the 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions that produce 
\emph on
equal
\emph default
 final reheated volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

; a delay in reheating is not rewarded but suppressed by the small probability
 of a quantum fluctuation at the end of inflation.
 Therefore, most of these 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions have 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

normal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 slow-roll evolution before reheating.
 For this reason, the youngness paradox is absent in the RV measure.
 A more explicit calculation confirming this conclusion will be given in
 Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:RV-cutoff-for-landscape"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
RV cutoff in slow-roll inflation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a first specific application, I implement the RV measure in a slow-roll
 inflationary model with a scalar inflaton 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and the action
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S=\int\left[-\frac{R}{16\pi G}+\frac{1}{2}\left(\partial_{\mu}\phi\right)^{2}-V(\phi)\right]\sqrt{-g}d^{4}x.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We recapitulate the main assumptions of the stochastic approach to inflation.
 If the energy density is dominated by the potential energy 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\phi)$
\end_inset

, the Hubble expansion rate 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is approximately given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H\approx\sqrt{\frac{8\pi G}{3}V(\phi)}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the stochastic approach to inflation, the semiclassical dynamics of the
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 averaged over an 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region is a superposition of a deterministic motion with velocity 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{\phi}=v(\phi)\equiv-\frac{1}{4\pi G}H_{,\phi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 and a random walk with root-mean-squared step size
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sqrt{\left\langle \delta\phi\right\rangle ^{2}}=\frac{H(\phi)}{2\pi}\equiv\sqrt{\frac{2D(\phi)}{H(\phi)}},\quad D\equiv\frac{H^{3}}{8\pi^{2}},\label{eq:D def}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

during time intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t=H^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 A convenient description of the evolution of the field at time scales 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t\lesssim H^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi(t+\delta t)=\phi(t)+v(\phi)\delta t+\xi(t)\sqrt{2D(\phi)\delta t},\label{eq:phi delta t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi(t)$
\end_inset

 is (approximately) a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

white noise
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 variable, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \xi\right\rangle =0,\quad\left\langle \xi(t)\xi(t')\right\rangle =\delta(t-t'),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is statistically independent for different 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions.
 This stochastic process describes the evolution 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(t)$
\end_inset

 along a single comoving worldline.
 For convenience, we assume that inflation ends in a given 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region when 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 reaches a fixed value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider an ensemble of initial 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{2}$
\end_inset

, ..., where the inflaton field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous and has value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 within the inflationary regime.
 Following the spacetime evolution of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 in each of the regions 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{j}$
\end_inset

 along comoving geodesics, we arrive at reheating surfaces 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{j}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Most of the surfaces 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{j}$
\end_inset

 will have infinite 3-volume; however, some (perhaps small) subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{j}$
\end_inset

 will have finite 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

-dependent probability, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}(\phi_{0})\equiv1-X(\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

, of having a finite volume of 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{j}$
\end_inset

 is a solution of the gauge-invariant equation (see Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Presence-of-eternal"

\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D(\phi)\bar{X}_{,\phi\phi}+v(\phi)\bar{X}_{,\phi}+3H(\phi)\bar{X}\ln\bar{X}=0,\label{eq:X equ 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the boundary conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}(\phi_{*})=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}(\phi_{\text{Pl}})=1$
\end_inset

 at reheating and at Planck boundaries.
 While 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}(\phi)\equiv1$
\end_inset

 is always a solution of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ 1"

\end_inset

), the existence of a nontrivial solution with 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\bar{X}(\phi)<1$
\end_inset

 indicates the possibility of eternal inflation.
 The gauge invariance of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ 1"

\end_inset

) is manifest since a change of the time variable, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(t)\equiv\int^{t}T(\phi)dt$
\end_inset

, results in dividing the three coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $D,v,H$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\phi)$
\end_inset

, which leaves Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ 1"

\end_inset

) unchanged.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The finitely-produced volume distribution is defined as the conditional
 probability
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rho def"

\end_inset

) and can be expressed using 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}(\phi)$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho(V;\phi_{0})=\lim_{dV\rightarrow0}\frac{\mbox{Prob}\left(V(R)\in\left[V,V+dV\right]\right)}{dV}\frac{1}{\bar{X}(\phi_{0})},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we explicitly introduced the dependence on the initial value of the
 inflaton, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

, in the initial spatial region.
 By construction, the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(V;\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 is normalized,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int\rho(V,\phi_{0})dV=1.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 can be found by considering a suitable generating function.
 Let us
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
 measure 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 in units of the Hubble 3-volume 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{*}^{-3}$
\end_inset

 at reheating
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Here we assume that the value 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{*}$
\end_inset

 is the same in all reheating regions.
 A varying 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{*}$
\end_inset

 can be implemented
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
 at the cost of complicating the equations
\end_layout

\end_inset

 by defining the generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z,\phi_{0})=\left\langle e^{-zVH^{3}(\phi_{0})}\right\rangle _{V<\infty}$
\end_inset

 instead of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g def"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 and
\end_layout

\end_inset

 define the generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
averaging over events with finite 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(z;\phi_{0})\equiv\left\langle e^{-z\mathcal{V}}\right\rangle _{\mathcal{V}<\infty}\equiv\int_{0}^{\infty}\negthickspace e^{-z\mathcal{V}}\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi_{0})d\mathcal{V}.\label{eq:g def}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

(Note that the formal parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 has the dimension of inverse volume.
 The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 can be made dimensionless by a trivial rescaling which we omit.) The function
 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 is analytic in 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 and has no singularities for 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Re}\,z\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Moments of the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 are determined as usual through derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V},\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 itself can be reconstructed through the inverse Laplace transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Above we assumed that the value 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{*}$
\end_inset

 is the same in all reheating regions.
 A varying 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{*}$
\end_inset

 can be allowed if one defines the generating function by 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z,\phi_{0})=\left\langle e^{-zVH^{3}(\phi_{0})}\right\rangle _{V<\infty}$
\end_inset

 instead of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g def"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 has the following multiplicative property: For two statistically independent
 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions that have initial values 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{2}$
\end_inset

 respectively, the sum of the (finitely produced) reheating volumes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}_{1}+\mathcal{V}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is distributed with the generating function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle e^{-z(\mathcal{V}_{1}+\mathcal{V}_{2})}\right\rangle \!=\!\left\langle e^{-z\mathcal{V}_{1}}\right\rangle \!\left\langle e^{-z\mathcal{V}_{2}}\right\rangle \!=\!g(z;\phi_{1})g(z;\phi_{2}).\label{eq:g multiplicative}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This multiplicative property is the only assumption in the derivation of
 Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ 1"

\end_inset

).
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the same equation (we drop the subscript 0 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Dg_{,\phi\phi}+vg_{,\phi}+3Hg\ln g=0.\label{eq:g equ}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The boundary condition at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi_{*})=e^{-zH^{-3}(\phi_{*})}$
\end_inset

 since an 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 is already reheating and has volume 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{-3}(\phi_{*})$
\end_inset

.
 The boundary condition at the Planck boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{Pl}}$
\end_inset

 (or other boundary where the effective field theory breaks down) is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

absorbing,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

we assume that regions with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{\text{Pl}}$
\end_inset

 disappear and never generate any reheating volume: 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi_{\text{Pl}})=e^{z\cdot0}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 enters Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ"

\end_inset

) as a parameter and only through the boundary conditions.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 the solution of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ"

\end_inset

) is 
\begin_inset Formula $g(0;\phi)=\bar{X}(\phi)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Explicit approximate solutions of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ"

\end_inset

) can be obtained using the methods developed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2001np"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now consider FPRV distributions of cosmological parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 The generating function for the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V},\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}};\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 discussed above is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{g}(z,q;\phi,Q)\equiv\!\iint\!e^{-z\mathcal{V}-q\mathcal{V}_{Q}}\rho(\mathcal{V},\mathcal{V}_{Q};\phi,Q)d\mathcal{V}d\mathcal{V}_{Q}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z,q;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 is derived similarly to Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ"

\end_inset

) and is of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{\phi}\tilde{g}_{,\phi\phi}+D_{Q}\tilde{g}_{,QQ}+v_{\phi}\tilde{g}_{,\phi}+v_{Q}\tilde{g}_{,Q}+3H\tilde{g}\ln\tilde{g}=0,\label{eq:g equ 2 fields}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\phi},D_{Q},v_{\phi},v_{Q}$
\end_inset

 are the suitable kinetic coefficients representing the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

diffusion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and the mean 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

drift velocity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 The boundary condition at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{g}(z,q;\phi_{*},Q)=\exp\left[-\left(z+q\delta_{QQ_{R}}\right)H^{-3}(\phi_{*})\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where we use the delta-symbol defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{QQ_{R}}=1$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 belongs to a narrow interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[Q_{R},Q_{R}+dQ\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{QQ_{R}}=0$
\end_inset

 otherwise.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To obtain the distribution
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pQ RV"

\end_inset

), we need to compute the average 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \left.\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}\right|_{\mathcal{V}}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 at fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

.
 We define the auxiliary generating function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h(z;\phi,Q)\!\equiv\!\left\langle \mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}e^{-z\mathcal{V}}\right\rangle \!_{\mathcal{V}<\infty}\!=-\tilde{g}_{,q}(z,q=0;\phi,Q).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}(z,q=0;\phi,Q)=g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

.
 The equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $h(z;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 then follows from Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ 2 fields"

\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{\phi}h_{,\phi\phi}+D_{Q}h_{,QQ}+v_{\phi}h_{,\phi}+v_{Q}h_{,Q}+3H\left(\ln g+1\right)h=0.\label{eq:h equ}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This 
\emph on
linear
\emph default
 equation contains as a coefficient the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

, which is the solution of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ"

\end_inset

).
 The boundary condition for Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:h equ"

\end_inset

) is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h(z;\phi_{*},Q)=e^{-zH^{-3}(\phi_{*})}H^{-3}(\phi_{*})\delta(Q-Q_{R}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Here we can use the ordinary 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

-function instead of the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{QQ_{R}}$
\end_inset

 because the 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

-function enters linearly into the boundary condition.
 An appropriate rescaling of the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 by the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $dQ$
\end_inset

 is implied when we pass from 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{QQ_{R}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(Q-Q_{R})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, the expectation value 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \left.\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}\right|_{\mathcal{V}}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 at a fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 and the limit
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pQ RV"

\end_inset

) can be found using the inverse Laplace transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $h(z;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The computation just outlined allows one, in principle, to obtain quantitative
 predictions from the RV measure.
 Further details and a more direct computational procedure will be given
 elsewhere
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2008ph"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Presently, let us analyze the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 in qualitative terms.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q_{R};\mathcal{V})$
\end_inset

 is expressed as [cf.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pQ RV"

\end_inset

)] 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(Q_{R};\mathcal{V})\!\equiv\!\frac{\left\langle \left.\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}\right|_{\mathcal{V}}\right\rangle }{\mathcal{V}}\!=\!\frac{\int_{-\text{i}\infty}^{\text{i}\infty}\!e^{z\mathcal{V}}h(z;\phi,Q)dz}{\mathcal{V}\int_{-\text{i}\infty}^{\text{i}\infty}\!e^{z\mathcal{V}}g(z;\phi)dz}.\label{eq:pQ RV ans}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The asymptotic behavior of the inverse Laplace transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $h(z;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 at large 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 is determined by the locations of the singularities of 
\begin_inset Formula $h(z;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 in the complex 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 plane.
 The dominant asymptotics of the inverse Laplace transform are of the form
 
\begin_inset Formula $\propto\exp(z_{*}\mathcal{V})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}$
\end_inset

 is the singularity with the smallest 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mbox{Re}\,z_{*}|$
\end_inset

.
 It can be shown that solutions of Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:h equ"

\end_inset

) cannot diverge at 
\emph on
finite
\emph default
 values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h(z;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 cannot have 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

- or 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-dependent singularities in 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 cannot have pole-like singularities in 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

; the only possible singularities are branch points where the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 is finite but a derivative with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 diverges.
 Furthermore, derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{z}^{n}h$
\end_inset

 satisfy linear equations with coefficients depending on the derivatives
 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{z}^{n-1}g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

, which diverge at the singularities of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 Hence the singularities of 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{z}^{n}h$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 plane coincide with those of 
