\begin_layout Standard
An attractive feature of the RV measure is that its construction lacks extraneou
s geometric elements that could introduce a bias.
 An example of a biased measure is the equal-time cutoff where one considers
 the subdomain of the reheating surface to the past of a hypersurface of
 fixed proper time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{c}$
\end_inset

, subsequently letting 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{c}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
 It is well known that the volume-weighted distribution of observables within
 a hypersurface of equal proper time is strongly dominated by regions where
 inflation ended very recently.
 A time delay 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t$
\end_inset

 in the onset of reheating due to a rare quantum fluctuation is overwhelmingly
 rewarded by an additional volume expansion factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\propto\exp[3H_{\max}\delta t]$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\max}$
\end_inset

 is roughly the highest Hubble rate accessible to the inflaton.
 This is the essence of the youngness paradox that seems unavoidable in
 an equal-time cutoff.
 Moreover, the results of the equal-time cutoff are sensitive to the choice
 of the time gauge, as discussed in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Gauge-dependence-issues"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spherical cutoff
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vilenkin:1998kr"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stationary measure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Linde:2007nm"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 prescriptions were motivated by the need to remove the bias inherent in
 the equal-time cutoff.
 In particular, the spherical cutoff selects as a compact subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 the interior of a large sphere drawn within the reheating surface 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 around a randomly chosen center.
 The spherical cutoff is manifestly gauge-invariant since its construction
 uses only the intrinsically defined 3-volume of the reheating surface rather
 than the spacetime coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(t,x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Some results were obtained in the spherical cutoff using numerical simulations
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vanchurin:1999iv"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 A disadvantage of the spherical cutoff is that its direct implementation
 requires one to perform costly numerical simulations of random-walk inflation
 on a spacetime grid, for instance, using the techniques of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Linde:1993xx,Vanchurin:1999iv,Winitzki:1999ve"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Instead, one would prefer to obtain a generally valid analytic formula
 for the probability distribution of cosmological observables.
 For instance, one could ask whether the results of the spherical cutoff
 depend in an essential way on the spherical shape of the region, on the
 position of the center of the sphere, and on the initial conditions.
 Satisfactory answers to these questions (in the negative) were obtained
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vilenkin:1998kr,Vanchurin:1999iv"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 in some tractable cases where results could be obtained analytically.
 However, it is difficult to analyze these questions in full generality
 since one lacks a general analytic formula for the probability distribution
 in the spherical cutoff.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The RV measure is similar in spirit to the spherical cutoff because the
 RV cutoff uses only the intrinsic geometrical information defined by the
 reheating surface.
 It can be argued that the RV cutoff is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

more natural
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 than other cutoffs in that it selects a finite portion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 of the reheating surface without using artificial constant-time hypersurfaces,
 spheres, worldlines, or any other extraneous geometrical data.
 Instead, the selection of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 in the RV cutoff is performed using a certain well-defined selection of
 subensemble in the probability space, which is determined by the stochastic
 evolution itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The central concept in the RV cutoff is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

finitely produced volume.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The basic idea is that there is always a nonzero probability that a given
 initial 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
does
\emph default
 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 give rise to an infinite reheating surface in its comoving future.
 For instance, it is possible that by a rare coincidence the inflaton field
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 rolls towards reheating at approximately the same time everywhere in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, there is a nonzero (if small) probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V})d\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 that the total volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Vol}(R)$
\end_inset

 of the reheating surface 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 to the future of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 belongs to a given interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathcal{V},\mathcal{V}+d\mathcal{V}\right]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho(\mathcal{V})\equiv\lim_{d\mathcal{V}\rightarrow0}\frac{\mbox{Prob}\left\{ \mbox{Vol}(R)\in\left[\mathcal{V},\mathcal{V}+d\mathcal{V}\right]\right\} }{d\mathcal{V}}.\label{eq:rho def}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

I call 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V})$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

finitely produced volume distribution.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 This distribution is nontrivial because the probability of the event 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Vol}(R)<\infty$
\end_inset

 is nonzero, if small, for any given (non-reheated) initial region 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 The distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V})$
\end_inset

 is, by construction, normalized to that probability:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{0}^{\infty}\rho(\mathcal{V})d\mathcal{V}=\mbox{Prob}\left\{ \mbox{Vol}(R)<\infty\right\} <1.\label{eq:rho V normalization}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The RV cutoff consists of a selection of a certain ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\mathcal{V}}$
\end_inset

 of the histories that produce a total reheated volume equal to a given
 value 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 starting from an initial 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region.
 In the limit of large 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

, the ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\mathcal{V}}$
\end_inset

 consists of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions that evolve 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

almost
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to the regime of eternal inflation.
 Thus, heuristically one can expect that the ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\mathcal{V}}$
\end_inset

 provides a representative sample of the infinite reheating surface.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Of course, this heuristic statement cannot be made rigorous since there
 exists no natural measure on the infinite reheating surface.
 We use this statement merely as an additional motivation for considering
 the RV measure.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Given the ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\mathcal{V}}$
\end_inset

, one can determine the volume-weighted probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q|{\cal E}_{\mathcal{V}})$
\end_inset

 of a cosmological parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 by ordinary sampling of the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 throughout the finite volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, the probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q)$
\end_inset

 is defined as the limit of 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q|{\cal E}_{\mathcal{V}})$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, provided that the limit exists.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To clarify the construction of the ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\mathcal{V}}$
\end_inset

, it is helpful to begin by considering the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V})$
\end_inset

 in a model that does 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 permit eternal inflation.
 In that case, the volume of the reheating surface is finite with probability
 1, so the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V})$
\end_inset

 is an ordinary probability distribution normalized to unity.
 In that context, the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V})$
\end_inset

 was introduced in the recent work
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Creminelli:2008es"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 where the authors considered a family of inflationary models parametrized
 by a number 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, such that eternal inflation is impossible in models where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega>1$
\end_inset

.
 It was then found by a direct calculation that all the moments of the distribut
ion 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V})$
\end_inset

 diverge at the value 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=1$
\end_inset

 where the possibility of eternal inflation is first switched on.
 One can show that the 
\emph on
finitely produced
\emph default
 distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V})$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega<1$
\end_inset

 is again well-behaved and has finite moments (see Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Asymptotics-of-rho"

\end_inset

).
 This FPRV distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V})$
\end_inset

 is the formal foundation of the RV cutoff.
 It is worth emphasizing that the RV cutoff does not regulate the volume
 of the reheating surface by modifying the dynamics of a given inflationary
 model and making eternal inflation impossible.
 Rather, finite volumes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 are generated by rare chance (
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

within the ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\mathcal{V}}$
\end_inset

) through the unmodified dynamics of the model, directly in the regime of
 eternal inflation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Below I compute the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V})$
\end_inset

 asymptotically for very large 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 in models of slow-roll inflation (Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Asymptotics-of-rho"

\end_inset

).
 Specifically, I will compute the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the (homogeneous) value of the inflaton field in the initial region
 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 To implement the RV cutoff explicitly for predicting the distribution of
 a cosmological parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, it is necessary to consider the joint finitely produced distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V},\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}};\phi_{0},Q_{0})$
\end_inset

 for the reheating volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}(R)$
\end_inset

 and the portion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}$
\end_inset

 of the reheating volume in which 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=Q_{R}$
\end_inset

.
 (As before, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}$
\end_inset

 are the values in the initial 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region.) If the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V},\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}};\phi_{0},Q_{0})$
\end_inset

 is found, one can determine the mean volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \left.\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}\right|_{\mathcal{V}}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 while the total reheating volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 is held fixed,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \left.\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}\right|_{\mathcal{V}}\right\rangle =\frac{\int\rho(\mathcal{V},\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}};\phi_{0},Q_{0})\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}d\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}}{\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi_{0},Q_{0})}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Then one computes the probability of finding the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 within the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[Q_{R},Q_{R}+dQ\right]$
\end_inset

 at a random point in the volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(Q=Q_{R};\mathcal{V})\equiv\frac{\left\langle \left.\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}\right|_{\mathcal{V}}\right\rangle }{\mathcal{V}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The RV cutoff 
\emph on
defines
\emph default
 the probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q)$
\end_inset

 for an observable 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 as the limit of the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q;\mathcal{V})$
\end_inset

 at large 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(Q)\equiv\lim_{\mathcal{V}\rightarrow\infty}\frac{\left\langle \left.\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}\right|_{\mathcal{V}}\right\rangle }{\mathcal{V}}.\label{eq:p Q def}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

One expects that this limit is independent of the initial values 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0},Q_{0}$
\end_inset

 because the large volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 is generated by regions that spent a very long time in the self-reproduction
 regime and forgot the initial conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the previous chapter I derived equations from which the distributions
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V},\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}};\phi_{0},Q_{0})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi_{0},Q_{0})$
\end_inset

 can be in principle determined.
 However, a direct computation of the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 (for instance, by a numerical method) will be cumbersome since the relevant
 probabilities are exponentially small in that limit.
 One of the main results of the present chapter is an analytic evaluation
 of the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 and a derivation of a more explicit formula, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pQR main ans"

\end_inset

), for the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q)$
\end_inset

.
 The formula shows that the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q)$
\end_inset

 can be computed as a ground-state eigenfunction of a certain modified Fokker–Pl
anck equation.
 The explicit representation also proves that the limit
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:p Q def"

\end_inset

) exists, is gauge-invariant, and is independent of the initial conditions
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was argued qualitatively in the previous chapter that the RV measure
 does not suffer from the youngness paradox.
 In this chapter I demonstrate the absence of the youngness paradox in the
 RV measure by an explicit calculation.
 To this end, I will consider a toy model where every 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region starts in the fluctuation-dominated (or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

self-reproduction
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) regime with a constant expansion rate 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 and proceeds to reheating via two possible channels.
 The first channel consists of a short period 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t_{1}$
\end_inset

 of deterministic slow-roll inflation, yielding 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{1}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-foldings until reheating; the second channel has a different period 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t_{2}\neq\delta t_{1}$
\end_inset

 of deterministic inflation, yielding 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{2}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-foldings.
 (For simplicity, in this model one neglects fluctuations that may return
 the field from the slow-roll regime to the self-reproduction regime, and
 thus the time periods 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t_{2}$
\end_inset

 are sharply defined.) Thus there are two types of reheated regions corresponding
 to the two possible slow-roll channels.
 The task is to compute the relative volume-weighted probability 
\begin_inset Formula $P(2)/P(1)$
\end_inset

 of regions of these types within the reheating surface.
 (Essentially the same model was considered, 
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default
, in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vilenkin:1995yd,Vilenkin:1998kr,Winitzki:2005ya,Linde:2007nm"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 See Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cap:pot1"

\end_inset

 for a sketch of the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\phi)$
\end_inset

 in this model.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This toy model serves as a litmus test of measure prescriptions.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

holographic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

worldline
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 prescription yields 
\begin_inset Formula $P(2)/P(1)$
\end_inset

 equal to the probability ratio of exiting through the two channels for
 a single comoving worldline.
 This probability ratio depends on the initial conditions.
 Thus, the worldline measure is (by design) blind to the volume growth during
 the slow-roll periods.
 On the other hand, the volume-weighted prescriptions of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vilenkin:1998kr,Linde:2007nm"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 both yield 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{P(2)}{P(1)}=\frac{\exp(3N_{2})}{\exp(3N_{1})},\label{eq:unbiased youngness}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

rewarding the reheated 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions that went through channel 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 by the additional volume factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp(3N_{j})$
\end_inset

.
 This ratio is now independent of the initial conditions.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This result has been obtained in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spherical cutoff
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as well as in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stationary measure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 prescriptions.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

For comparison, an equal-time cutoff gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{P(2)}{P(1)}=\frac{\exp\left[3N_{2}-\left(3H_{\max}-\Gamma_{1}-\Gamma_{2}\right)\delta t_{2}\right]}{\exp\left[3N_{1}-\left(3H_{\max}-\Gamma_{1}-\Gamma_{2}\right)\delta t_{1}\right]}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The overwhelming exponential dependence on 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t_{2}$
\end_inset

 manifests the youngness paradox: Even a small difference 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t_{2}-\delta t_{1}$
\end_inset

 in the duration of the slow-roll inflationary epoch leads to the exponential
 bias towards the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

younger
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 universes.
 The bias persists regardless of the choice of the time gauge
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2005ya"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, essentially because the 
\emph on
presence
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t_{2}$
\end_inset

 in the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $P(2)/P(1)$
\end_inset

 cannot be eliminated by using a different time coordinate.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It should be noted that the youngness bias becomes very small, possibly
 even negligible, if one uses the number 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 of inflationary 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-foldings as the time variable rather than the proper time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 I am grateful to A.
 Linde and A.
 Vilenkin for bringing this to my attention.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 One expects that the RV measure will be free from this bias because the
 RV prescription does not involve the time coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 at all.
 Below (Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Toy-model-of"

\end_inset

) I will show that the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $P(2)/P(1)$
\end_inset

 computed using the RV cutoff is indeed independent of the slow-roll durations
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t_{1,2}$
\end_inset

.
 The RV-regulated result [shown in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:RV result toy"

\end_inset

) below] depends only on the gauge-invariant quantities such as 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{2}$
\end_inset

 and is, in general, different from Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:unbiased youngness"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

