\begin_layout Subsection
Preliminaries
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I consider a model of slow-roll inflation driven by an inflaton 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 with the action 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int\left[\frac{R}{16\pi G}+\frac{1}{2}\left(\partial_{\mu}\phi\right)^{2}-V(\phi)\right]\sqrt{-g}d^{4}x.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

As before, I use the semiclassical stochastic approach to inflation in which
 the semiclassical dynamics of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 averaged over an 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region is regarded as a superposition of a deterministic slow roll, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{\phi}=v(\phi)\equiv-\frac{V_{,\phi}(\phi)}{3H(\phi)}=-\frac{H_{,\phi}}{4\pi G},\label{eq:v def 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 and a random walk with root-mean-squared step size
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sqrt{\left\langle \delta\phi\right\rangle ^{2}}=\frac{H(\phi)}{2\pi}\equiv\sqrt{\frac{2D(\phi)}{H(\phi)}},\quad D\equiv\frac{H^{3}}{8\pi^{2}},\label{eq:D def 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

during time intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t=H^{-1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $H(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is the function defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H(\phi)\equiv\sqrt{\frac{8\pi G}{3}V(\phi)}.\label{eq:H def 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

A useful effective description of the evolution of the field at time scales
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t\lesssim H^{-1}$
\end_inset

 can be given as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi(t+\delta t)=\phi(t)+v(\phi)\delta t+\xi(t)\sqrt{2D(\phi)\delta t},\label{eq:phi delta t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi(t)$
\end_inset

 is a normalized 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

white noise
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 function, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \xi\right\rangle =0,\quad\left\langle \xi(t)\xi(t')\right\rangle =\delta(t-t'),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is approximately statistically independent between different 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions.
 This stochastic process describes the evolution 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(t)$
\end_inset

 and the accompanying cosmological expansion of space along a single comoving
 worldline.
 For simplicity, we assume that inflation ends in a given horizon-size region
 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 is a fixed value such that the relative change of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 during one Hubble time 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t=H^{-1}$
\end_inset

 becomes of order 1, 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|\frac{H_{,\phi}vH^{-1}}{H}\right|_{\phi=\phi_{*}}=\left|\frac{H_{,\phi}^{2}}{4\pi GH^{2}}\right|_{\phi=\phi_{*}}\sim1.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

From the point of view of the stochastic approach, an inflationary model
 is fully specified by the kinetic coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\phi)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v(\phi)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $H(\phi)$
\end_inset

.
 These coefficients are found from Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:v def 1"

\end_inset

)–(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:H def 1"

\end_inset

) in models of canonical slow-roll inflation and by suitable analogues in
 other models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dynamics of any fluctuating cosmological parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is described in a similar way.
 One assumes that the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions.
 The evolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is described by an effective Langevin equation,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q(t+\delta t)=Q(t)+v_{Q}(\phi,Q)\delta t+\xi_{Q}(t)\sqrt{2D_{Q}(\phi,Q)\delta t},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the kinetic coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{Q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{Q}$
\end_inset

 can be computed, similarly to 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

, from first principles.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us consider an initial 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 where the inflaton field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 as well as the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 are homogeneous and have values 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=Q_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 For convenience we assume that reheating starts when 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 and the Planck energy scales are reached at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{\text{Pl}}$
\end_inset

 independently of the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 (If necessary, the field variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi,Q$
\end_inset

 can be redefined to achieve this.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although eternal inflation to the future of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is almost always the case, it is possible that reheating is reached at
 a finite time everywhere to the future of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, due to a rare fluctuation.
 In that event, the total reheating volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 to the future of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 The (small) probability of that event, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{Prob}\left(\mathcal{V}<\infty|\phi_{0},Q_{0}\right)\equiv\bar{X}(\phi_{0},Q_{0}),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 can be found as the solution of the following nonlinear equation, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{D}{H}\bar{X}_{,\phi\phi}+\frac{D_{Q}}{H}\bar{X}_{,QQ}+\frac{v}{H}\bar{X}_{,\phi}+\frac{v_{Q}}{H}\bar{X}_{,Q}+3\bar{X}\ln\bar{X} & =0,\label{eq:X equ 02}\\
\bar{X}(\phi_{\text{Pl}},Q)=1,\quad\bar{X}(\phi_{*},Q) & =1,
\end{align}

\end_inset

where for brevity we dropped the subscript 0 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This basic equation is of reaction-diffusion type and can be viewed as a
 nonlinear modification of the Fokker–Planck equations used previously in
 the literature on the stochastic approach to inflation.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}(\phi,Q)\equiv1$
\end_inset

 is always a solution of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ 02"

\end_inset

), it is not the correct one for the case of eternal inflation.
 A nontrivial solution, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}(\phi,Q)\not\equiv1$
\end_inset

, exists and has small values 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}(\phi,Q)\ll1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi,Q$
\end_inset

 away from the thermalization boundary.
 If the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $D/H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v/H$
\end_inset

 happen to be 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-independent, the solution of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ 02"

\end_inset

) will be also independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}(\phi,Q)=\bar{X}(\phi)$
\end_inset

, and thus determined by a simpler equation obtained from Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ 02"

\end_inset

) by omitting derivatives with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{D}{H}\bar{X}_{,\phi\phi}+\frac{v}{H}\bar{X}_{,\phi}+3\bar{X}\ln\bar{X}=0.\label{eq:X equ phi 03}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

As we have already seen, Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ 02"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ phi 03"

\end_inset

) are manifestly gauge-invariant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Finitely produced volume
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a scenario where eternal inflation is possible, we now consider the probabili
ty density 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 of having a 
\emph on
finite
\emph default
 total reheating volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 to the comoving future of an initial 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region with homogeneous value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 (focusing attention at first on the case of inflation driven by a single
 scalar field).
 The distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 is normalized to the overall probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}(\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 of having a finite total reheating volume, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{0}^{\infty}\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi_{0})d\mathcal{V}=\bar{X}(\phi_{0}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 can be calculated by first determining the generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

, which is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(z;\phi_{0})\equiv\left\langle e^{-z\mathcal{V}}\right\rangle _{\mathcal{V}<\infty}\equiv\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-z\mathcal{V}}\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi_{0})d\mathcal{V}.\label{eq:g def 0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This generating function is a solution of the nonlinear Fokker–Planck equation,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{L}g+3g\ln g=0,\label{eq:g equ 0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the differential operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{L}\equiv\frac{D}{H}\partial_{\phi}\partial_{\phi}+\frac{v}{H}\partial_{\phi}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the case of several fields, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, one needs to use the corresponding Fokker–Planck operator such as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{L}=\frac{D_{\phi\phi}}{H}\partial_{\phi}\partial_{\phi}+\frac{D_{QQ}}{H}\partial_{Q}\partial_{Q}+\frac{v_{\phi}}{H}\partial_{\phi}+\frac{v_{Q}}{H}\partial_{Q}.\label{eq:L FP phi Q}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The boundary conditions for Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ 0"

\end_inset

) are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
g(z;\phi,Q) & =1\:\mbox{\text{for} }\left\{ \phi,Q\right\} \in\text{Planck boundary},\\
g(z;\phi,Q) & =\left.e^{-zH^{-3}(\phi,Q)}\right|_{\left\{ \phi,Q\right\} \in\text{reheating boundary}}.
\end{align}

\end_inset

Note that the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 enters the boundary conditions but is not explicitly involved in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ 0"

\end_inset

).
 Also, the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 and Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ 0"

\end_inset

) are manifestly gauge-invariant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 plays a central role in the calculations of the RV cutoff.
 It will be shown below that the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ 0"

\end_inset

) needs to be obtained only at an appropriately determined 
\emph on
negative
\emph default
 value of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 This solution can be obtained by a numerical method or through an analytic
 approximation if available.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Asymptotics of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi_{0})$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Asymptotics-of-rho"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The finitely produced distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi)$
\end_inset

 can be found through the inverse Laplace transform of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi)=\frac{1}{2\pi\text{i}}\int_{-\text{i}\infty}^{\text{i}\infty}\negmedspace dz\,e^{z\mathcal{V}}g(z;\phi),\label{eq:rho integral 0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the integration contour in the complex 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 plane can be chosen along the imaginary axis.
 While a full analysis of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V},\phi)$
\end_inset

 is complicated (see, however, the recent work
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dubovsky:2008rf"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 where this function was investigated in more detail), we will merely need
 to derive the asymptotic behavior of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi)$
\end_inset

 at large 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

.
 This asymptotic behavior is determined by the right-most singularity of
 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 in the complex 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 plane.
 It turns out that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 always has a singularity at a real, nonpositive 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

, and that the singularity is of the type
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(z;\phi)=g(z_{*};\phi)+\sigma(\phi)\sqrt{z-z_{*}}+O(z-z_{*}),\label{eq:g sing}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\phi)$
\end_inset

 are determined as follows.
 One considers the (
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-dependent) linear operator
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\tilde{L}}\equiv\hat{L}+3(\ln g(z;\phi)+1),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 is the Fokker–Planck operator described above.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $z>0$
\end_inset

 this operator is invertible in the space of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\phi)$
\end_inset

 satisfying zero boundary conditions.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}$
\end_inset

 turns out to be the algebraically largest real number (in any case, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}\leq0$
\end_inset

) such that there exists an eigenfunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\phi)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\tilde{L}}$
\end_inset

 with zero eigenvalue and zero boundary conditions,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\tilde{L}}\sigma(\phi)=0,\quad\sigma(\phi_{*})=\sigma(\phi_{\text{Pl}})=0.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The specific normalization of the eigenfunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\phi)$
\end_inset

 can be derived analytically but is unimportant for the present calculations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The singularity type shown in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g sing"

\end_inset

) determines the leading asymptotic of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi)$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi)\approx\frac{1}{2\sqrt{\pi}}\sigma(\phi)\mathcal{V}^{-3/2}e^{z_{*}\mathcal{V}}.\label{eq:rho asympt}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The explicit form
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rho asympt"

\end_inset

) allows one to investigate the moments of the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi)$
\end_inset

.
 It is clear that all the moments are finite as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}<0$
\end_inset

.
 However, if 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}=0$
\end_inset

 all the moments diverge, namely for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \mathcal{V}^{n}\right\rangle =\int_{0}^{\infty}\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi)\mathcal{V}^{n}d\mathcal{V}\propto\int_{0}^{\infty}\mathcal{V}^{n-3/2}d\mathcal{V}=\infty.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The case 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}=0$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

transition point
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 analyzed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Creminelli:2008es"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=1$
\end_inset

 in their notation.
 This is the borderline case between the presence and the absence of eternal
 inflation.
 The fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}=0$
\end_inset

 in the borderline case can be seen directly by noting that the Fokker–Planck
 operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}+3$
\end_inset

 has in that case a zero eigenvalue, meaning that the 3-volume of equal-time
 surfaces does not expand with time (reheating of some regions is perfectly
 compensated by inflationary expansion of other regions).
 In that case, the only solution 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z=0;\phi)=\bar{X}(\phi)$
\end_inset

 of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ phi 03"

\end_inset

) is 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}\equiv1$
\end_inset

 because there are no eternally inflating comoving geodesics.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln g(z=0,\phi)=0$
\end_inset

, and so the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\tilde{L}}$
\end_inset

 is simply 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\tilde{L}}=\hat{L}+3$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\tilde{L}}$
\end_inset

 also has a zero eigenvalue at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

, and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}=0$
\end_inset

 is the dominant singularity of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

.
 This argument reproduces and generalizes the results obtained in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Creminelli:2008es"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 where direct calculations of various moments of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi)$
\end_inset

 were performed for the case of the absence of eternal inflation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note that the only necessary ingredients in the computation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is the knowledge of the singularity point 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}$
\end_inset

 and the corresponding function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z_{*};\phi)$
\end_inset

, which is a solution of the nonlinear reaction-diffusion equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ 0"

\end_inset

).
 Determining 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z_{*};\phi)$
\end_inset

 in a given inflationary model does not require extensive numerical simulations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Distribution of a fluctuating field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Above we denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 a cosmological parameter that fluctuates during inflation but is in principle
 observable after reheating.
 One of the main questions to be answered using a multiverse measure is
 to derive the probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q)$
\end_inset

 for the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 observed in a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

typical
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 place in the multiverse.
 I will now present a formula for the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q)$
\end_inset

 in the RV cutoff.
 This formula is significantly more explicit and lends itself more easily
 to practical calculations than the expressions first shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2008yb"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As in the previous section, we assume that the dynamics of the inflaton
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is described by a suitable Fokker–Planck operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

, 
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

of the form
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:L FP phi Q"

\end_inset

), and that reheating occurs at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 independently of the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 We then consider Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ 0"

\end_inset

) for the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 and the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\tilde{L}}\equiv\hat{L}+3(\ln g+1)$
\end_inset

; we need to determine the value 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}$
\end_inset

 at which 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 has a singularity.
 The operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\tilde{L}}$
\end_inset

 has an eigenfunction with zero eigenvalue for this value of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 This eigenfunction 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}(z_{*};\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 needs to be determined with zero boundary conditions (at reheating and
 Planck boundaries).
 Then the RV-regulated distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 at reheating is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(Q_{R})=\mbox{const}\left[\frac{\partial f_{0}(z_{*};\phi,Q)}{\partial\phi}\frac{D_{\phi\phi}e^{-z_{*}H^{-3}}}{H^{4}}\right]_{\phi=\phi_{*},Q=Q_{R}},\label{eq:pQR main ans}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the normalization constant needs to be chosen such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int p(Q_{R})dQ_{R}=1$
\end_inset

.
 The derivation of this result occupies Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:FPRV-distribution-of-Q"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the eigenfunction 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}$
\end_inset

 of a gauge-invariant operator, and that the result in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pQR main ans"

\end_inset

) depends on the kinetic coefficients only through the gauge-independent
 ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $D/H$
\end_inset

 times the volume factor 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{-3}$
\end_inset

.
 The distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q_{R})$
\end_inset

 is independent of the initial conditions, which is due to a specific asymptotic
 behavior of the finitely produced volume distributions, as shown in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:FPRV-distribution-of-Q"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Toy model of inflation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Toy-model-of"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now apply the RV cutoff to the toy model described at the end of Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Introduction-and-motivation"

\end_inset

.
 We consider a model of inflation driven by a scalar field with a potential
 shown in Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cap:pot1"

\end_inset

.
 For the purposes of the present argument, we may assume that there is exactly
 zero 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

diffusion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the deterministic regimes 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{*}^{(1)}<\phi<\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}<\phi<\phi_{*}^{(2)}$
\end_inset

, while the range 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}<\phi<\phi_{2}$
\end_inset

 is sufficiently wide to allow for eternal self-reproduction.
 Thus there are two slow-roll channels that produce respectively 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{2}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-foldings of slow-roll inflation after exiting the self-reproduction regime.
 Since the self-reproduction range generates arbitrarily large volumes of
 space that enter both the slow-roll channels, the total reheating volume
 going through each channel is infinite.
 We apply the RV cutoff to the problem of computing the regularized ratio
 of the reheating volumes in regions of types 1 and 2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this toy model it is possible to obtain the results of the RV cutoff
 using analytic approximations.
 The required calculations are somewhat lengthy and can be found in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:A-model-of-slow-roll"

\end_inset

.
 The result for a generic case where one of the slow-roll channels has many
 more 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-foldings than the other (say, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{2}\gg N_{1}$
\end_inset

) can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{P(2)}{P(1)}\approx O(1)\frac{H^{-3}(\phi_{*}^{(2)})}{H^{-3}(\phi_{*}^{(1)})}\frac{\exp\left[3N_{2}\right]}{\exp\left[3N_{1}\right]}\exp\left[3N_{12}\right],\label{eq:RV result toy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we have defined 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N_{12}\equiv\frac{\pi^{2}}{\sqrt{2}H_{0}^{2}}\left(\phi_{2}-\phi_{1}\right)^{2},\quad H_{0}^{2}\equiv\frac{8\pi G}{3}V_{0}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The pre-exponential factor 
\begin_inset Formula $O(1)$
\end_inset

 can be computed numerically, as outlined in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:A-model-of-slow-roll"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note that the ratio
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:RV result toy"

\end_inset

) is gauge-invariant and does not involve any spacetime coordinates.
 This result can be interpreted as the ratio of volumes 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{3N_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{3N_{2}}$
\end_inset

 gained during the slow-roll regime in the two channels multiplied by a
 correction factor 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{3N_{12}}$
\end_inset

.
 The dimensionless number 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{12}$
\end_inset

 can be suggestively interpreted (up to the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

) as the mean number of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

steps
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of size 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\phi\sim\frac{1}{2\pi}H_{0}$
\end_inset

 required for a random walk to reach the boundary of the flat region 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\phi_{1},\phi_{2}\right]$
\end_inset

 starting from the middle point 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}\equiv\frac{1}{2}\left(\phi_{1}+\phi_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Since each of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

steps
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the random walk takes a Hubble time 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and corresponds to one 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-folding of inflation, the volume factor gained during such a traversal
 will be 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{3N_{12}}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the correction factor increases the probability of channel 2
 that was 
\emph on
already
\emph default
 the dominant one due to the larger volume factor 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{3N_{2}}\gg e^{3N_{1}}$
\end_inset

.
 Depending on the model, this factor may be a significant modification of
 the ratio
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:unbiased youngness"

\end_inset

) obtained in previously used volume-based measures.
\end_layout

