\begin_layout Subsection
Derivation of the equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Distribution-of-finitely-produced"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section I derive Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ 0"

\end_inset

), closely following the derivation of the nonlinear diffusion equation
 shown in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Xequ"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin by considering the case when inflation is driven by a single scalar
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, such that reheating is reached at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 be the probability density of obtaining the finite reheated volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

.
 We will derive an equation for a generating function of the distribution
 of volume, rather than an equation directly for 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 Since the volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 is by definition nonnegative, it is convenient to define a generating function
 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 through the expectation value of the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp(-z\mathcal{V})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $z>0$
\end_inset

 is the formal parameter of the generating function, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(z;\phi_{0})\equiv\left\langle e^{-z\mathcal{V}}\right\rangle _{\mathcal{V}<\infty}\equiv\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-z\mathcal{V}}\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi_{0})d\mathcal{V}.\label{eq:g def}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Re}\,z\geq0$
\end_inset

 the integral in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g def"

\end_inset

) converges, and the events with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}=+\infty$
\end_inset

 are automatically excluded from consideration.
 However, we use the subscript 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}<\infty$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to indicate explicitly that the statistical average is performed over the
 subensemble of all events with finite 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

.
 The distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

 is not normalized to unity; instead, the normalization is given by Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rho V normalization"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 has the dimension of inverse 3-volume.
 Physically, this is the 3-volume measured along the reheating surface and
 hence is defined in a gauge-invariant manner.
 If desired for technical reasons, the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 can be made dimensionless by a constant rescaling.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 has the following multiplicative property: For two statistically independent
 regions that have initial values 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{2}$
\end_inset

 respectively, the sum of the (finitely produced) reheating volumes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}_{1}+\mathcal{V}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is distributed with the generating function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle e^{-z(\mathcal{V}_{1}+\mathcal{V}_{2})}\right\rangle =\left\langle e^{-z\mathcal{V}_{1}}\right\rangle \left\langle e^{-z\mathcal{V}_{2}}\right\rangle =g(z;\phi_{1})g(z;\phi_{2}).\label{eq:g multiplicative}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now consider an 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region at some time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, having an arbitrary value 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(t)$
\end_inset

 not yet in the reheating regime.
 Suppose that the finitely produced volume distribution for this 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region has the generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

.
 After time 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t$
\end_inset

 the initial 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region grows to 
\begin_inset Formula $N\equiv e^{3H\delta t}$
\end_inset

 statistically independent, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

daughter
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-th daughter region (
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,...,N$
\end_inset

) is found from Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:phi delta t"

\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi_{k}=\phi+v(\phi)\delta t+\xi_{k}\sqrt{2D(\phi)\delta t},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

noise
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{k}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,...,N$
\end_inset

) are statistically independent because they describe the fluctuations of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 in causally disconnected 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions.
 The finitely produced volume distribution for the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-th daughter region has the generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi_{k})$
\end_inset

.
 The combined reheating volume of the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 daughter regions must be distributed with the same generating function
 as reheating volume of the original 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region.
 Hence, by the multiplicative property we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(z;\phi)=\prod_{k=1}^{N}g(z;\phi_{k}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 We can average both sides of this equation over the noise variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{k}$
\end_inset

 to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(z;\phi)=\left\langle \prod_{k=1}^{N}g(z;\phi_{k})\right\rangle _{\xi_{1},...,\xi_{N}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since all the 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{k}$
\end_inset

 are independent, the average splits into a product of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 identical factors, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(z;\phi)=\left[\left\langle g(z;\phi+v(\phi)\delta t+\sqrt{2D(\phi)}\xi)\right\rangle _{\xi}\right]^{N}.\label{eq:g equ pre}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The derivation now proceeds as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2001np"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 We first compute, to first order in 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle g(z;\phi+v(\phi)\delta t+\sqrt{2D(\phi)}\xi)\right\rangle _{\xi}=g+\left(vg_{,\phi}+Dg_{,\phi\phi}\right)\delta t.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $N=e^{3H\delta t}$
\end_inset

 and taking the logarithmic derivative of both sides of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ pre"

\end_inset

) with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t=0$
\end_inset

, we then obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
0 & =\frac{\partial}{\partial\delta t}\ln g(z;\phi)\nonumber \\
 & =3H\ln g+\frac{vg_{,\phi}+Dg_{,\phi\phi}}{g}.
\end{align}

\end_inset

The equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 follows,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Dg_{,\phi\phi}+vg_{,\phi}+3Hg\ln g=0.\label{eq:g equ}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is formally the same as Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ 02"

\end_inset

).
 However, the boundary conditions for Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ"

\end_inset

) are different.
 The condition at the end-of-inflation boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(z;\phi_{*})=e^{-zH^{-3}(\phi_{*})}\label{eq:bc reheating}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

because an 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 immediately reheats and produces the reheating volume 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{-3}(\phi_{*})$
\end_inset

.
 The condition at Planck boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{Pl}}$
\end_inset

 (if present), or other boundary where the effective field theory breaks
 down, is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

absorbing,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

regions that reach 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{\text{Pl}}$
\end_inset

 do not generate any reheating volume: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(z;\phi_{\text{Pl}})=1.\label{eq:bc Planck}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The variable 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 enters Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ"

\end_inset

) as a parameter and only through the boundary conditions.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 the solution is 
\begin_inset Formula $g(0;\phi)=\bar{X}(\phi)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A fully analogous derivation can be given for the generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi_{0},Q_{0})$
\end_inset

 in the case when additional fluctuating fields, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, are present.
 The generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi_{0},Q_{0})$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(z;\phi_{0},Q_{0})=\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{-z\mathcal{V}}\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi_{0},Q_{0})d\mathcal{V},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi_{0},Q_{0})$
\end_inset

 is the probability density for achieving a total reheating volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 in the future of an 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region with initial values 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0},Q_{0}$
\end_inset

 of the fields.
 In the general case, the fluctuations of the fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi,Q$
\end_inset

 can be described by the Langevin equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\phi(t+\delta t) & =\phi(t)+v_{\phi}\delta t+\xi_{\phi}\sqrt{2D_{\phi\phi}\delta t}+\xi_{Q}\sqrt{2D_{\phi Q}\delta t},\\
Q(t+\delta t) & =Q(t)+v_{Q}\delta t+\xi_{\phi}\sqrt{2D_{\phi Q}\delta t}+\xi_{Q}\sqrt{2D_{QQ}\delta t},
\end{align}

\end_inset

 where the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

diffusion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\phi\phi}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\phi Q}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{QQ}$
\end_inset

 have been introduced, as well as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

slow roll
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 velocities 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\phi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{Q}$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

noise
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{\phi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 The resulting equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi_{0},Q_{0})$
\end_inset

 is (dropping the subscript 0)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{L}g+3g\ln g=0,\label{eq:g equ gen 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the differential operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{L}\equiv\frac{D_{\phi\phi}}{H}\partial_{\phi}\partial_{\phi}+\frac{2D_{\phi Q}}{H}\partial_{\phi}\partial_{Q}+\frac{D_{QQ}}{H}\partial_{Q}\partial_{Q}+\frac{v_{\phi}}{H}\partial_{\phi}+\frac{v_{Q}}{H}\partial_{Q}.\label{eq:FP operator L for Q}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The ratios 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\phi\phi}/H$
\end_inset

, etc., are manifestly gauge-invariant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Performing a redefinition of the fields if needed, one may assume that reheating
 is reached when 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 independently of the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 Then the boundary conditions for Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ gen 1"

\end_inset

) at the reheating boundary can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(z;\phi_{*},Q)=e^{-zH^{-3}(\phi_{*},Q)}.\label{eq:bc reheating phi Q}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The Planck boundary still has the boundary condition 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi_{\text{Pl}})=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Singularities of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Singularities-of-g"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For simplicity we now focus attention on the case of single-field inflation;
 the generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 then depends on the initial value of the inflaton field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding analysis for multiple fields is carried out as a straightforw
ard generalization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main nonlinear equation in the calculations of the RV cutoff is Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ 0"

\end_inset

) for the generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

.
 That equation differs from Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ phi 03"

\end_inset

) mainly by the presence of the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 in the boundary conditions.
 Therefore, we may expect that solutions of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ 0"

\end_inset

) may exist for some values of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 but not for other values.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z=0;\phi)=\bar{X}(\phi)$
\end_inset

; hence, nontrivial solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 exist for 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 under the same conditions as nontrivial solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}(\phi)\not\equiv1$
\end_inset

 of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:X equ phi 03"

\end_inset

).
 While it is certain that solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 exist for 
\begin_inset Formula $z\geq0$
\end_inset

, there may be values 
\begin_inset Formula $z<0$
\end_inset

 for which no real-valued solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 exist at all.
 However, the calculations in the RV cutoff require only to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z_{*};\phi)$
\end_inset

 for a certain value 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}<0$
\end_inset

, which is the algebraically largest value 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 has a singularity in the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 plane.
 The structure of that singularity will be investigated in detail below,
 and it will be shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z_{*};\phi)$
\end_inset

 is finite while 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial g/\partial z\propto(z-z_{*})^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

 diverges at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 remains well-defined at least for all real 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[z_{*},+\infty\right]$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 may be obtained 
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

by a numerical solution of a well-conditioned problem with 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}+\varepsilon$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 is a small real constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 is an integral of a probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi)$
\end_inset

 times 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-z\mathcal{V}}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 is analytic in 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 and has no singularities for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Re}\,z>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then the probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi)$
\end_inset

 can be recovered from the generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 through the inverse Laplace transform,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi)=\frac{1}{2\pi\text{i}}\int_{-\text{i}\infty}^{\text{i}\infty}\negmedspace dz\,e^{z\mathcal{V}}g(z;\phi),\label{eq:rho integral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the integration contour in the complex 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 plane can be chosen along the imaginary axis because all the singularities
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 are to the left of that axis.
 The RV cutoff procedure depends on the limit of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi)$
\end_inset

 and related distributions at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
 The asymptotic behavior at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 is determined by the type and the location of the right-most singularity
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 in the half-plane 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Re}\,z<0$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, if 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

 is such a singularity, the asymptotic is 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi)\propto\exp[-z_{*}\mathcal{V}]$
\end_inset

.
 The prefactor in this expression needs to be determined; for this, a detailed
 analysis of the singularities of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 will be carried out.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to verify that the singularities of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

-independent.
 We first show that solutions of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ gen 1"

\end_inset

) cannot diverge at finite values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 If that were the case and say 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\rightarrow\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\ln g$
\end_inset

 as well as derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{,\phi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{,\phi\phi}$
\end_inset

 would diverge as well.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lim_{\phi\rightarrow\phi_{1}}\partial_{\phi}\left[\ln\ln g\right]=\lim_{\phi\rightarrow\phi_{1}}\frac{\partial_{\phi}g}{g\ln g}=\infty.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It follows that the term 
\begin_inset Formula $g\ln g$
\end_inset

 is negligible near 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ gen 1"

\end_inset

) compared with the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\phi}g$
\end_inset

 and hence also with the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\phi}\partial_{\phi}g$
\end_inset

.
 In a very small neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

, the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 can be approximated by a linear operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}_{1}$
\end_inset

 with constant coefficients, such as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{L}\approx\hat{L}_{1}\equiv A_{1}\partial_{\phi}\partial_{\phi}+B_{1}\partial_{\phi}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since at least one of the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1},B_{1}$
\end_inset

 is nonzero at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 is approximately a solution of the linear equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}_{1}g=0$
\end_inset

 near 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 However, solutions of linear equations cannot diverge at finite values
 of the argument.
 Hence, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 cannot diverge at a finite value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The only remaining possibility is that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 has singular points 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z_{*};\phi)$
\end_inset

 remains finite while 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial g/\partial z$
\end_inset

, or a higher-order derivative, diverges at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 We will now investigate such divergences and show that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 has a leading singularity of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(z;\phi)=g(z_{*};\phi)+\sigma(\phi)\sqrt{z-z_{*}}+O(z-z_{*}),\label{eq:g sing structure}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

-independent location of the singularity such that 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}\leq0$
\end_inset

, while the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is yet to be determined.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Denoting temporarily 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(z;\phi)\equiv\partial g/\partial z$
\end_inset

, we find a 
\emph on
linear
\emph default
 equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{L}g_{1}+3\left(\ln g+1\right)g_{1}=0,\label{eq:g1 equ}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with inhomogeneous boundary conditions
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g_{1}(\phi_{*})=-H^{-3}(\phi_{*})e^{-zH^{-3}(\phi_{*})},\quad g_{1}(\phi_{\text{Pl}})=0.\label{eq:g1 bc}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The solution 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 of this linear problem can be found using a standard method involving the
 Green's function.
 The problem with inhomogeneous boundary conditions is equivalent to the
 problem with zero boundary conditions but with an inhomogeneous equation.
 To be definite, let us consider the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 of the form used in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ"

\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{L}=\frac{D(\phi)}{H(\phi)}\partial_{\phi}\partial_{\phi}+\frac{v(\phi)}{H(\phi)}\partial_{\phi}.\label{eq:L one dim}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g1 equ"

\end_inset

)–(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g1 bc"

\end_inset

) are equivalent to the inhomogeneous problem with zero boundary conditions,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{L}g_{1}+3\left(\ln g+1\right)g_{1} & =DH^{-4}e^{-zH^{-3}}\delta^{\prime}(\phi-\phi_{*}),\label{eq:g1 delta eq}\\
g_{1}(z;\phi_{*}) & =g_{1}(z;\phi_{\text{Pl}})=0.\label{eq:g1 delta bc}
\end{align}

\end_inset

 The solution of this inhomogeneous equation exists as long as the linear
 operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}+3(\ln g+1)$
\end_inset

 does not have a zero eigenfunction with zero boundary conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}+3(\ln g+1)$
\end_inset

 is explicitly 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-dependent through the coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

.
 Note also that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)\neq0$
\end_inset

 by definition
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g def"

\end_inset

) for values of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 such that the integral in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g def"

\end_inset

) converges; hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln g$
\end_inset

 is finite for those 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 Let us denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $G(z;\phi,\phi')$
\end_inset

 the Green's function of that operator with zero boundary conditions,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{L}G+3\left(\ln g(z,\phi)+1\right)G & =\delta(\phi-\phi'),\\
G(z;\phi_{*},\phi') & =G(z;\phi_{\text{Pl}},\phi')=0.
\end{align}

\end_inset

This Green's function is well-defined for values of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}+3(\ln g(z;\phi)+1)$
\end_inset

 is invertible.
 For these 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 we may express the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 of Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g1 equ"

\end_inset

)–(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g1 bc"

\end_inset

) explicitly through the Green's function as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g_{1}(z;\phi)=-\left.\frac{D}{H^{4}}e^{-zH^{-3}}\right|_{\phi_{*}}\left.\frac{\partial G(z;\phi,\phi')}{\partial\phi'}\right|_{\phi'=\phi_{*}}.\label{eq:g1 through Green}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Hence, for these 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(z;\phi)\equiv\partial g/\partial z$
\end_inset

 remains finite at every value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 A similar argument shows that all higher-order derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial^{n}g/\partial z^{n}$
\end_inset

 remain finite at every 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 for these 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the singularities of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 can occur only at certain 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

-independent points 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 is nonsingular for all complex 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Re}\,z>0$
\end_inset

, it is assured that 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G(z;\phi,\phi')$
\end_inset

 exist for such 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 However, there will be values of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 for which the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}+3(\ln g+1)$
\end_inset

 has a zero eigenfunction with zero boundary conditions, so the Green's
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is undefined.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}$
\end_inset

 such a value with the algebraically largest real part; we already know
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Re}\,z_{*}\leq0$
\end_inset

 in any case.
 Let us now show that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 actually diverges when 
\begin_inset Formula $z\rightarrow z_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{z\rightarrow z_{*}}g_{1}(z;\phi)=\infty$
\end_inset

 for every value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To show this, we need to use the decomposition of the Green's function in
 the eigenfunctions of the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}+3(\ln g+1)$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G(z;\phi,\phi')=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\lambda_{n}(z)}f_{n}(\phi)f_{n}^{*}(\phi'),\label{eq:Green decomp}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 are the (appropriately normalized) eigenfunctions with eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{n}(z)$
\end_inset

 and zero boundary conditions,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left[\hat{L}+3(\ln g(z;\phi)+1)\right]f_{n}(z;\phi) & =\lambda_{n}(z)f_{n}(z;\phi),\label{eq:fn equ}\\
f_{n}(z;\phi)=0 & \,\:\mbox{for}\,\:\phi=\phi_{*},\,\phi=\phi_{\text{Pl}}.\label{eq:fn bc}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The decomposition
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Green decomp"

\end_inset

) is possible as long as the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 is self-adjoint with an appropriate choice of the scalar product in the
 space of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\phi)$
\end_inset

.
 The scalar product can be chosen in the following way,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle f_{1},f_{2}\right\rangle =\int f_{1}(\phi)f_{2}^{*}(\phi)M(\phi)d\phi,\label{eq:f1 f2 scalar}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is a weighting function.
 One can attempt to determine 
\begin_inset Formula $M(\phi)$
\end_inset

 such that the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 is self-adjoint,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle f_{1},\hat{L}f_{2}\rangle=\langle\hat{L}f_{1},f_{2}\rangle.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In single-field models of inflation where the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 has the form
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:L one dim"

\end_inset

), it is always possible to choose 
\begin_inset Formula $M(\phi)$
\end_inset

 appropriately
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:1995pg"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 However, in multi-field models this is not necessarily possible.
