 We leave the detailed investigation of those cases for future work.
 Presently, let us focus on the case when the decomposition of the form
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Green decomp"

\end_inset

) holds, with appropriately chosen scalar product and the normalized eigenfuncti
ons
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle f_{m},f_{n}\right\rangle =\delta_{mn}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The eigenfunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{m}(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 can be obtained 
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

numerically by solving the boundary value problem
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fn equ"

\end_inset

)–(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fn bc"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $z\rightarrow z_{*}$
\end_inset

, one of the eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{n}$
\end_inset

 approaches zero.
 Since linear operators such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 always have a spectrum bounded from above
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:1995pg"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, we may renumber the eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the largest one.
 Then we define 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}$
\end_inset

 as the value with the (algebraically) largest real part, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}(z_{*})=0$
\end_inset

.
 By construction, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Re}\,z>\mbox{Re}\,z_{*}$
\end_inset

 all the eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{n}$
\end_inset

 are negative.
 Note that the (algebraically) largest eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}(z)$
\end_inset

 is always nondegenerate, and the corresponding eigenfunction 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 can be chosen real and positive for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, except at the boundaries 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{\text{Pl}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 satisfies the zero boundary conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 near 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}$
\end_inset

, only the nondegenerate eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}$
\end_inset

 will be near zero, so the decomposition
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Green decomp"

\end_inset

) of the Green's function will be dominated by the term 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\lambda_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, we can use Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g1 through Green"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Green decomp"

\end_inset

) to determine the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 approximately as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g_{1}(z;\phi)\approx-\frac{f_{0}(z;\phi)}{\lambda_{0}(z)}\frac{\partial f_{0}(z;\phi_{*})}{\partial\phi}\left[\frac{D}{H^{4}}e^{-zH^{-3}}\right]_{\phi_{*}}.\label{eq:g1 explicit}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It follows that indeed 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(z;\phi)\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $z\rightarrow z_{*}$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}(z)\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This detailed investigation allows us now to determine the behavior of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 at the leading singularity 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 We will consider the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 near 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}$
\end_inset

 and show that the singularity indeed has the structure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g sing structure"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have already shown that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 itself does not diverge at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

 but its derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}\equiv\partial g/\partial z$
\end_inset

 does.
 Hence, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z_{*};\phi)$
\end_inset

 is continuous, and the difference 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z_{*};\phi)-g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 is small for 
\begin_inset Formula $z\approx z_{*}$
\end_inset

, so that we have the expansion 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\delta g(z;\phi) & \equiv g(z;\phi)-g(z_{*};\phi)\\
 & \approx g_{1}(z;\phi)\left(z-z_{*}\right)+O\left[(z_{*}-z)^{2}\right].\label{eq:delta g g1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

(Note that we are using the 
\emph on
finite
\emph default
 value 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 rather than the divergent value 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(z_{*};\phi)$
\end_inset

 in the above equation.) On the other hand, we have the explicit representation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g1 explicit"

\end_inset

).
 Let us examine the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}(z)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $z\approx z_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}(z_{*})=0$
\end_inset

, so the (small) value 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}(z)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $z\approx z_{*}$
\end_inset

 can be found using standard perturbation theory for linear operators.
 If we denote the change in the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta\hat{L}\equiv3(\ln g(z;\phi)-\ln g(z_{*};\phi))\approx\frac{3\delta g(z;\phi)}{g(z_{*};\phi)},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

we can write, to first order, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda_{0}(z)\approx\left\langle f_{0},\delta\hat{L}f_{0}\right\rangle =\int\left|f_{0}(\phi)\right|^{2}\frac{3\delta g(z;\phi)}{g(z_{*};\phi)}d\phi.\label{eq:lambda 0 integral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now, Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g1 explicit"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:delta g g1"

\end_inset

) yield
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\delta g(z;\phi)}{z-z_{*}}\approx-\frac{f_{0}(z;\phi)}{\lambda_{0}(z)}\left[\frac{\partial f_{0}}{\partial\phi}\frac{D}{H^{4}}e^{-zH^{-3}}\right]_{\phi_{*}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Integrating the above equation in 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 with the prefactor
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|f_{0}(\phi)\right|^{2}\frac{3}{g(z_{*};\phi)}d\phi
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and using Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lambda 0 integral"

\end_inset

), we obtain a closed equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}(z)$
\end_inset

 in which terms of order 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(z-z_{*}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 have been omitted, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\lambda_{0}(z)}{z-z_{*}} & \approx-\frac{1}{\lambda_{0}(z)}\left[\frac{\partial f_{0}}{\partial\phi}\frac{D}{H^{4}}e^{-zH^{-3}}\right]_{\phi_{*}}\nonumber \\
 & \quad\times\int\left|f_{0}\right|^{2}\frac{3\delta g(z;\phi)}{g(z_{*};\phi)}f_{0}(\phi)d\phi.\label{eq:lambda 0 ans}
\end{align}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}(z)\propto\sqrt{z-z_{*}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(z;\phi)\propto\left(z-z_{*}\right)^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

, confirming the leading asymptotic of the form
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g sing structure"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us also obtain a more explicit form of the singularity structure of
 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

.
 We can rewrite Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lambda 0 ans"

\end_inset

) as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda_{0}(z)\approx\sigma_{0}\sqrt{z-z_{*}}+O(z-z_{*}),\label{eq:lambda 0 sing}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a constant that may be obtained explicitly.
 Then Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g1 explicit"

\end_inset

) yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g_{1}(z;\phi)\approx\frac{f_{0}(z;\phi)}{\sqrt{z-z_{*}}}\sigma_{1},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with a different constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, we can integrate this in 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 and obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(z;\phi)=g(z_{*};\phi)+2\sigma_{1}f_{0}(z;\phi)\sqrt{z-z_{*}}+O(z-z_{*}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We may rewrite this by substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
g(z;\phi) & =g(z_{*};\phi)+\sigma(\phi)\sqrt{z-z_{*}}+O(z-z_{*}),\label{eq:g asympt sigma 1}\\
\sigma(\phi) & \equiv2\sigma_{1}f_{0}(z_{*};\phi).
\end{align}

\end_inset

The result is now explicitly of the form
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g sing structure"

\end_inset

).
 It will turn out that the normalization constant 
\begin_inset Formula $2\sigma_{1}$
\end_inset

 cancels in the final results.
 So in a practical calculation the eigenfunction 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}(z_{*};\phi)$
\end_inset

 may be determined with an arbitrary normalization.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a side note, let us remark that the argument given above will apply also
 to other singular points 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}^{\prime}\neq z_{*}$
\end_inset

 as long as the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{k}(z)$
\end_inset

 of the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}+3(\ln g+1)$
\end_inset

 is nondegenerate when it vanishes at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 If the relevant eigenvalue becomes degenerate, the singularity structure
 will not be of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{z-z_{*}^{\prime}}$
\end_inset

 but rather 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(z-z_{*}^{\prime}\right)^{s}$
\end_inset

 with some other power 
\begin_inset Formula $0<s<1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we are ready to obtain the asymptotic form of the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
 We deform the integration contour in the inverse Laplace transform
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rho integral"

\end_inset

) such that it passes near the real axis around 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we use Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g asympt sigma 1"

\end_inset

) for 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 and obtain the leading asymptotic 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi) & \approx\frac{1}{2\pi\text{i}}\sigma(\phi)\left[\int_{-\infty}^{z_{*}}-\int_{z_{*}}^{-\infty}\right]\sqrt{z-z_{*}}\,e^{z\mathcal{V}}dz\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{1}{2\sqrt{\pi}}\sigma(\phi)\mathcal{V}^{-3/2}e^{z_{*}\mathcal{V}}.\label{eq:rho asympt 1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The subdominant terms come from the higher-order terms in the expansion
 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g asympt sigma 1"

\end_inset

) and are of the order 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 times the leading term shown in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rho asympt 1"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}$
\end_inset

 must be real-valued and that there are no other singularities 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Re}\,z_{*}^{\prime}=\mbox{Re}\,z_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 This is so because the integral
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g_{1}(z_{*};\phi)=-\int_{0}^{\infty}\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi)e^{-z_{*}\mathcal{V}}\mathcal{V}d\mathcal{V}=\infty\label{eq:g1 integral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

will definitely diverge for purely real 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}$
\end_inset

 if it diverges for a nonreal value 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}^{\prime}=z_{*}+\text{i}A$
\end_inset

.
 If, on the other hand, the integral
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g1 integral"

\end_inset

) diverges for a real 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}$
\end_inset

, it will 
\emph on
converge
\emph default
 for any nonreal 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}^{\prime}=z_{*}+\text{i}A$
\end_inset

 with real 
\begin_inset Formula $A\neq0$
\end_inset

 because the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi)$
\end_inset

 has the large-
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 asymptotic of the form
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rho asympt 1"

\end_inset

) and the oscillations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp(\text{i}A\mathcal{V})$
\end_inset

 will make the integral
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g1 integral"

\end_inset

) convergent.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
FPRV distribution of a field 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:FPRV-distribution-of-Q"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In this section we follow the notation of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2008yb"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

Consider a fluctuating field 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 such that the Fokker–Planck operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 is of the form
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FP operator L for Q"

\end_inset

).
 We are interested in the portion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}$
\end_inset

 of the total reheated volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 where the field 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 has a value within a given interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[Q_{R},Q_{R}+dQ\right]$
\end_inset

.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V},\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}};\phi_{0},Q_{0})$
\end_inset

 the joint probability distribution of the volumes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\mathcal{V}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}$
\end_inset

 for initial 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions with initial values 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=Q_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}(z,q;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 corresponding to that distribution is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{g}(z,q;\phi,Q)\equiv\int e^{-z\mathcal{V}-q\mathcal{V}_{Q}}\rho(\mathcal{V},\mathcal{V}_{Q};\phi,Q)d\mathcal{V}d\mathcal{V}_{Q}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since this generating function satisfies the same multiplicative property
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g multiplicative"

\end_inset

) as the generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

, we may repeat the derivation of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ gen 1"

\end_inset

) without modifications for the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}(z,q;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z,q;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 is the solution of the same equation as 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

.
 The only difference is the boundary conditions at reheating, which are
 given not by Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bc reheating phi Q"

\end_inset

) but by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{g}(z,q;\phi_{*},Q)=\exp\left[-\left(z+q\delta_{QQ_{R}}\right)H^{-3}(\phi_{*},Q)\right],\label{eq:bc for g tilda z q}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where (with a slight abuse of notation) 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{QQ_{R}}$
\end_inset

 is the indicator function of the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[Q_{R},Q_{R}+dQ\right]$
\end_inset

, 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta_{QQ_{R}}\equiv\theta(Q-Q_{R})\theta(Q_{R}+dQ-Q).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We employ this 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

finite
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 version of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

-function only because we cannot use a standard Dirac 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

-function under the exponential.
 This slight technical inconvenience will disappear shortly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution for the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}(z,q;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 may be obtained in principle and will provide complete information about
 the distribution of possible values of the volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}_{Q}$
\end_inset

 together with the total reheating volume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 to the future of an initial 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region.
 In the context of the RV cutoff, one is interested in the event when 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 is finite and very large.
 Then one expects that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}_{Q}$
\end_inset

 also becomes typically very large while the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}_{Q}/\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 remains roughly constant.
 In other words, one expects that the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}_{Q}$
\end_inset

 is sharply peaked around a mean value 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \mathcal{V}_{Q}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, and that the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \mathcal{V}_{Q}\right\rangle /\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 is well-defined at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
 The value of that limit is the only information we need for calculations
 in the RV cutoff.
 Therefore, we do not need to compute the entire distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathcal{V},\mathcal{V_{Q}};\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 but only the mean value 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \left.\mathcal{V}_{Q}\right|_{\mathcal{V}}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 at fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us therefore define the generating function of the mean value 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \left.\mathcal{V}_{Q}\right|_{\mathcal{V}}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 as follows,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h(z;\phi,Q)\equiv\left\langle \mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}e^{-z\mathcal{V}}\right\rangle _{\mathcal{V}<\infty}=-\frac{\partial\tilde{g}}{\partial q}(z,q=0;\phi,Q).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

(The dependence on the fixed value of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{R}$
\end_inset

 is kept implicit in the function 
\begin_inset Formula $h(z;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 in order to make the notation less cumbersome.) The differential equation
 and the boundary conditions for 
\begin_inset Formula $h(z;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 follow straightforwardly by taking the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{q}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $q=0$
\end_inset

 of Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ gen 1"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bc for g tilda z q"

\end_inset

).
 It is clear from the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}(z,q=0;\phi,Q)=g(z;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

.
 Hence we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{L}h+3\left(\ln g(z;\phi,Q)+1\right)h & =0,\label{eq:h equ pre 0}\\
h(z;\phi_{*},Q) & =\frac{e^{-zH^{-3}(\phi_{*},Q)}}{H^{3}(\phi_{*},Q)}\delta_{QQ_{R}},\\
h(z;\phi_{\text{Pl}},Q) & =0.
\end{align}

\end_inset

Note that it is the generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, not 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset

, that appears as a coefficient in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:h equ pre 0"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

finite
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

-function 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{QQ_{R}}$
\end_inset

 now enters only linearly rather than under an exponential, we may replace
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{QQ_{R}}$
\end_inset

 by the ordinary Dirac 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

-function 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(Q-Q_{R})$
\end_inset

.
 To maintain consistency, we need to divide 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $dQ$
\end_inset

, which corresponds to computing the 
\emph on
probability
\emph default
 
\emph on
density
\emph default
 of the reheated volume with 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=Q_{R}$
\end_inset

.
 This probability density is precisely the goal of the present calculation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The RV-regularized probability density for values of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is defined as the limit
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
p(Q_{R}) & =\lim_{\mathcal{V}\rightarrow\infty}\frac{\left\langle \left.\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}\right|_{\mathcal{V}}\right\rangle _{\mathcal{V}<\infty}}{\mathcal{V}\,\rho(\mathcal{V};\phi,Q)}\nonumber \\
 & =\lim_{\mathcal{V}\rightarrow\infty}\frac{\int_{-\text{i}\infty}^{\text{i}\infty}\!e^{z\mathcal{V}}h(z;\phi,Q)dz}{\mathcal{V}\int\!e^{z\mathcal{V}}g(z;\phi,Q)dz}.\label{eq:pQR limit 1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

To compute this limit, we need to consider the asymptotic behavior of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \left.\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}\right|_{\mathcal{V}}\right\rangle _{\mathcal{V}<\infty}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
 This behavior is determined by the leading singularity of the function
 
\begin_inset Formula $h(z;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 in the complex 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 plane.
 The arguments of Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Singularities-of-g"

\end_inset

 apply also to 
\begin_inset Formula $h(z;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 and show that 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 cannot have a 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

- or 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

-dependent singularity in the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 plane.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $h(z;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 has precisely the same singular points, in particular 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

, as the basic generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 of the reheating volume.
 Indeed, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $h(z;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 can be expressed through the Green's function 
\begin_inset Formula $G(z;\phi,Q,\phi',Q')$
\end_inset

 of the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}+3(\ln g+1)$
\end_inset

, similarly to the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 considered in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Singularities-of-g"

\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $z\neq z_{*}$
\end_inset

, this operator is invertible on the space of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 satisfying zero boundary conditions.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $h(z;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 is nonsingular at 
\begin_inset Formula $z\neq z_{*}$
\end_inset

 and becomes singular precisely at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now obtain an explicit form of 
\begin_inset Formula $h(z;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 near the singular point 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 We assume again the eigenfunction decomposition of the Green's function
 (with the same caveats as in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Singularities-of-g"

\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G(z;\phi,Q,\phi',Q')=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\lambda_{n}(z)}f_{n}(z;\phi,Q)f_{n}^{*}(z;\phi',Q'),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}$
\end_inset

 are appropriately normalized eigenfunctions of the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-dependent operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}+3(\ln g+1)$
\end_inset

 with eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{n}(z)$
\end_inset

.
 The eigenfunctions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}$
\end_inset

 must satisfy zero boundary conditions at reheating and Planck boundaries.
 Similarly to the way we derived Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g1 explicit"

\end_inset

), we obtain the explicit solution
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h(z;\phi,Q)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{f_{n}(z;\phi,Q)}{\lambda_{n}(z)}\left[\frac{\partial f_{n}}{\partial\phi}\frac{D_{\phi\phi}e^{-zH^{-3}}}{H^{4}}\right]_{\phi_{*},Q_{R}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $h(z;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $z\approx z_{*}$
\end_inset

 is dominated by the contribution of the large factor 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\lambda_{0}(z)\propto\left(z-z_{*}\right)^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

, so the leading term is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h(z;\phi,Q)\approx\frac{f_{0}(z_{*};\phi,Q)}{\lambda_{0}(z)}\left[\frac{\partial f_{0}}{\partial\phi}\frac{D_{\phi\phi}e^{-z_{*}H^{-3}}}{H^{4}}\right]_{\phi_{*},Q_{R}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The asymptotic behavior of the mean value 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \left.\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}\right|_{\mathcal{V}}\right\rangle _{\mathcal{V}<\infty}$
\end_inset

 is determined by the singularity of 
\begin_inset Formula $h(z;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 As before, we may deform the integration contour to pass near the real
 axis around 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 We can then express the large-
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 asymptotic of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \left.\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}\right|_{\mathcal{V}}\right\rangle _{\mathcal{V}<\infty}$
\end_inset

 as follows,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left\langle \left.\mathcal{V}_{Q_{R}}\right|_{\mathcal{V}}\right\rangle  & =\frac{1}{2\pi\text{i}}\int_{-\text{i}\infty}^{\text{i}\infty}\!e^{z\mathcal{V}}h(z;\phi,Q)dz\nonumber \\
 & \approx\frac{f_{0}(z_{*};\phi,Q)}{\sqrt{\pi}\sigma_{0}\sqrt{\mathcal{V}}}e^{z_{*}\mathcal{V}}\left[\frac{\partial f_{0}}{\partial\phi}\frac{D_{\phi\phi}e^{-z_{*}H^{-3}}}{H^{4}}\right]_{\phi_{*},Q_{R}},\label{eq:V QR ave ans}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the constant defined by Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lambda 0 sing"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now complete the analytic evaluation of the limit
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pQR limit 1"

\end_inset

).
 Since the denominator of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pQR limit 1"

\end_inset

) has the large-
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 asymptotics of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{V}\int_{0}^{\infty}\negmedspace g(z;\phi,Q)e^{z\mathcal{V}}d\mathcal{V}\propto f_{0}(z_{*};\phi,Q)\mathcal{V}^{-\frac{1}{2}}e^{z_{*}\mathcal{V}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the same eigenfunction, the dependence on 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 identically cancels in the limit
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pQR limit 1"

\end_inset

).
 Hence, that limit is independent of the initial values 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 but is a function only of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{R}$
\end_inset

, on which 
\begin_inset Formula $h(z;\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 implicitly depends.
 Using this fact,, we can significantly simplify the rest of the calculation.
 It is not necessary to compute the denominator of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pQR limit 1"

\end_inset

) explicitly.
 The distribution of the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=\phi_{*}$
\end_inset

 is simply proportional to the 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{R}$
\end_inset

-dependent part of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:V QR ave ans"

\end_inset

); the denominator of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pQR limit 1"

\end_inset

) serves merely to normalize that distribution.
 Hence, the RV cutoff yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(Q_{R})=\mbox{const}\left[\frac{\partial f_{0}(z_{*};\phi,Q)}{\partial\phi}\frac{D_{\phi\phi}e^{-z_{*}H^{-3}}}{H^{4}}\right]_{\phi=\phi_{*},Q=Q_{R}},\label{eq:PQR ans 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the normalization constant needs to be chosen such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int p(Q_{R})dQ_{R}=1$
\end_inset

.
 This is the final analytic formula for the RV cutoff applied to the distributio
n of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 at reheating.
 The the value 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}$
\end_inset

, and the corresponding solution 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z_{*};\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ 0"

\end_inset

), and the eigenfunction 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}(z_{*};\phi,Q)$
\end_inset

 need to be obtained numerically unless an analytic solution is possible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us comment on the presence of the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\phi\phi}$
\end_inset

 in the formula
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:PQR ans 1"

\end_inset

).
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

diffusion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\phi\phi}$
\end_inset

 is evaluated at the reheating boundary and is thus small since the fluctuation
 amplitude at reheating is (in slow-roll inflationary models)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\delta\phi}{\phi}\sim\frac{H^{2}}{\dot{\phi}}=\frac{\sqrt{8\pi^{2}D_{\phi\phi}H}}{v_{\phi}}\sim10^{-5}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Nevertheless it is not possible to set 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\phi\phi}=0$
\end_inset

 directly in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:PQR ans 1"

\end_inset

).
 This is so because the existence of the Green's function of the Fokker–Planck
 operator such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 depends on the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 is a second-order differential operator of elliptic type.
 If one sets 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\phi\phi}=0$
\end_inset

 near the reheating boundary, the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 becomes first-order in 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 at that boundary.
 Then one needs to use a different formula than Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g1 delta eq"

\end_inset

) for reducing an equation with inhomogeneous boundary conditions to an
 inhomogeneous equation with zero boundary conditions.
 Accordingly, one cannot use formulas such as Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g1 through Green"

\end_inset

) for the solutions.
 Alternative ways of solving the relevant equations in that case will be
 used in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:A-model-of-slow-roll"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

