\begin_layout Standard
In this section we perform explicit calculations of RV cutoff for a model
 of slow-roll inflation driven by a scalar field with a potential shown
 in Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cap:pot1"

\end_inset

.
 The kinetic coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\phi)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v(\phi)$
\end_inset

 are such that 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\phi)=D_{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v(\phi)=0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $H(\phi)=H_{0}$
\end_inset

 in the flat region 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}<\phi<\phi_{2}$
\end_inset

, where the constants 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H_{0}=\sqrt{\frac{8\pi G}{3}V_{0}},\quad D_{0}=\frac{H_{0}^{3}}{8\pi^{2}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the slow-roll regions 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}<\phi<\phi_{*}^{(1)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}<\phi<\phi_{*}^{(2)}$
\end_inset

, the coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is set equal to zero, while 
\begin_inset Formula $v(\phi)\ne0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H(\phi)$
\end_inset

 is not constant any more.
 The number of 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-foldings in the two slow-roll 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shoulders
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 can be computed by the standard formula, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N_{j}=\int_{\phi_{j}}^{\phi_{*}^{(j)}}\frac{H}{v}d\phi=-4\pi G\int_{\phi_{j}}^{\phi_{*}^{(j)}}\frac{H}{H'}d\phi,\quad j=1,2.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first step of the calculation is to determine the singular point 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

 of solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ"

\end_inset

).
 We expect 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}$
\end_inset

 to be real and negative.
 The boundary conditions for 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(z;\phi_{*}^{(1,2)})=\exp\left[-zH^{-3}(\phi_{*}^{(1,2)})\right].\label{eq:bc for g 12}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In each of the two deterministic regions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{*}^{(1)}<\phi<\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}<\phi<\phi_{*}^{(2)}$
\end_inset

, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ"

\end_inset

) becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{v}{H}\partial_{\phi}g+3g\ln g=0,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the general solution
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(z;\phi)=\exp\left[C\exp\left(-3\int^{\phi}\!\frac{H}{v}d\phi\right)\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is an integration constant.
 Since the equation is first-order within the deterministic regions, the
 solutions are fixed by the boundary condition
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bc for g 12"

\end_inset

) in the respective region,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(z;\phi)=\exp\left[-zH^{-3}(\phi_{*}^{(1,2)})\exp\!\left(\!-3\!\int_{\phi_{*}^{(1,2)}}^{\phi}\!\!\frac{H}{v}d\phi\right)\!\right].\label{eq:g sol nodiff 12}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We may therefore compute the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 at the boundaries 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1,2}$
\end_inset

 of the self-reproduction region as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(z;\phi_{1,2})=\exp\left[-zH^{-3}(\phi_{*}^{(1,2)})\exp\left(3N_{1,2}\right)\right].\label{eq:bc for g equ const 0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now we need to solve Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ"

\end_inset

) with these boundary conditions in the region 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}<\phi<\phi_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The equation has then the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{D_{0}}{H_{0}}\partial_{\phi}\partial_{\phi}g+3g\ln g=0.\label{eq:g equ const 0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Exact solutions of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ const 0"

\end_inset

) were studied in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2001np"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, to which the reader is referred for further details.
 It is easy to show that Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ const 0"

\end_inset

) is formally equivalent to a one-dimensional motion of a particle with
 coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\phi)$
\end_inset

 in a potential 
\begin_inset Formula $U(g)$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U(g)=\frac{6\pi^{2}}{H_{0}^{2}}g^{2}\left(2\ln g-1\right),\label{eq:U pot def}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

while 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 plays the role of time.
 A solution 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 with boundary conditions
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bc for g equ const 0"

\end_inset

) corresponds to a trajectory that starts at the given value 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi_{1})$
\end_inset

 with the initial velocity chosen such that the motion takes precisely the
 specified time interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}-\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and reaches 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $z<0$
\end_inset

 the boundary conditions specify 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi_{1,2})>1$
\end_inset

, 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

the trajectory begins and ends to the right of the minimum of the potential
 (see Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Potential-U"

\end_inset

).
 Since the system is conservative, there is a constant of motion 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 (the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

energy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) such that 
\begin_inset Formula $E=U(g_{0})$
\end_inset

 at the highest point of the trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{0}$
\end_inset

 where the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

kinetic energy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 vanishes.
 The solution 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;\phi)$
\end_inset

 can be written implicitly as one of the two alternative formulas,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pm\int_{g(z;\phi)}^{g(z;\phi_{1,2})}\frac{dg}{\sqrt{2E(z)-2U(g)}}=\phi-\phi_{1,2},\label{eq:g sol implicit}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

valid in appropriate intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}<\phi<\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}<\phi<\phi_{2}$
\end_inset

 respectively, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the turning point 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{0}=g(z;\phi_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 The value 
\begin_inset Formula $E=E(z)$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g sol implicit"

\end_inset

) must be chosen such that the total 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{2}-\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\int_{g_{0}}^{g(z;\phi_{1})}+\int_{g_{0}}^{g(z;\phi_{2})}\right]\frac{dg}{\sqrt{2E-2U(g)}}=\phi_{2}-\phi_{1}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This condition together with 
\begin_inset Formula $E=U(g_{0})$
\end_inset

 implicitly determine the values 
\begin_inset Formula $E=E(z)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{0}=g_{0}(z)$
\end_inset

.
 
