\begin_layout Standard
In this chapter I extend the RV measure, originally formulated in the context
 of random-walk inflation, to landscape scenarios.
 The basic idea of the RV proposal is to select multiverses that are very
 large but (by rare chance) have a finite total number of observers.
 In the context of a string landscape scenario (or a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

recycling universe
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

), this can happen if sufficiently many anti-de Sitter or Minkowski bubbles
 nucleate everywhere, collide, and merge.
 In such a case, there will be a finite time after which no de Sitter regions
 remain and no further nucleations can occur.
 Hence, there will be a finite time after which no more observers are created
 anywhere.
 By this construction, one obtains a subensemble of multiverses having a
 fixed, finite total number 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{\text{obs}}$
\end_inset

 of observers.
 These finite multiverses with very large 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{\text{obs}}$
\end_inset

 are regarded as controlled approximations to the actual infinite multiverse.
 The observer-weighted statistical distribution of any quantity within a
 finite multiverse can be obtained by ordinary counting, since the total
 number of observers within any such multiverse is finite.
 The limit of that statistical distribution as 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{\text{obs}}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 is the final result of the RV prescription.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was shown in Chapters
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cha:A-new-measure-for"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cha:The-new-measure-for-random-walk"

\end_inset

 that the RV measure is gauge-invariant, independent of the initial conditions,
 and free of the youngness paradox in the context of random-walk inflation.
 Presently I investigate whether the same features persist in an application
 of the RV measure to landscape scenarios.
 In particular, it is important to obtain RV predictions with respect to
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Boltzmann brain
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problem that has been widely discussed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In principle, the RV prescription can be extended to landscape models in
 different ways, depending on the precise choice of the ensemble of finite
 multiverses.
 The ensemble of multiverses with a fixed total number of observers 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{\text{obs}}$
\end_inset

 (where one counts both the ordinary observers and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Boltzmann brains
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) appears to be the natural choice.
 However, it is difficult to compute the number of observers directly and
 unambiguously.
 Instead of the total number of observers, I propose to fix the total number
 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{tot}}$
\end_inset

 of bubbles nucleated to the future of an initial bubble.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total number of ordinary observers in bubbles of a given kind is proportiona
l to the volume of the reheating surface in those bubbles.
 It is known that the square bubble approximation
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
square bubble approximation
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bousso:2007nd"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, which neglects the effects of bubble wall geometry, is adequate for the
 purposes of volume counting.
 Then the evolution of the landscape is well described by the approximate
 model called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

inflation in a box
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Aryal:1987vn,Winitzki:2005ya,Winitzki:2008yb"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 In that approximation, one keeps track only of the number of new bubbles
 nucleated in previously existing bubbles, and each new bubble is assumed
 to be instantaneously nucleated exactly of Hubble size in comoving coordinates.
 Motivated by this approximation,  I study a simplified definition of the
 RV measure for a landscape scenario (see Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Extending-the-RV"

\end_inset

 for details): One requires the total number of bubbles of all types, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{tot}}$
\end_inset

, to be finite and evaluates the statistical distribution of bubble types
 (or other cosmological observables) in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{tot}}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
 In principle, this limit can be calculated if the bubble nucleation rates
 are known.
 Since this  is a first attempt to perform this technically challenging
 calculation, I concentrate only on bubble abundances and on the relative
 abundance of Boltzmann brains.
 I neglect the increased number of observers due to additional slow-roll
 inflation within bubbles; this effect was considered in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2008yb"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and requires additional complications in the formalism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A landscape scenario may be specified by enumerating the available 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

