\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

landscape
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 scenarios where transitions between metastable vacuum states occur via
 bubble nucleation, promise to explain the values of presently observed
 cosmological parameters, such as the effective cosmological constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 For this reason it is important to be able to apply the RV measure to landscape
-type scenarios and, in particular, to compute the relative abundances of
 different bubble types.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the terminology of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Garriga:2005av"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

terminal bubbles
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are those with nonpositive value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 No further transitions are possible from such bubbles because bubbles with
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda<0$
\end_inset

 rapidly collapse while bubbles with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda=0$
\end_inset

 do not support tunneling instantons.
 The RV measure, as presently formulated, can be used directly for comparing
 the abundances of 
\emph on
terminal
\emph default
 bubbles.
 (Extending the RV prescription to non-terminal bubble types is certainly
 possible but is delegated to a future publication.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bousso:2007nd"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 that the bubble volume calculations may use the simplifying 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

square bubble
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 approximation, which neglects the effects of bubble wall geometry.
 In this approximation, the evolution of the landscape is well described
 by the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

inflation in a box
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 model
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2005ya"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, defined as follows.
 All the vacuum states are labeled by 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,...,N$
\end_inset

 of which the terminal states are 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,...,N_{T}$
\end_inset

.
 During a time step 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t$
\end_inset

, an initial 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region of type 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 expands into 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{j}\equiv e^{3H_{j}\delta t}$
\end_inset

 independent daughter 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions of type 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 Each of the daughter 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions then has probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{jk}$
\end_inset

 of changing into an 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region of type 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 (for convenience we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{jj}\equiv1-\sum_{k\neq j}\kappa_{jk}$
\end_inset

).
 The process is repeated 
\emph on
ad infinitum
\emph default
 for each resulting 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region, except for 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions of terminal types.
 A newly created 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region of terminal type will admit no further transitions and will not
 expand (or, perhaps, will expand only by a fixed amount of slow-roll inflation
 occurring immediately after nucleation).
 This imitates the behavior of anti-de Sitter or Minkowski vacua that do
 not admit further bubble nucleations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To implement the RV cutoff in this model, let us consider the probability
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}(n,n';k)$
\end_inset

 of producing a finite total number 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 of terminal 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions of which 
\begin_inset Formula $n'$
\end_inset

 are of type 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, starting from one initial 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region of (nonterminal) type 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 A generating function for this distribution can be defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g_{j}(z,q;k)\equiv\negmedspace\sum_{n,n'=0}^{\infty}\negmedspace z^{n}q^{n'}p_{j}(n,n';k)\equiv\left\langle z^{n}q^{n'}\right\rangle _{n<\infty}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

One can show that this generating function satisfies the following system
 of nonlinear algebraic equations,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g_{j}^{1/n_{k}}(z,q;k)=\sum_{i=1}^{N_{T}}\kappa_{ki}zq^{\delta_{ij}}+\negmedspace\sum_{i=N_{T}+1}^{N}\negmedspace\kappa_{ki}g_{j}(z,q;i),\label{eq:g equ landscape}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

I will merely sketch the derivation of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ landscape"

\end_inset

) here.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This equation is similar to the equations for generating functions used
 in the theory of branching processes (see 
\emph on
e.g.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

the book
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "AthreyaNey:1972:BP"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for a mathematically rigorous presentation).
 A more detailed derivation will be given in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Derivation-of-Eq."

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{j}$
\end_inset

 satisfies a multiplicative property analogous to Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g multiplicative"

\end_inset

).
 This property applies to the 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{k}$
\end_inset

 independent daughter 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions created by expansion from an 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region of type 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{j}(z,q;k)$
\end_inset

, which is the expectation value of 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{n}q^{n'}$
\end_inset

 in an initial 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region of type 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, is equal to the product of 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{k}$
\end_inset

 expectation values of 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{n}q^{n'}$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{k}$
\end_inset

 daughter 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions (which may be of different types).
 The latter expectation value is given by the right-hand side of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ landscape"

\end_inset

).
 This yields Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ landscape"

\end_inset

) after raising both sides to the power 
\begin_inset Formula $1/n_{k}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the generating functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{j}$
\end_inset

 are known, the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}(n,n';k)$
\end_inset

 can be recovered by computing derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{j}(z,q;k)$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q=0$
\end_inset

.
 Further, the mean fraction of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions of type 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 at fixed total number 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 of terminal 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions is found as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(j|n)\equiv\frac{\left\langle \left.n'\right|_{n}\right\rangle }{n}=\frac{\partial_{z}^{n}\partial_{q}g_{j}(z=0,q=1;k)}{n\,\partial_{z}^{n}g_{j}(z=0,q=1;k)}.\label{eq:p n' n lim}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then the RV cutoff 
\emph on
defines
\emph default
 the probability of terminal type 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, among all the possible 
\emph on
terminal
\emph default
 types, through the limit 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(j)\equiv\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}p(j|n)=\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\frac{\partial_{z}^{n}\partial_{q}g_{j}(z=0,q=1;k)}{n\,\partial_{z}^{n}g_{j}(z=0,q=1;k)},\label{eq:p n'n lim 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

similarly to Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pQ RV"

\end_inset

).
 Again one expects that the limit exists and is independent of the initial
 bubble type, as long as the initial bubble is not of terminal type.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a specific example requiring fewer calculations, let us consider a toy
 model with only three bubble types.
 There is one de Sitter (
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda>0$
\end_inset

) vacuum labeled 
\begin_inset Formula $j=3$
\end_inset

 that can decay into two possible anti-de Sitter terminal bubbles labeled
 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j=2$
\end_inset

.
 The growth rate 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}$
\end_inset

 and the nucleation probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{31}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{32}$
\end_inset

 are assumed known.
 To mimic interesting features of the landscape, let us also assume that
 there is a period of slow-roll inflation inside the bubbles 1 and 2, generating
 respectively 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{2}$
\end_inset

 additional 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-foldings of inflationary expansion after nucleation.
 Hence, the model is determined by the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{31}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{32}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{1}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 For convenience we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{33}\equiv1-\kappa_{31}-\kappa_{32}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now perform the calculations for the RV cutoff in this simple model.
 There are only two generating functions, 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(z,q;k)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}(z,q;k)$
\end_inset

, that need to be considered.
 The only meaningful initial value is 
\begin_inset Formula $k=3$
\end_inset

 (
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default
, the initial bubble is of de Sitter type) since the two other bubble types
 do not lead to eternal inflation.
 Hence, we will suppress the argument 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{j}(z,q;k)$
\end_inset

.
 We also need to modify Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ landscape"

\end_inset

) to take into account the additional expansion inside the terminal bubbles.
 Let us denote the volume expansion factors by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Z_{1}\equiv e^{3N_{1}},\quad Z_{2}\equiv e^{3N_{2}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Then the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 are solutions of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
g_{1}^{1/n_{3}} & =\kappa_{31}z^{Z_{1}}q^{Z_{1}}+\kappa_{32}z^{Z_{2}}+\kappa_{33}g_{1},\\
g_{2}^{1/n_{3}} & =\kappa_{31}z^{Z_{1}}+\kappa_{32}z^{Z_{2}}q^{Z_{2}}+\kappa_{33}g_{2}.
\end{align}

\end_inset

An explicit solution of these equations is impossible for a general 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}$
\end_inset

 (barring the special cases 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}=2,3,4$
\end_inset

).
 Nevertheless, sufficient information about the limit
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:p n'n lim 1"

\end_inset

) can be obtained by the following method.
 Introduce the auxiliary function 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)$
\end_inset

 as the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $F>0$
\end_inset

 of the algebraic equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F^{1/n_{3}}=x+\kappa_{33}F,\label{eq:F def}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

choosing the branch connected to the value 
\begin_inset Formula $F(0)=0$
\end_inset

.
 (It is straightforward to see that Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:F def"

\end_inset

), has at most two positive solutions, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)$
\end_inset

 is always the smaller solution of the two.) The generating functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 are then expressed through 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
g_{1}(z,q) & =F(\kappa_{31}z^{Z_{1}}q^{Z_{1}}+\kappa_{32}z^{Z_{2}}),\label{eq:g1 through F}\\
g_{2}(z,q) & =F(\kappa_{31}z^{Z_{1}}+\kappa_{32}z^{Z_{2}}q^{Z_{2}}).\label{eq:g2 through F}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The limit
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:p n'n lim 1"

\end_inset

) involves derivatives of these functions of very high order with respect
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 We note that the function 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)$
\end_inset

 is analytic; thus the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 are also analytic in 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To evaluate the high-order derivatives, we need an elementary result from
 complex analysis.
 The asymptotic growth of high-order derivatives of an analytic function
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)$
\end_inset

 is determined by the location of the singularities of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)$
\end_inset

 in the complex 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 plane.
 The required result can be derived by the following elementary argument.
 Consider the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $d^{n}f/dz^{n}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

, and assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)$
\end_inset

 admits an expansion around the singularity 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}$
\end_inset

 nearest to 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

, such as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(z)=c_{0}+c_{1}\left(z-z_{*}\right)^{s}+...,\label{eq:f sing}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s\neq0,1,2,...$
\end_inset

 is the power of the leading-order singularity, and the omitted terms are
 either higher powers of 
\begin_inset Formula $z-z_{*}$
\end_inset

 or singularities at points 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 located further away from 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
 The singularity structure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:f sing"

\end_inset

) yields the large-
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 asymptotics
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{d^{n}f}{dz^{n}}\right|_{z=0}\negmedspace\approx c_{1}(-z_{*})^{s}\frac{\Gamma(n-s)}{\Gamma(-s)}z_{*}^{-n}+...\label{eq:large-n derivative}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This formula enables one to evaluate large-
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 limits such as Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:p n'n lim 1"

\end_inset

).
 It can be seen from this formula that any other singular point 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 located further away from 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 gives a contribution that is smaller by the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|z_{*}^{\prime}/z_{*}\right|^{s-n}$
\end_inset

.
 The contribution of a subdominant singularity of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(z-z_{*}\right)^{s'}$
\end_inset

, 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

at the same point 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

 but with a higher power 
\begin_inset Formula $s'>s$
\end_inset

, is suppressed, in comparison with the term in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:large-n derivative"

\end_inset

), by the factor 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Gamma(n-s')}{\Gamma(n-s)}\frac{\Gamma(-s)}{\Gamma(-s')}\approx\frac{1}{\left(n-1\right)^{s'-s}}\frac{\Gamma(-s)}{\Gamma(-s')}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It is clear that the terms omitted from Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:large-n derivative"

\end_inset

) indeed give subleading contributions at large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and so Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:large-n derivative"

\end_inset

) is indeed the leading asymptotic term at 
\begin_inset Formula $n\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To proceed, we need to determine the location of the singularities of 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)$
\end_inset

 is obtained as an intersection of a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{1/n_{3}}$
\end_inset

 and a straight line 
\begin_inset Formula $x+\kappa_{33}F$
\end_inset

, there will be a value 
\begin_inset Formula $x=x_{*}$
\end_inset

 where the straight line is tangent to the curve.
 At this value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 the function 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)$
\end_inset

 has a singularity of the type
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F(x)=F(x_{*})+F_{1}\sqrt{x-x_{*}}+O(x-x_{*}),\label{eq:F sqrt}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a constant that can be easily determined; we omit further details that
 will not be required below.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{*}$
\end_inset

 is found from the condition that 
\begin_inset Formula $dF/dx$
\end_inset

 diverge at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=x_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $dF/dx$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq x_{*}$
\end_inset

 is found as the derivative of the inverse function, or by taking the derivative
 of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:F def"

\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{dF}{dx}=\frac{1}{\frac{1}{n_{3}}F^{\frac{1}{n_{3}}-1}-\Gamma_{33}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This expression diverges at the values 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F(x_{*}) & =\left(n_{3}\kappa_{33}\right)^{-\frac{n_{3}}{n_{3}-1}},\\
x_{*} & =\left(n_{3}-1\right)\kappa_{33}F(x_{*})=\kappa_{33}\frac{n_{3}-1}{n_{3}^{n_{3}/(n_{3}-1)}}.
\end{align}

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{33}\approx1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}\gg1$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{*}$
\end_inset

 is a constant of order 1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rather than compute the limit
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:p n' n lim"

\end_inset

) directly, we will perform an easier computation of the 
\emph on
ratio
\emph default
 of the mean number of bubbles of types 1 and 2 at fixed total number 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 of terminal bubbles, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\left\langle \left.n_{(1)}^{\prime}\right|_{n}\right\rangle }{\left\langle \left.n_{(2)}^{\prime}\right|_{n}\right\rangle }=\frac{\partial_{z}^{n}\partial_{q}g_{1}(z=0,q=1)}{\partial_{z}^{n}\partial_{q}g_{2}(z=0,q=1)}.\label{eq:n ratio lim}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{q}g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{q}g_{2}$
\end_inset

 can be evaluated directly through Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g1 through F"

\end_inset

)–(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g2 through F"

\end_inset

).
 For instance, we compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{q}g_{1}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{\partial g_{1}(z,q)}{\partial q}\right|_{q=1}=F^{\prime}(\kappa_{31}z^{Z_{1}}+\kappa_{32}z^{Z_{2}})\kappa_{31}Z_{1}z^{Z_{1}}.\label{eq:dg1 dq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It is clear that the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{q}g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{q}g_{2}$
\end_inset

 have a singularity at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the singularity 
\begin_inset Formula $x=x_{*}$
\end_inset

 of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}$
\end_inset

 is found from the condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\kappa_{31}z_{*}^{Z_{1}}+\kappa_{32}z_{*}^{Z_{2}}=x_{*}.\label{eq:z star equ}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Let us analyze this equation in order to estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 If the nucleation rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{31}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{32}$
\end_inset

 differ by many orders of magnitude, we may expect that one of the terms
 in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:z star equ"

\end_inset

), say 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{31}z_{*}^{Z_{1}}$
\end_inset

, dominates.
 Then the value 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}$
\end_inset

 is well approximated by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
z_{*}\approx\left(\frac{x_{*}}{\kappa_{31}}\right)^{1/Z_{1}}.\label{eq:z star ans}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This approximation is justified if the first term in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:z star equ"

\end_inset

) indeed dominates, which is the case if
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{\kappa_{32}}{x_{*}}\right)^{1/Z_{2}}\ll\left(\frac{\kappa_{31}}{x_{*}}\right)^{1/Z_{1}}.\label{eq:gamma32 cond}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If the reversed inequality holds, we can relabel the bubble types 1 and
 2 and still use Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:z star ans"

\end_inset

).
 If neither Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gamma32 cond"

\end_inset

) nor the reversed inequality hold, the approximation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:z star ans"

\end_inset

) for 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}$
\end_inset

 can be used only as an order-of-magnitude estimate.
 To be specific, let us assume that the condition
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gamma32 cond"

\end_inset

) holds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now compute the ratio
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:n ratio lim"

\end_inset

) asymptotically for large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 using Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:F sqrt"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:large-n derivative"

\end_inset

).
 The singularities of the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}$
\end_inset

 are directly due to the singularity of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Then the dominant singularity structure of the function
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dg1 dq"

\end_inset

) is found as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{\partial g_{1}(z,q)}{\partial q}\right|_{q=1}\approx\left.\frac{\kappa_{31}Z_{1}z^{Z_{1}}}{2\sqrt{\frac{\partial}{\partial z}\left(\kappa_{31}z^{Z_{1}}+\kappa_{32}z^{Z_{2}}\right)}}\right|_{z=z_{*}}\frac{F_{1}}{\sqrt{z-z_{*}}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This fits Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:f sing"

\end_inset

), where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)\equiv\partial_{q}g_{1}(z,q=1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s=-1/2$
\end_inset

.
 After canceling the common 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dependent factors, we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{p(1)}{p(2)}=\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\frac{\left\langle \left.n_{(1)}^{\prime}\right|_{n}\right\rangle }{\left\langle \left.n_{(2)}^{\prime}\right|_{n}\right\rangle }=\left.\frac{\kappa_{31}Z_{1}z^{Z_{1}}}{\kappa_{32}Z_{2}z^{Z_{2}}}\right|_{z=z_{*}}.\label{eq:prob ratio ans}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is the final probability ratio found by applying the RV cutoff to a
 toy model landscape containing two terminal vacua.
 Substituting the approximation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:z star ans"

\end_inset

), which assumes the condition
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gamma32 cond"

\end_inset

), we can simplify Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:prob ratio ans"

\end_inset

) to a more suggestive form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{p(1)}{p(2)}\approx\frac{\kappa_{31}Z_{1}}{\kappa_{32}Z_{2}}\left(\frac{\kappa_{31}}{x_{*}}\right)^{-1+Z_{2}/Z_{1}}.\label{eq:new answer}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We can interpret this as the ratio of nucleation probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{31}/\kappa_{32}$
\end_inset

 times the ratio of volume expansion factors, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{1}/Z_{2}$
\end_inset

, times a certain 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

correction
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 factor.
 As we have seen, the correction factor is actually a complicated function
 of all the parameters of the landscape.
 The correction factor takes the simple form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{\kappa_{31}}{x_{*}}\right)^{-1+Z_{2}/Z_{1}}\label{eq:correction factor}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 only if the condition
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gamma32 cond"

\end_inset

) holds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note that the result
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:new answer"

\end_inset

) is similar to but does not exactly coincide with the results obtained
 in previously studied volume-based measures.
 For comparison, the volume-based measures proposed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Garriga:2005av"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Linde:2007nm"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 both yield
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{p(1)}{p(2)}=\frac{\kappa_{31}Z_{1}}{\kappa_{32}Z_{2}},\label{eq:old answer}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is readily interpreted as the ratio of nucleation probabilities enhanced
 by the ratio of volume factors.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

holographic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 measure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bousso:2006ev"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, which is not a volume-based measure, gives the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{p(1)}{p(2)}=\frac{\kappa_{31}}{\kappa_{32}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

that does not depend on the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-foldings after nucleation.
 While the discrepancy between volume-based and worldline-based measures
 is to be expected, the correction factor that distinguishes Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:new answer"

\end_inset

) from Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:old answer"

\end_inset

) is model-dependent and may be either negligible or significant depending
 on the particular model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a specific example, consider bubbles that nucleate with equal probability,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{31}=\kappa_{32}\ll1$
\end_inset

, but have very different expansion factors, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{1}\gg Z_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then the condition
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gamma32 cond"

\end_inset

) holds and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

correction
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 factor is given by Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:correction factor"

\end_inset

), which is an exponentially large quantity of order 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{31}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Qualitatively this means that the RV measure rewards bubbles with a larger
 slow-roll expansion factor even more than previous volume-based measures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, if 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{1}=Z_{2}$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{31}\gg\kappa_{32}$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

correction
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 factor disappears and we recover the result found in the other measures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To conclude, we note that the result
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:prob ratio ans"

\end_inset

) does not depend on the durations of 
\emph on
time
\emph default
 spent during slow-roll inflation inside the terminal bubbles, but only
 on the number of 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-foldings gained.
 This confirms that the RV measure does not suffer from the youngness paradox.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we were able to apply of the RV measure to the comparison of the
 abundances of terminal vacua.
 In the next section, the RV measure can be extended to arbitrary observables
 in landscape models.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Regulating the total number of bubbles
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Extending-the-RV"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The RV measure prescription as formulated in the previous section applies
 only to the calculation of abundances of terminal bubbles.
 We will now extend the RV measure to computing arbitrary statistics on
 any landscape.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first note that RV measure prescription can be applied, strictly speaking,
 only to landscapes that contain 
\emph on
some
\emph default
 terminal bubble types (
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

vacua from which no further tunneling is possible).
 However, this limitation is quite benign, for two reasons.
 First, a landscape without any Minkowski or AdS states is not expected
 to be realized in any realistic string theory scenario without an exceptional
 amount of fine-tuning.
 Second, the previously proposed volume-based and the world-line based measure
 prescriptions agree for a landscape without terminal bubble types
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vanchurin:2006qp,Bousso:2006ev"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 One may therefore consider the measure problem as solved in such landscapes
 and turn one's attention to more realistic landscapes where terminal bubble
 types are present.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us take an initial bubble of a nonterminal type 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and consider the statistical ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}(j)$
\end_inset

 of all possible evolutions of the initial bubble such that the total number
 of nucleated bubbles of all types is finite and equals 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 (not counting the initial bubble).
 The total number of nucleated bubbles in a multiverse can be finite only
 if terminal bubbles nucleate everywhere and merge globally to the future
 of the initial bubble.
 This can happen by rare chance; however, it is important the total probability
 of all events in the ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}(j)$
\end_inset

 is always nonzero for any given 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, so that the ensembles 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}(j)$
\end_inset

 are well-defined and nonempty.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}(j)$
\end_inset

 may be described in the language of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

transition trees
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 used in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bousso:2006ev"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The ensemble consists of all trees that have a total number 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

 of bubbles, including the initial bubble of type 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 The trees in 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}(j)$
\end_inset

 are finite because all the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

outer
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 leaves are bubbles of terminal types.
 The motivation for considering the ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}(j)$
\end_inset

 is that a finite but very large tree (with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 large) is a controlled approximation to infinite trees that typically occur.
 Hence, we are motivated to consider 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}(j)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 finite but very large.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}(j)$
\end_inset

 differs from the ensemble defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2008yb"
literal "true"

\end_inset

; in 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}(j)$
\end_inset

 the total number of bubbles of 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 types is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, rather than the total number of 
\emph on
terminal
\emph default
 bubbles as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2008yb"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Thus, the current proposal, which appears more natural, is an extension
 of that of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2008yb"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Future work will show whether this technical difference is significant;
 presently I will investigate the consequences of the current proposal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once the ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}(j)$
\end_inset

 is defined, one may consider the statistical distribution of some cosmological
 observable within the multiverses belonging to the set 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}(j)$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, one can count the number of bubbles of some type 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, or the number of observers within bubbles of type 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, or the number of observations of some physical process, etc.
 In a very large multiverse belonging to 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}(j)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n\gg1$
\end_inset

, one may expect that the statistics of observations will be independent
 of the initial bubble type 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, this will be one of the results of this chapter.
 Hence, let us suppress the argument 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and write simply 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each multiverse belonging to 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}$
\end_inset

 has a naturally defined probability weight, which is simply equal to the
 probability of realizing that multiverse.
 This probability weight needs to be taken into account when computing the
 statistical distributions of observables.
 The sum of all probability weights of multiverses within 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}$
\end_inset

 is equal to the total probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}$
\end_inset

, which is exponentially small for large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 but always nonzero.
 Since the multiverses from the ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}$
\end_inset

 are by construction finite, 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

each multiverse supports only a finite total number of possible observers,
 we are assured that any statistics we desire to compute on 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}$
\end_inset

 will be well-defined.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now consider the probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q|E_{n})$
\end_inset

 of some interesting observable 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 within the ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}$
\end_inset

 and take the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $n\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
 One expects that the probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q|E_{n})$
\end_inset

 will have a well-defined limit for large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(Q)\equiv\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}p(Q|E_{n}).\label{eq:PQ lim}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It was shown in previous work on the RV prescription
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2008yb,Winitzki:2008ph"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 that the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q)$
\end_inset

 is well-defined for a simplest toy landscape as well as in the case of
 random-walk eternal inflation.
 In this work I extend these results to a general landscape scenario.
 Below (Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Uniqueness-of-the"

\end_inset

) I will prove rigorously that the limit
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:PQ lim"

\end_inset

) indeed exists and is independent of the chosen initial bubble type 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 as long as the initial bubble is not of terminal type and as long as the
 landscape is irreducible (every vacuum can be reached from every other
 non-terminal vacuum by a chain of nucleations).
 Thus, the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q)$
\end_inset

 is unique and well-defined.
 This distribution is the final result of applying the RV prescription to
 the observable 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practice, it is necessary to compute the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q|E_{n})$
\end_inset

 asymptotically in the limit of large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 A direct numerical calculation of probabilities in that limit by enumerating
 all possible evolution trees is extremely difficult because of the exponential
 growth of the number of possible evolutions.
 Instead, I derive explicit formulas for the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p(Q)$
\end_inset

 in a generic landscape by evaluating the limit
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:PQ lim"

\end_inset

) analytically.
 These formulas are the main result of the present chapter.
\end_layout

