\begin_layout Standard
I begin by applying the RV measure to a toy landscape with very few vacua.
 Using this simple example, I develop the computational techniques needed
 for the practical evaluation of the limit such as Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:PQ lim"

\end_inset

).
 In Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:A-general-landscape"

\end_inset

 the same techniques will be extended to a more general landscape with an
 arbitrary number of vacua.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:RV-cutoff-for-landscape"

\end_inset

 we considered the simplest possible nontrivial landscape: a single dS and
 two AdS (terminal) vacua.
 The next least complicated example that can be treated analytically is
 a toy landscape having two nonterminal and two terminal vacua.
 This toy landscape was called the 
\emph on

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\emph default
FABI
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 model in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Garriga:2005av"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and consists of the vacua labeled 
\begin_inset Formula $F,I,A,B$
\end_inset

 with the transition diagram 
\begin_inset Formula $A\leftarrow F\leftrightarrow I\rightarrow B$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, one assumes that the vacuum 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

false
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 vacuum) can nucleate only bubbles of types 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, the vacuum 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

intermediate
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 vacuum) can nucleate bubbles of types 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, while 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are terminal vacua that do not have further nucleations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To describe the finitely produced probability in this landscape, I use the
 discrete picture called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

eternal inflation in a box
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2005ya,Winitzki:2008yb"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, which is closely related to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

square bubble
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 approximation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bousso:2007nd"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 In this picture, one considers the evolution of discrete, causally disjoint
 homogeneous 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions in discrete time.
 All possible vacuum types are labeled by 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,...,N$
\end_inset

.
 During one time step of order 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t=H_{j}^{-1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the local Hubble rate in a given 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region of type 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, the evolution consists of expanding the 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region into 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
e^{3H_{j}\delta t}=e^{3}\equiv\nu
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 daughter 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions of type 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 Each of the daughter 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions has then the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{j\rightarrow k}$
\end_inset

 of changing immediately into an 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region of type 
\begin_inset Formula $k\neq j$
\end_inset

; this imitates a nucleation of a horizon-size bubble of type 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 If no transition has taken place, the daughter 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region retains its type 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 For convenience, we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\kappa_{j\rightarrow j}\equiv1-\sum_{k\neq j}\kappa_{j\rightarrow k}\label{eq:kappa jj def}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 the probability of no transitions during one Hubble time.
 The process of expansion and transition is continued 
\emph on
ad infinitum
\emph default
, independently for each resulting 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions of terminal types will admit no further transitions and will not
 expand further (except, perhaps, by a fixed amount due to slow-roll inflation
 occurring immediately after nucleation).
 An example simulation is shown in Fig.
