\begin_layout Subsection
Bubble abundances
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Bubble-abundance"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first task is to compute the relative abundance of bubbles of different
 types.
 Consider the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p(n_{\text{tot}},n_{F},n_{I},n_{A},n_{B};k)$
\end_inset

 of having a finite total number 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{tot}}$
\end_inset

 of bubbles of which 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{j}$
\end_inset

 are of type 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $j=F,I,A,B$
\end_inset

), if one starts from a single initial 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region of type 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $k=F,I$
\end_inset

).
 By construction, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\neq0$
\end_inset

 only for 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{tot}}=n_{F}+n_{I}+n_{A}+n_{B}$
\end_inset

.
 A generating function for this probability distribution can be defined
 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
g(z,\left\{ q_{j}\right\} ;k) & \equiv\negmedspace\sum_{n{\geq0,n}_{j}\geq0}\negmedspace z^{n}p(n,\left\{ n_{j}\right\} ;k)\negmedspace\prod_{j=F,I,A,B}\negmedspace q_{j}^{n_{j}}\nonumber \\
 & \equiv\left\langle z^{n}q_{F}^{n_{F}}q_{I}^{n_{I}}q_{A}^{n_{A}}q_{B}^{n_{B}}\right\rangle _{n<\infty;k},\label{eq:g FABI def}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle ...\right\rangle _{n<\infty;k}$
\end_inset

 stands for a statistical average restricted to events with a finite total
 number 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 of bubbles nucleated to the future of an initial bubble of type 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 plays a crucial role in the entire calculation.
 Since we will be only interested in the initial bubbles of types 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

, let us denote 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F(z,\left\{ q_{j}\right\} )\equiv g(z,\left\{ q_{j}\right\} ;F),\quad I(z,\left\{ q_{j}\right\} )\equiv g(z,\left\{ q_{j}\right\} ;I).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The generating functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 satisfy the following system of nonlinear algebraic equations
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Winitzki:2008yb"
literal "true"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F^{\frac{1}{\nu}} & =zq_{A}\kappa_{FA}+zq_{I}\kappa_{FI}I+\kappa_{FF}F,\label{eq:F equ 1}\\
I^{\frac{1}{\nu}} & =zq_{B}\kappa_{IB}+zq_{F}\kappa_{IF}F+\kappa_{II}I.\label{eq:I equ 1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Here we denoted for brevity 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{FF}\equiv1-\kappa_{FA}-\kappa_{FI}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{II}\equiv1-\kappa_{IB}-\kappa_{IF}$
\end_inset

; within our assumptions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{FF}\approx1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{II}\approx1$
\end_inset

.
 In Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:F equ 1"

\end_inset

)–(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:I equ 1"

\end_inset

) the generating variable 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 multiplies only the terms that correspond to changing the type of the 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region (which imitates the nucleation of new bubbles) but not the terms
 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{FF}F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{II}I$
\end_inset

 that correspond to the eventuality of not changing the type of the 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region during one Hubble time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The nonlinear equations
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:F equ 1"

\end_inset

)–(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:I equ 1"

\end_inset

) may have several real-valued solutions, as well as complex-valued solutions
 that are certainly not of physical interest.
 In particular, for 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}=1$
\end_inset

 there exists the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

trivial
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 solution 
\begin_inset Formula $F=I=1$
\end_inset

 as well as a nontrivial solution with 
\begin_inset Formula $F\ll1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I\ll1$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, for 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 near 0 there exists the solution that approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $F(0)=I(0)=0$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F=\left(zq_{A}\kappa_{FA}\right)^{\nu}+O(z^{2\nu-1}),\;I\approx\left(zq_{B}\kappa_{IB}\right)^{\nu}+O(z^{2\nu-1}),\label{eq:approx sol F I at z0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

as well as the solution 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F\approx\kappa_{FF}^{\frac{\nu}{1-\nu}}\approx1,\quad I\approx\kappa_{II}^{\frac{\nu}{1-\nu}}\approx1\label{eq:approx sol bad}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and solutions where 
\begin_inset Formula $F\approx1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I\approx0$
\end_inset

 and vice versa.
 It is important to determine the solution branch 
\begin_inset Formula $F(z),I(z)$
\end_inset

 that has the physical significance as the actual generating function of
 the finitely produced distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F(z),I(z)$
\end_inset

 are solutions of algebraic equations and thus are continuous functions
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 that are analytic everywhere in complex 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 plane except for branch cuts.
 It is easy to see that the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $F=I=1$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1,q_{j}=1$
\end_inset

 is continuously connected with the solution
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:approx sol bad"

\end_inset

) at 
\begin_inset Formula $z\approx0$
\end_inset

, while the solution
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:approx sol F I at z0"

\end_inset

) is continued to a solution with 
\begin_inset Formula $F(z)\ll1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I(z)\ll1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $0<z<1$
\end_inset

.
 The values 
\begin_inset Formula $F(1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I(1)$
\end_inset

 are the probabilities of the events that the evolution of an initial bubble
 of type 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 ends globally.
 These probabilities are extremely small and of order 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{FA}^{\nu}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{IB}^{\nu}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 This is easy to interpret because, for instance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{FA}^{\nu}$
\end_inset

 is the probability of nucleating 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 terminal regions at once after one Hubble time within an 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region of type 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, the generating functions for the finitely produced distribution
 of bubbles are given by the solution branch having 
\begin_inset Formula $F\ll1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I\ll1$
\end_inset

 rather than by the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $F=I=1$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

.
 More precisely, the physically meaningful solution 
\begin_inset Formula $F(z),I(z)$
\end_inset

 is selected by the asymptotic behavior
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:approx sol F I at z0"

\end_inset

).
 This argument removes the ambiguity inherent in solving Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:F equ 1"

\end_inset

)–(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:I equ 1"

\end_inset

).
 Below we refer to the branch of solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $F(z),I(z)$
\end_inset

 connected to the nontrivial solution
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:approx sol F I at z0"

\end_inset

) near 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

main branch.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once the main branch of the generating functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z,\{q_{j}\};k)$
\end_inset

 are known, one can express the mean number of bubbles of type 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $i=F,I,A,B$
\end_inset

) at a fixed total number 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{tot}}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p(i|n_{\text{tot}})\equiv\frac{\left\langle n_{i}\right\rangle _{n_{\text{tot}}}}{n_{\text{tot}}}=\frac{\partial_{z}^{n_{\text{tot}}}\partial_{q_{i}}g(z=0,\left\{ q_{j}=1\right\} ;k)}{n_{\text{tot}}\partial_{z}^{n_{\text{tot}}}g(z=0,\left\{ q_{j}=1\right\} ;k)}.\label{eq:p n' n lim}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

One expects that the limit of this ratio at 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{tot}}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 will be independent of the initial bubble type 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 since the ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n_{\text{tot}}}$
\end_inset

 will consist of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions having a very long evolution, so that the initial conditions are
 forgotten.
 Below I will show explicitly that this is indeed the case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is more convenient to compute the ratios of the number of bubbles of
 types 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i'$
\end_inset

 at fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{tot}}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{p(i|n_{\text{tot}})}{p(i'|n_{\text{tot}})}=\left.\frac{\partial_{z}^{n_{\text{tot}}}\partial_{q_{i}}g}{\partial_{z}^{n_{\text{tot}}}\partial_{q_{i'}}g}\right|_{z=0,\left\{ q_{j}=1\right\} }.\label{eq:i i' ratio ntot}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Then one only needs to compute derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{q_{i}}g\equiv g_{,q_{i}}$
\end_inset

 evaluated at 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}=1$
\end_inset

.
 These derivatives satisfy a system of 
\emph on
linear
\emph default
 equations that can be easily derived from Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:F equ 1"

\end_inset

)–(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:I equ 1"

\end_inset

).
 For instance, the derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{,q_{A}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{,q_{A}}$
\end_inset

 satisfy
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{1}{\nu}F^{\frac{1}{\nu}-1}F_{,q_{A}} & =z\kappa_{FA}+z\kappa_{FI}I_{,q_{A}}+\kappa_{FF}F_{,q_{A}},\\
\frac{1}{\nu}I^{\frac{1}{\nu}-1}I_{,q_{A}} & =z\kappa_{IF}F_{,q_{A}}+\kappa_{II}I_{,q_{A}}.
\end{align}

\end_inset

Rewriting these equations in a matrix form, we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{1}{\nu}F^{\frac{1}{\nu}-1}-\kappa_{FF} & -z\kappa_{FI}\\
-z\kappa_{IF} & \frac{1}{\nu}I^{\frac{1}{\nu}-1}-\kappa_{II}
\end{array}\right)\left[\begin{array}{c}
F_{,q_{A}}\\
I_{,q_{A}}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{c}
z\kappa_{FA}\\
0
\end{array}\right].\label{eq:FIqA eqs}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The coefficients of the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

-dependent matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{M}(z)\equiv\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{1}{\nu}F^{\frac{1}{\nu}-1}-\kappa_{FF} & -z\kappa_{FI}\\
-z\kappa_{IF} & \frac{1}{\nu}I^{\frac{1}{\nu}-1}-\kappa_{II}
\end{array}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 are the main branch of solutions of the nonlinear equations
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:F equ 1"

\end_inset

)–(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:I equ 1"

\end_inset

) at 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}=1$
\end_inset

 but at arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can verify using Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:approx sol F I at z0"

\end_inset

) that the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}(z)$
\end_inset

 is invertible near 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
 Hence the solution of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FIqA eqs"

\end_inset

) can be written, at least within some range of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}(z)$
\end_inset

 remains invertible, as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\begin{array}{c}
F_{,q_{A}}\\
I_{,q_{A}}
\end{array}\right]=\hat{M}^{-1}(z)\left[\begin{array}{c}
z\kappa_{FA}\\
0
\end{array}\right].\label{eq:FqA eq 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Similarly, the derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{,q_{F}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{,q_{F}}$
\end_inset

 satisfy the equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{M}(z)\left[\begin{array}{c}
F_{,q_{F}}\\
I_{,q_{F}}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
z\kappa_{IF}F
\end{array}\right],\label{eq:FqF equ 1 pre}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

whose solution is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\begin{array}{c}
F_{,q_{F}}\\
I_{,q_{F}}
\end{array}\right]=\hat{M}^{-1}(z)\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
z\kappa_{IF}F
\end{array}\right].\label{eq:FqF eq 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Other generating functions can be expressed in the same manner.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One could in principle obtain a numerical solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{,q_{A}}(z)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{,q_{A}}(z)$
\end_inset

, and all the other generating functions at any given value of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 However, the numerical solution is not particularly useful at this point
 because the next step in the calculation is the evaluation of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:i i' ratio ntot"

\end_inset

) in the limit of very large 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{tot}}$
\end_inset

, for instance,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{p(A|n_{\text{tot}})}{p(F|n_{\text{tot}})}=\left.\frac{\partial_{z}^{n_{\text{tot}}}F_{,q_{A}}}{\partial_{z}^{n_{\text{tot}}}F_{,q_{F}}}\right|_{z=0}.\label{eq:ratio a to f}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

It is generally not feasible to compute the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-th derivative of a numerically obtained function in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $n\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, because the unavoidable round-off errors are amplified by a fixed factor
