 Therefore, we need a way to evaluate the ratio
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:i i' ratio ntot"

\end_inset

) in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{tot}}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 without using numerics.
 Indeed we will be able to compute the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A)/p(F)$
\end_inset

.
 We will also show that, for instance,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{p(A)}{p(F)}=\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\left.\frac{\partial_{z}^{n}F_{,q_{A}}}{\partial_{z}^{n}F_{,q_{F}}}\right|_{z=0}=\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\left.\frac{\partial_{z}^{n}I_{,q_{A}}}{\partial_{z}^{n}I_{,q_{F}}}\right|_{z=0};\label{eq:ratio a to f lim}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

in other words, that the final RV-regulated ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A)/p(F)$
\end_inset

 is independent of whether the initial bubble is of type 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 or of type 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To proceed, we use the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{,q_{A}}(z)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{,q_{A}}(z)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{,q_{F}}(z)$
\end_inset

, etc.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

are analytic functions of the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 The asymptotic growth of high-order derivatives of an analytic function
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)$
\end_inset

 is determined by the location of the singularities of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)$
\end_inset

 in the complex 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 plane, as shown in Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:large-n derivative"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now need to determine the location of the singularities of 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{,q_{A}}(z)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{,q_{A}}(z)$
\end_inset

, etc., as functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 This task is much simplified once we observe that all these quantities
 are expressed through the inverse matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}^{-1}(z)$
\end_inset

, and hence it remains to analyze the singularities of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}^{-1}(z)$
\end_inset

.
 That matrix can be singular at some value 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

 either because some of the coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}(z)$
\end_inset

 are singular, or because the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}(z)$
\end_inset

 is degenerate (noninvertible) at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 The coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}(z)$
\end_inset

 depend on solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $F(z),I(z)$
\end_inset

 of algebraic equations
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:F equ 1"

\end_inset

)–(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:I equ 1"

\end_inset

) at 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}=1$
\end_inset

 and thus cannot be divergent as functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 These coefficients can be singular only in that some derivative in 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 diverges.
 The derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{,z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{,z}$
\end_inset

 satisfy the equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{M}(z)\left[\begin{array}{c}
F_{,z}\\
I_{,z}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\kappa_{FA}+\kappa_{FI}I\\
\kappa_{IB}+\kappa_{IF}F
\end{array}\right].\label{eq:equations for FI derivatives}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{,z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{,z}$
\end_inset

 diverge only for those 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 for which the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}(z)$
\end_inset

 is degenerate.
 For these 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, all the derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{,z}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{,z}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{,q_{A}}$
\end_inset

, etc.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

will be divergent at the same time since they are all proportional to the
 inverse matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}^{-1}(z)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note that the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}(z)$
\end_inset

 is the Jacobian of the nonlinear system
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:F equ 1"

\end_inset

)–(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:I equ 1"

\end_inset

).
 As long as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}(z)$
\end_inset

 is nondegenerate, all the different branches of the solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $F(z),I(z)$
\end_inset

 do not meet and remain smooth functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 As we noted above, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

main
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 branch 
\begin_inset Formula $F(z),I(z)$
\end_inset

 is the one connected to the nontrivial solution
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:approx sol F I at z0"

\end_inset

) at 
\begin_inset Formula $z\approx0$
\end_inset

.
 The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}(z)$
\end_inset

 is nondegenerate near 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

; therefore, the solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $F(z),I(z)$
\end_inset

 remain smooth functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}(z)$
\end_inset

 is nondenegerate.
 We conclude that the only possible singularities of 
\begin_inset Formula $F(z),I(z)$
\end_inset

 are those values 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\hat{M}(z)=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Below it will be shown that the behavior of 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\hat{M}(z)$
\end_inset

 near 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\det\hat{M}(z)\approx c_{1}\sqrt{z_{*}-z},\label{eq:det M sing 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

of the form
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:f sing"

\end_inset

) with 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 It now follows from Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FqA eq 1"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FqF eq 1"

\end_inset

) that the derivatives such as 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{,q_{A}}(z)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{,q_{A}}(z)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{,q_{F}}(z)$
\end_inset

, etc., all diverge at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

 with the same asymptotic behavior, namely proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(z_{*}-z\right)^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

.
 We may express the inverse matrix as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{M}^{-1}(z) & =\frac{1}{\det\hat{M}(z)}\hat{\tilde{M}}(z),\\
\hat{\tilde{M}}(z) & \equiv\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{1}{\nu}I^{\frac{1}{\nu}-1}-\kappa_{II} & z\kappa_{FI}\\
z\kappa_{IF} & \frac{1}{\nu}F^{\frac{1}{\nu}-1}-\kappa_{FF}
\end{array}\right),\label{eq:cofactor matrix}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where we introduced the algebraic complement matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\tilde{M}}\equiv\hat{M}^{-1}\det\hat{M}$
\end_inset

, which remains well-defined at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 It then follows from Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FqA eq 1"

\end_inset

) that the asymptotic behavior of the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{,q_{A}}(z)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{,q_{A}}(z)$
\end_inset

 near 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left[\begin{array}{c}
F_{,q_{A}}\\
I_{,q_{A}}
\end{array}\right] & \approx\frac{1}{c_{1}\sqrt{z_{*}-z}}\hat{\tilde{M}}(z_{*})\left[\begin{array}{c}
z_{*}\kappa_{FA}\\
0
\end{array}\right]\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{1}{c_{1}\sqrt{z_{*}-z}}\left[\begin{array}{c}
\left(\frac{1}{\nu}I^{\frac{1}{\nu}-1}-\kappa_{II}\right)z_{*}\kappa_{FA}\\
z_{*}^{2}\kappa_{IF}\kappa_{FA}
\end{array}\right].
\end{align}

\end_inset

Similarly, using Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FqF eq 1"

\end_inset

) we find near 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left[\begin{array}{c}
F_{,q_{F}}\\
I_{,q_{F}}
\end{array}\right] & \approx\frac{1}{c_{1}\sqrt{z_{*}-z}}\hat{\tilde{M}}(z_{*})\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
z_{*}\kappa_{IF}F
\end{array}\right]\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{1}{c_{1}\sqrt{z_{*}-z}}\left[\begin{array}{c}
z_{*}^{2}\kappa_{FI}\kappa_{IF}F\\
\left(\frac{1}{\nu}F^{\frac{1}{\nu}-1}-\kappa_{FF}\right)z_{*}\kappa_{IF}F
\end{array}\right].
\end{align}

\end_inset

 Using Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:large-n derivative"

\end_inset

) and noticing that all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dependent factors are the same in 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{z}^{n}F_{,q_{A}}$
\end_inset

 and other such derivatives, we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\left.\frac{\partial_{z}^{n}F_{,q_{A}}}{\partial_{z}^{n}F_{,q_{F}}}\right|_{z=0} & =F^{\frac{1}{\nu}}\frac{\left(\frac{1}{\nu}I_{*}^{\frac{1}{\nu}-1}-\kappa_{II}\right)\kappa_{FA}}{z_{*}\kappa_{FI}\kappa_{IF}F_{*}},\\
\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\left.\frac{\partial_{z}^{n}I_{,q_{A}}}{\partial_{z}^{n}I_{,q_{F}}}\right|_{z=0} & =\frac{z_{*}\kappa_{FA}}{\left(\frac{1}{\nu}F_{*}^{\frac{1}{\nu}-1}-\kappa_{FF}\right)F_{*}}.
\end{align}

\end_inset

It is important that the two limits above are equal; this is so because
 the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\hat{M}(z_{*})=0$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\det\hat{M}=\left[\frac{F_{*}^{\frac{1}{\nu}-1}}{\nu}-\kappa_{FF}\right]\negmedspace\left[\frac{I_{*}^{\frac{1}{\nu}-1}}{\nu}-\kappa_{II}\right]-z_{*}^{2}\kappa_{FI}\kappa_{IF}=0,\label{eq:det M equ 0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where we denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}\equiv F(z_{*})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{*}\equiv I(z_{*})$
\end_inset

 for brevity.
 It follows that the ratio of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-bubbles to 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

-bubbles is independent of whether the initial bubble is of type 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 or of type 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, the RV-regulated ratio of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

-bubbles to 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

-bubbles is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{p(A)}{p(F)}=\frac{z_{*}\kappa_{FA}}{\left(\frac{1}{\nu}F_{*}^{\frac{1}{\nu}-1}-\kappa_{FF}\right)F_{*}}\label{eq:AF ratio}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

independently of the initial bubble type.
 Below (Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Uniqueness-of-the"

\end_inset

) the independence of initial conditions will be rigorously proved for a
 general landscape using mathematical techniques of the theory of nonnegative
 matrices.
 Presently we have shown this independence using explicit formulas available
 for the toy landscape under consideration.
 
\end_layout

