\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It remains to justify the statement of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:det M sing 1"

\end_inset

).
 Below in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Uniqueness-of-the"

\end_inset

 I will demonstrate that the property
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:det M sing 1"

\end_inset

) holds for a general landscape.
 Here only a simple argument is presented to illustrate this property for
 Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:F equ 2 s"

\end_inset

)–(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:I equ 2 s"

\end_inset

).
 Using those equations, we can express 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{*}$
\end_inset

 through 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}$
\end_inset

 and derive a closed algebraic equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{*}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{*}=z^{\nu}\left[\kappa_{FA}+\kappa_{FI}z^{\nu}\left(\kappa_{IB}+\kappa_{IF}F_{*}\right)^{\nu}\right]^{\nu}\equiv f(z;F_{*}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The solution 
\begin_inset Formula $F(z)$
\end_inset

 is given by the intersection of the line 
\begin_inset Formula $y=F$
\end_inset

 and the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f(z;F)$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $y-F$
\end_inset

 plane.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z;F)$
\end_inset

 is convex in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $F>0,z>0$
\end_inset

; hence, there will be a value 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

 for which the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z_{*};F)$
\end_inset

 is tangent to the line 
\begin_inset Formula $y=F$
\end_inset

, 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $f_{,F}(z_{*};F_{*})=1$
\end_inset

.
