\begin_layout Standard
Let us now use the same techniques to compute the relative abundance of
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Boltzmann brain
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 observers to ordinary observers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We need to introduce an appropriate set of generating functions.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Boltzmann brains
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 can be created with a fixed probability per unit 4-volume, unlike ordinary
 observers who can appear only within a narrow interval of time after creation
 of a given bubble.
 Let us therefore compare the total number of bubbles 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{j}$
\end_inset

 with the total number of 4-volumes 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{j}^{-4}$
\end_inset

 in bubbles of type 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To be specific, let us fix 
\begin_inset Formula $j=F$
\end_inset

 (no Boltzmann brains can be expected in a terminal vacuum).
 Consider the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p(n_{\text{tot}},n_{F},N_{F};k)$
\end_inset

 of having a finite total number 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{tot}}$
\end_inset

 of bubbles of which 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{F}$
\end_inset

 are of type 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{F}$
\end_inset

 is the total number of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-regions of type 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, if one starts from a single initial 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region of type 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $k=F,I$
\end_inset

).
 The number of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Boltzmann brains
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in bubbles of type 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{F}$
\end_inset

 with a small proportionality constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{F}^{BB}$
\end_inset

, which we will include at the end of the calculation.
 A generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 for the probability distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 can be defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
g(z,q,r;k) & \equiv\negmedspace\sum_{n,n_{F},N_{F}\geq0}\negmedspace z^{n}q^{n_{F}}r^{N_{F}}p(n,n_{F},N_{F};k)\nonumber \\
 & \equiv\left\langle z^{n}q^{n_{F}}r^{N_{F}}\right\rangle _{n<\infty;k}.\label{eq:g FABI def BB}
\end{align}

\end_inset

For the initial bubble types 
\begin_inset Formula $k=F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k=I$
\end_inset

, let us denote for brevity 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F(z,q,r)\equiv g(z,q,r;F),\quad I(z,q,r)\equiv g(z,q,r;I).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The generating functions 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 satisfy the following system of equations, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F^{\frac{1}{\nu}} & =z\kappa_{FA}+z\kappa_{FI}I+r\kappa_{FF}F,\label{eq:F equ 1 BB}\\
I^{\frac{1}{\nu}} & =z\kappa_{IB}+zrq\kappa_{IF}F+\kappa_{II}I.\label{eq:I equ 1 BB}
\end{align}

\end_inset

These equations differ from the analogous Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:F equ 1"

\end_inset

)–(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:I equ 1"

\end_inset

) in that the generating parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 appears when a 
\emph on
new
\emph default
 
\emph on
bubble
\emph default
 of type 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is created, while the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 appears every time a new 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

-region of type 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is created, which can happen via Hubble expansion of old 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

-bubbles as well as through nucleation of new 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

-bubbles.
 
