) is more straightforwardly analyzed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As before, we first obtain the equations for the derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{,q}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{,q}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{,r}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{,r}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $q=r=1$
\end_inset

 from Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:F equ 1 BB"

\end_inset

)–(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:I equ 1 BB"

\end_inset

).
 The derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{,q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{,q}$
\end_inset

 satisfy the same equations as before, namely Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
