\begin_layout Section
A general landscape
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:A-general-landscape"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the previous section we performed computations in a simple toy model
 of the landscape.
 Let us now consider a general landscape containing 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 vacua, labeled 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1$
\end_inset

, ..., 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 The dimensionless transition rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{j\rightarrow k}$
\end_inset

 between vacua 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 are considered known.
 The main task is to compute the RV-regulated ratio of abundances of bubbles
 of kinds 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 We will also compare the abundances of ordinary observers with that of
 Boltzmann brains.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bubble abundances
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Bubble-abundances-landscape"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is convenient to denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 the set of terminal bubble types and to relabel the vacua such that 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1$
\end_inset

, ..., 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{r}$
\end_inset

 are the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

recyclable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (nonterminal) vacua.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\left\{ N_{r}+1,...,N\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 We start by considering the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p(n,\left\{ n_{j}\right\} ;k)$
\end_inset

 of having 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{j}$
\end_inset

 bubbles of type 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, with total 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\sum_{j}n_{j}$
\end_inset

 bubbles of all types, to the future of an initial bubble of type 
\begin_inset Formula $k\not\in T$
\end_inset

.
 The generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z,\left\{ q_{j}\right\} ;k)$
\end_inset

 for this probability distribution can be defined by a straightforward generaliz
ation of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g FABI def"

\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(z,\left\{ q_{l}\right\} ;k)\equiv\sum_{n,\left\{ n_{l}\right\} \geq0}p(n,\left\{ n_{l}\right\} ;k)z^{n}\prod_{j}q_{j}^{n_{j}}.\label{eq:g general def}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is the generating parameter for 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

 are the generating parameters for 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 The generating function can be written symbolically as the average
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(z,\left\{ q_{l}\right\} ;k)\equiv\left\langle z^{n}q_{1}^{n_{1}}...q_{N}^{n_{N}}\right\rangle _{n<\infty;k},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $(n<\infty)$
\end_inset

 indicates that only the events with a finite total number of bubbles contribute
 to the statistical average.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For terminal bubble types 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in T$
\end_inset

, the definition
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g general def"

\end_inset

) yields 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z,\left\{ q_{j}\right\} ;k)=1$
\end_inset

 since there are no further bubbles to the future of terminal bubbles, thus
 
\begin_inset Formula $n=n_{j}=0$
\end_inset

 with probability 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z,\left\{ q_{j}\right\} ;k)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,...,N_{r}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the system of 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{r}$
\end_inset

 nonlinear equations 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
g^{\frac{1}{\nu}}(z,\left\{ q_{j}\right\} ;k) & =\sum_{i\not\in T,i\neq k}zq_{i}\kappa_{k\rightarrow i}g(z,\left\{ q_{j}\right\} ;i)\nonumber \\
 & \quad+\sum_{i\in T}zq_{i}\kappa_{k\rightarrow i}+\kappa_{k\rightarrow k}g(z,\left\{ q_{j}\right\} ;k),\label{eq:g general equ}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu\equiv e^{3}$
\end_inset

 as before, and the quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{k\rightarrow k}$
\end_inset

 defined by Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:kappa jj def"

\end_inset

).
 A derivation of Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g general equ"

\end_inset

) will be given below in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Derivation-of-Eq."

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution of Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g general equ"

\end_inset

) can be visualized as 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{r}$
\end_inset

 analytic functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z,\left\{ q_{j}\right\} ;k)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,...,N_{r}$
\end_inset

, of the free parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,...,N$
\end_inset

).
 Arguments similar to those of Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:A-toy-landscape"

\end_inset

 show that the physically significant solution of Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g general equ"

\end_inset

) is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

main branch
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that has the following asymptotic form at 
\begin_inset Formula $z\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g(z;k)=z^{\nu}\left[\sum_{i\in T}q_{i}\kappa_{k\rightarrow i}\right]^{\nu}+O(z^{2\nu-1})\label{eq:main branch landscape}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

(see also the argument at the end of Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Derivation-of-Eq."

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once the generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z,\left\{ q_{j}\right\} ;k)$
\end_inset

 is determined, the RV measure gives the ratio of the mean number of bubbles
 of type 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 to that of type 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{p(j)}{p(k)}=\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\left.\frac{\partial_{z}^{n}\partial_{q_{j}}g(z,\left\{ q_{i}\right\} ;i')}{\partial_{z}^{n}\partial_{q_{k}}g(z,\left\{ q_{i}\right\} ;i')}\right|_{z=0,\left\{ q_{i}\right\} =1},\label{eq:limit i j general}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where, for clarity, we wrote explicitly the type 
\begin_inset Formula $i'$
\end_inset

 of the initial bubble.
 We will now use the methods developed in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Bubble-abundance"

\end_inset

 to reduce Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:limit i j general"

\end_inset

) to an expression that does not contain limits and so can be analyzed more
 easily.
 It will then become evident that the limit
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:limit i j general"

\end_inset

) is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $i'$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a fixed bubble type 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, we first consider the derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{q_{j}}g(z,\left\{ q_{i}\right\} ;k)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,...,N_{r}$
\end_inset

, evaluated at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ q_{i}\right\} =1$
\end_inset

.
 Let us denote these 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{r}$
\end_inset

 derivatives by 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{j}(z;k)$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h_{j}(z;k)\equiv\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial q_{j}}\right|_{q_{i}=1}g(z,\left\{ q_{i}\right\} ;k),\quad k=1,...,N_{r}.\label{eq:hjzk def}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

These quantities are conveniently represented by an 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{r}$
\end_inset

-dimensional vector, which we will denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|h_{j}(z)\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 using the Dirac notation (although no connection to quantum mechanics is
 present here).
 This vector satisfies an inhomogeneous linear equation that follows straightfor
wardly by taking the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{q_{j}}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ q_{i}\right\} =1$
\end_inset

 of Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g general equ"

\end_inset

).
 That equation can be written in the matrix form as follows, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sum_{i=1}^{N}M_{ki}(z)h_{j}(z;i) & =z\kappa_{k\rightarrow j}g(z;j),\quad k\neq j,\label{eq:linear gen 0}\\
\sum_{i=1}^{N}M_{ki}(z)g_{,q_{j}}(z;i) & =0,\quad k=j,\label{eq:linear gen 1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where we denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;j)\equiv g(z;\left\{ q_{i}\right\} =1;j)$
\end_inset

 the solution of Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g general equ"

\end_inset

) at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ q_{i}\right\} =1$
\end_inset

, written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
g^{\frac{1}{\nu}}(z;k) & =z\negmedspace\sum_{i\not\in T,i\neq k}\negmedspace\kappa_{k\rightarrow i}g(z;i)\nonumber \\
 & \quad+z\sum_{i\in T}\kappa_{k\rightarrow i}+\kappa_{k\rightarrow k}g(z;k),\label{eq:g equ for q1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

while the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{ki}(z)$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{M}(z)\equiv M_{ki}(z)=\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{\nu}g^{\frac{1}{\nu}-1}(z;k)-\kappa_{k\rightarrow k}, & k=i;\\
-z\kappa_{k\rightarrow i}, & k\neq i.
\end{cases}\label{eq:matrix M}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For convenience we rewrite Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linear gen 0"

\end_inset

)–(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linear gen 1"

\end_inset

) in a more concise form,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{M}(z)\left|h_{j}(z)\right\rangle =\left|Q_{j}(z)\right\rangle ,\label{eq:Mh Q}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|Q_{j}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is the vector with the components 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|Q_{j}\right\rangle _{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,...,N_{r}$
\end_inset

  given by the right-hand sides of Eqs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linear gen 0"

\end_inset

)–(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linear gen 1"

\end_inset

),
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|Q_{j}(z)\right\rangle _{i}\equiv z\kappa_{i\rightarrow j}g(z;j)\left[1-\delta_{ij}\right].\label{eq:Qj def}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The solution of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Mh Q"

\end_inset

) is found symbolically as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|h_{j}(z)\right\rangle =\hat{M}^{-1}(z)\left|Q_{j}(z)\right\rangle ,\label{eq:h sol M Q}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

provided that the inverse matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}^{-1}(z)$
\end_inset

 exists.
 Of course, it is impractical to obtain the inverse matrix explicitly; but
 we will never need to do that.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next task is to determine 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 for which the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}(z)$
\end_inset

 remains nondegenerate, 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\hat{M}(z)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 It will be shown in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Uniqueness-of-the"

\end_inset

 that there exists an eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}(z)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}(z)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}(z_{*})=0$
\end_inset

 at some real 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}>0$
\end_inset

, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}(z)>0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $z<z_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, the (left and right) eigenvectors corresponding to the eigenvalue
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}(z)$
\end_inset

 are always nondegenerate and can be chosen with all positive components.
 At the same time, all the other eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}(z)$
\end_inset

 remain nonzero for all 
\begin_inset Formula $z\leq z_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 It will also be shown (see Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Asymptotic-behavior-of-lambda"

\end_inset

) that the following asymptotic expansion holds near 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda_{0}(z)=c_{1}\sqrt{z_{*}-z}+O(z_{*}-z),\quad c_{1}>0.\label{eq:lambda0 asympt}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

One can see from the small-
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 asymptotics
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:main branch landscape"

\end_inset

) and from Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:matrix M"

\end_inset

) that, for small enough 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}(z)$
\end_inset

 contains very large positive numbers on the diagonal and very small negative
 numbers off the diagonal.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\hat{M}(z)>0$
\end_inset

 for all sufficiently small 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 Since the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}(z)$
\end_inset

 remain nonzero except for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}(z)$
\end_inset

 that first vanishes at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

, we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\hat{M}(z)$
\end_inset

 remains positive for all 
\begin_inset Formula $0<z<z_{*}$
\end_inset

, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

 is the smallest positive value of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\hat{M}(z)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we restrict our attention to 
\begin_inset Formula $0<z<z_{*}$
\end_inset

, for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\hat{M}(z)>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}^{-1}(z)$
\end_inset

 exists.
 We need to analyze the behavior of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 near 
\begin_inset Formula $z\approx z_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 We treat 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}(z)$
\end_inset

 as an operator in 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{r}$
\end_inset

-dimensional real space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}$
\end_inset

 is not symmetric and may not be diagonalizable.
 Instead of diagonalizing 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}(z)$
\end_inset

, we split the space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 into the 1-dimensional subspace corresponding to the smallest eigenvalue
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}(z)$
\end_inset

, and into the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(N_{r}-1\right)$
\end_inset

-dimensional complement subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 We know that the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}(z)$
\end_inset

 is nondegenerate.
 Thus, we may symbolically write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{M}(z)=\lambda_{0}(z)\left|v^{0}(z)\right\rangle \left\langle u^{0}(z)\right|+\hat{M}_{1}(z),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v^{0}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle u^{0}\right|$
\end_inset

 are the right and the left eigenvectors corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}(z)$
\end_inset

, normalized such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle u^{0}|v^{0}\right\rangle =1,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and it is implied that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}_{1}(z)$
\end_inset

 vanishes on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v^{0}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle u^{0}\right|$
\end_inset

 but is nonsingular on the complement space 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{M}\left|v^{0}\right\rangle  & =\lambda_{0}\left|v_{0}\right\rangle ,\quad\left\langle u^{0}\right|\hat{M}=\lambda_{0}\left\langle u^{0}\right|,\\
\hat{M}_{1}\left|v^{0}\right\rangle  & =0,\quad\left\langle u^{0}\right|\hat{M}_{1}=0.
\end{align}

\end_inset

There exists a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}_{1(V_{1})}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 that acts as the inverse to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}_{1}$
\end_inset

 when restricted to the subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}$
\end_inset

 and again vanishes on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v^{0}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle u^{0}\right|$
\end_inset

.
 Using that matrix, we may write the inverse matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 explicitly as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{M}^{-1}(z)=\frac{1}{\lambda_{0}(z)}\left|v^{0}(z)\right\rangle \left\langle u^{0}(z)\right|+\hat{M}_{1(V_{1})}^{-1}(z).\label{eq:M inverse}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Hence, the solution
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:h sol M Q"

\end_inset

) can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|h_{j}(z)\right\rangle =\frac{\left\langle u^{0}|Q_{j}\right\rangle }{\lambda_{0}(z)}\left|v^{0}\right\rangle +\hat{M}_{1(V_{1})}^{-1}\left|Q_{j}\right\rangle .\label{eq:hj lambda0 ans}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now it is clear from Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lambda0 asympt"

\end_inset

) that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|h_{j}(z)\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 diverges at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\propto\left(z_{*}-z\right)^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

.
 It also follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|h_{j}(z)\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 does not diverge at any smaller real 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}(z)$
\end_inset

 cannot vanish at some 
\emph on
complex
\emph default
 value of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 that is closer to 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 than 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}(z_{*}^{\prime})=0$
\end_inset

 with a complex-valued 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, then a derivative of the generating function, such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{z}g(z;j)$
\end_inset

, would diverge at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 Using the definition
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g general def"

\end_inset

) of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}=1$
\end_inset

, we find that the following sum diverges,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{\partial g(z;j)}{\partial z}\right|_{z=z_{*}^{\prime}}=\sum_{n\geq1}\left(z_{*}^{\prime}\right)^{n-1}np(n;j)=\infty.\label{eq:series for dgdz}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The sum of absolute values is not smaller than the above, and hence also
 diverges:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{\partial g(z;j)}{\partial z}\right|_{z=\left|z_{*}^{\prime}\right|}=\sum_{n\geq1}\left|z_{*}^{\prime}\right|^{n-1}np(n;j)=\infty.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{z}g$
\end_inset

 has also a singularity at a 
\emph on
real
\emph default
 value 
\begin_inset Formula $z=\left|z_{*}^{\prime}\right|$
\end_inset

.
 As we have shown, 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

 is the smallest such real-valued singularity point; hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|z_{*}^{\prime}\right|\geq z_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}$
\end_inset

 is equal to the radius of convergence of the series
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:series for dgdz"

\end_inset

), which is a Taylor series for the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{z}g$
\end_inset

.
 There remains the possibility that a singularity 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 is located directly on the circle of convergence, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|z_{*}^{\prime}\right|=z_{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}^{\prime}=z_{*}e^{\text{i}\phi}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\phi<2\pi$
\end_inset

.
 This possibility can be excluded using the following argument.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{z}g$
\end_inset

 can have only finitely many singularities on the circle 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|z\right|=z_{*}$
\end_inset

; infinitely many singularities on the circle would indicate an accumulation
 point which would be an essential singularity, 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

not a branch point.
 However, by construction 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;j)$
\end_inset

 is an algebraic function of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 that cannot have singularities other than branch points.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;j)$
\end_inset

 is regular at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, all branch points of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 must be of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(z-z_{*}^{\prime}\right)^{s}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $s>0$
\end_inset

.
 Using the explicit formula
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:large-n derivative"

\end_inset

) for the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-th derivative of an analytic function with a branch cut singularity of
 the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(z-z_{*}^{\prime}\right)^{s}$
\end_inset

, we find that the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $np(n;j)$
\end_inset

 of the Taylor series
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:series for dgdz"

\end_inset

) decay at large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 asymptotically as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
np(n;j) & =\frac{1}{n!}\partial_{z}^{n}\partial_{z}g\propto\frac{\Gamma(n+1-s)}{\Gamma(n+1)}\left(z_{*}^{\prime}\right)^{-n}\left(1+O(n^{-1})\right)\nonumber \\
 & \propto n^{-s}\left(z_{*}^{\prime}\right)^{-n}\left(1+O(n^{-1})\right).\label{eq:sing contrib}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 has a finite number of singularities 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}^{\prime}=z_{*}e^{\text{i}\phi}$
\end_inset

 on the circle 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|z\right|=z_{*}$
\end_inset

, and each singularity gives a contribution of the form
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:sing contrib"

\end_inset

).
 Hence, we may estimate (for sufficiently large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, say for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq n_{0}$
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
np(n;j)=c_{0}n^{-s}z_{*}^{-n}\left(1+O(n^{-1})\right),\quad c_{0}>0.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Then the partial sum for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq n_{0}$
\end_inset

 of the series
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:series for dgdz"

\end_inset

) is estimated by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sum_{n\geq n_{0}}\left(z_{*}^{\prime}\right)^{n-1}np(n;j) & \approx\sum_{n\geq n_{0}}\left(z_{*}^{\prime}\right)^{n-1}c_{0}n^{-s}z_{*}^{-n}\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{c_{0}}{z_{*}}\sum_{n\geq n_{0}}n^{-s}e^{\text{i}n\phi}.
\end{align}

\end_inset

The latter series converges for 
\begin_inset Formula $s>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\phi<2\pi$
\end_inset

.
 (The neglected terms of order 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{-1-s}$
\end_inset

 build an absolutely convergent series and hence introduce an arbitrarily
 small error into the estimate.) Therefore, the series
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:series for dgdz"

\end_inset

) also converges at 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}^{\prime}\neq z_{*}$
\end_inset

, contradicting the assumption that other singularities exist on the circle
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|z\right|=z_{*}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We conclude from these arguments that the singularity of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;j)$
\end_inset

 nearest to 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 in the complex 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 plane is indeed at a real value 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{*}$
\end_inset

, and all other singular points 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{*}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 satisfy the strict inequality 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|z_{*}^{\prime}\right|>z_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 The same statement about the locations of singularities holds for the generatin
g functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z,\left\{ q_{i}\right\} ;j)$
\end_inset

 and hence for their derivatives such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|h_{j}(z)\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

