\begin_layout Standard
Now we would like to estimate the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 for which the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}(z)$
\end_inset

 first becomes degenerate.
 We can use a general theorem for estimating the eigenvalues of a matrix
 (Gershgorin's theorem, see
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lancaster:1969:ToM"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, chapter 7).
 For each of the diagonal elements 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{kk}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,...,N_{r}$
\end_inset

 one needs to draw a circle in the complex 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 plane, centered at the diagonal element 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{kk}$
\end_inset

 with radius 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{k}\equiv\sum_{i\neq k}\left|M_{ki}\right|.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Thus one obtains 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{r}$
\end_inset

 circles 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|\lambda-M_{kk}\right|\leq\rho_{k},\quad k=1,...,N_{r},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 called the Gershgorin circles.
 The Gershgorin theorem says that all the eigenvalues of a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{jk}$
\end_inset

 are located within the union of these circles.
 An elementary proof is as follows.
 An eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 can be normalized such that its component of largest absolute value is
 equal to 1.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}=1$
\end_inset

 be this component (renumbering the components if necessary), then it is
 easy to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is within a circle with center 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{11}$
\end_inset

 and radius 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Namely, we start from the eigenvalue equation, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i\neq1}M_{1i}v_{i}+M_{11}v_{1}=\lambda v_{1},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and use the properties 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v_{i}\right|\leq1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq1$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|\lambda-M_{11}\right|=\left|\sum_{i\neq1}M_{1i}v_{i}\right|\leq\sum_{i\neq1}\left|M_{1i}\right|=\rho_{1}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Applying the theorem to the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}(z)$
\end_inset

 at small 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 such that Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:main branch landscape"

\end_inset

) is a good approximation for the generating function 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;j)$
\end_inset

, we find that the Gershgorin circles are centered at large positive values
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{kk}=\frac{1}{\nu}g^{\frac{1}{\nu}-1}(z;k)-\kappa_{k\rightarrow k}\approx\frac{1}{\nu}\frac{1}{\left(z\kappa_{k\rightarrow T}\right)^{\nu-1}}\gg1,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

while the radii of the circles are small, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{k}=z\sum_{i\neq k,i\not\in T}\kappa_{k\rightarrow i}\ll1.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Hence, for small 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 none of the circles can contain 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

, so the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}(z)$
\end_inset

 is nondegenerate.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 increases, the radii 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{k}$
\end_inset

 increase while the centers 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{kk}$
\end_inset

 move monotonically towards zero.
 The circle closest to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

 is the one with the center closest to zero and the largest radius.
 This circle is labeled by 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 with largest rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{k\rightarrow T}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{k\rightarrow i}$
\end_inset

.
 This value of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the high-energy vacua in the landscape, for which tunneling
 to any other vacua is much easier than for low-energy vacua.
 Therefore the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda(z_{*})=0$
\end_inset

 will be located inside the Gershgorin circle(s) centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{kk}(z_{*})$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 corresponding to high-energy vacua.
 The Gershgorin circle to which the eigenvalue belongs indicates the largest
 component of the eigenvector.
 Hence, one expects that the eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle u^{0}(z_{*})\right|$
\end_inset

 has the largest values of its components 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{k}^{0}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the high-energy vacua 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 The Gershgorin theorem requires that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}(z_{*})=0$
\end_inset

 be inside the circle centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{kk}(z_{*})$
\end_inset

 with radius 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{k}(z_{*})$
\end_inset

, 
\emph on
i.e.
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{kk}(z_{*})=\frac{1}{\nu}g^{\frac{1}{\nu}-1}(z_{*};k)-\kappa_{k\rightarrow k}\leq z_{*}\sum_{i\neq k,i\not\in T}\kappa_{k\rightarrow i}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Disregarding the terms 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{k\rightarrow k}$
\end_inset

, which are small in comparison with the remaining terms, and using Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:g equ for q1"

\end_inset

) for 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z_{*};k)$
\end_inset

 we obtain the following condition,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
z_{*}^{\nu}\geq\frac{1}{\nu}\frac{\left[\kappa_{k\rightarrow T}+\sum_{i\neq k,i\not\in T}\kappa_{k\rightarrow i}g(z_{*};i)\right]^{1-\nu}}{\sum_{i\neq k,i\not\in T}\kappa_{k\rightarrow i}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Proceeding further requires at least an estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z_{*};i)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, which is so far not available.
\end_layout

