\begin_inset Formula $g(z;j)$
\end_inset

 can be viewed as a solution of a differential equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{z}g(z;j)=\left|\partial_{z}g\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 with continuous coefficients and everywhere positive right-hand side.
 The solution of such differential equations, if bounded, will exist for
 all 
\begin_inset Formula $z>0$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z;j)$
\end_inset

 existed only up to some 
\begin_inset Formula $z=z_{1}$
\end_inset

, we would have, by assumption, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}(z_{1})>0$
\end_inset

 and hence a finite value 
\begin_inset Formula $g(z_{1};j)>0$
\end_inset

 and a finite derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{z}g(z_{1};j)>0$
\end_inset

.
